<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrainCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0750 08-01 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0750,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crews Begin Clearing Tracks From Head-On Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf to UPDATE with investigation
centering on accident's time. SUBS 10th graf, `Investigators
were...', with 2 grafs to UPDATE with interviews held, time
investigation. Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Investigators examined...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTOONA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters put out a fire in a tanker car
Monday night and authorities allowed 2,000 evacuees to return home
for the first time since two freight trains crashed head-on and
derailed.
   Police Chief Britt Adair said the fire was extinguished about 5
p.m. and the residents of northeast Altoona were allowed back in
their homes about a half hour later.
   The two Iowa Interstate Railroad trains, one of which included
two tanker cars carrying as much as 20,000 gallons each of volatile
denatured alcohol, collided shortly before noon Saturday. Two
crewmen were killed and their bodies were recovered Monday after
the last fire was out.
   The chief investigator said Monday the probe was centering on
whether one of the trains was off schedule.
   Fire coming from one of the cars had burned out by Monday but
authorities waited to allow residents to return because of the
danger of explosion from the second tanker.
   Flames shot up to 20 feet over the weekend but had shrunk to
about 1{ feet by Monday morning.
   ``If it fireballed, it would kill anything within its path for a
quarter mile, with devastating effects up to a half mile, and the
capability of throwing shrapnel from the cars a mile and a half.
That's why we evacuated a mile and a half surrounding it,'' said
Adair. ``That's with one of them exploding, and we had two burning
at one time.''
   Bulldozers and cranes were picking through the debris and
clearing the tracks of the 86 derailed cars.
   ``It's a situation where one of the engines rode up over the
other one in a head-on collision _ went clear up in the air _ and
it just completely annihilated two engines,'' the police chief
said. ``There is metal and twisted debris and wheels thrown all
over the place.''
   He said workers had removed about 16 hopper cars by
mid-afternoon Monday and that the rail line could be open to
traffic by midnight if the two tankers could be removed without
problems.
   Investigators were trying to determine how the two trains came
to be on the same track. Edward Dobranetski, who heads the National
Transportation Safety Board investigating team, said the two
surviving crewmen and other rail workers were interviewed Monday.
   Dobranetski said his inquiry has not determined ``whether one
train left early or whether the other was running late.'' The
westbound train was to have cleared the track by 11:56 a.m., while
the eastbound train wasn't scheduled to leave Altoona until 12:01
p.m., he said.
   Investigators examined the controls of the wrecked eastbound
train and found nothing out of order, said Dobranetski. ``The
emergency brake was being applied,'' he added.
   The crash killed William Peers, 54, of Des Moines, and Larry
Buckingham Jr., 35, of Winterset, both longtime employees of the
railroad. Their bodies were located under the two derailed tankers,
but had not been recovered earlier because of the danger of
explosion.
   Rail officials said the eastbound Council Bluffs-Chicago train
was pulling 78 cars, while the westbound train was pulling eight
cars from Newton to Des Moines.
   The two employees on the eastbound train jumped to safety before
the trains collided. Both victims were on the westbound train.
   ``He had an obviously dangerous job. He left home thousands of
times and came back thousands of times,'' said Peers' son, Dan.
``This time, he didn't.''
   ``They all worry about something like this happening,'' said
Buckingham's widow, La Voy. ``But he was always more worried about
someone else getting hurt at the crossings in a car or truck.''
</TEXT>
