<HEAD>Heat Records Set or Tied in 23 Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of cities where high-temperature records were
broken or tied Monday, according to the National Weather Service:
   Alpena, Mich., 94, breaks 1975 record of 93; Chicago, 100,
breaks 1987 record of 97; Detroit, 97, breaks 1935 record of 96;
Dubuque, Iowa, 100, breaks 1894 record of 98; Eau Clair, Wis., 104,
breaks 1964 record of 100; Flint, Mich., 98, breaks 1955 record of
95; Green Bay, Wis., 93, ties 1975 record; Greer, S.C., 98, ties
1980 record; Jackson, Mich., 96, ties 1917 record;
   La Cross, Wis., 105, breaks 1964 record of 97; Lansing, Mich.,
100, breaks 1975 record of 97; Madison, Wis., 101, breaks 1987
record of 95; Mason City, Iowa, 98, breaks 1919 record of 97;
Milwaukee, 103, breaks 1894 record of 95; Minneapolis, 101, breaks
1964 record of 98;
   Muskegon, Mich., 92, ties 1975 record; Ottumwa, Iowa, 102, ties
1941 record; Peoria, Ill., 101, breaks 1987 record of 100;
Rockford, Ill., 101, breaks 1917 record of 100; Rochester, Minn.,
99, breaks 1955 record of 98; St. Cloud, Minn., 99, tied 1964
record; South Bend, Ind., 103, breaks 1944 record of 96; Waterloo,
Iowa, 101, breaks 1987 record of 99.
</TEXT>
