<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Nelson     08-01 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Nelson,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Drop Plan To Protest Nelson Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers in West Virginia and
three other states dropped plans Monday to picket a Willie Nelson
appearance after learning the country-and-western singer will give
a concert to benefit both police and American Indian causes.
   ``If everything goes as planned, we probably won't have any
demonstration,'' said Al Leavitt, president of the state Fraternal
Order of Police.
   Police nationwide have been critical of Nelson's appearance last
October at a benefit for Leonard Peltier, an American Indian
activist serving two life sentences for the 1975 slayings of two
FBI agents.
   Peltier's supporters are raising money to pay for an appeal.
   The West Virginia FOP made plans to protest at Nelson's Aug. 27
concert in Charleston after Rhode Island police said they would
picket the singer concerts last weekend in Warwick, R.I.
   About 800 officers from four states demonstrated at the Friday
concert but canceled their Saturday protest after Nelson agreed to
the new benefit concert.
</TEXT>
