<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0729 08-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0729,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Heat Hits Upper Midwest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd and 4th grafs, bgng `The National...', with 3 grafs
to UPDATE with late-afternoon temperatures, which increases the
number of cities posting or tying records to 23. Also CORRECTS that
old Dubuque record was set in 1894, sted 1849; and CORRECTS that
old record in South Bend, Ind., for entire month of August was 100,
set in 1947, sted 96, set in 1944. Picks up 5th graf, `Temperatures
were...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures in the upper 90s or above 100 degrees lingered
Monday across the middle Mississippi Valley, parts of the upper
Mississippi Valley and upper Great Lakes region.
   Temperatures of 100 degrees or above were reported as far north
as southern Minnesota and southern Wisconsin, where high humidity
was pushing heat index values up close to 120 degrees at some
locations.
   The National Weather Service said 23 cities reported record
highs for the date. Dubuque, Iowa, had 100 degrees, breaking the
record of 98 set in 1894. Temperatures in Eau Claire, Wis., reached
a record 104; and in La Crosse, Wis., it reached 105, smashing a
24-year-old record by 8 degrees.
   In Indiana, South Bend established an all-time record for the
month of August with a 103 reading, topping the old record of 100
set on Aug. 5 and 6, 1947. Milwaukee also had all-time hottest
August reading with 103.
   Chicago had its sixth day of the season with a reading at or
above 100, padding a record broken earlier in the season.
   Temperatures were generally in the upper 80s and lower 90s
elsewhere east of the Rockies. Clouds were keeping readings in the
70s and lower 80s in the southern high Plains, in the upper 60s to
lower 80s from northeastern Montana to the northern half of
Minnesota and in the upper 70s and lower 80s in New England.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from south-central
Texas through the lower Mississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic
Coast states. Daytime heating of a humid air mass over the nation's
southeast brought afternoon showers and thunderstorms. A weak
weather disturbance over the Gulf of Mexico was producing showers
and thunderstorms over the Florida Keys.
   Showers and thunderstorms were also developing along and ahead
of a warm front curving through the northern Plains and the upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Sunny and dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation.
   Rainfall totals for the six hour period ended at 2 p.m. EDT
included an inch at Sierra Vista, Ariz., and a third of an inch at
Key West, Fla.
   Showers and thunderstorms produced up to an inch and a half of
rain in central North Dakota Monday morning. Showers and
thunderstorms in south-central Texas produced an inch of rain at
Del Rio, with close to 3 inches reported west of Loma Alta.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 104 degrees at Elkhart, Ind. The
nation's low Monday morning was 38 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Tuesday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Great Lakes region to the northern Plains
and across the Rockies, with showers and thunderstorms in northern
Arizona, western Montana and Upper Michigan. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms were forecast for south-central Texas through the
Tennessee Valley and central Gulf Coast states to the southern
Atlantic Coast.
   High temperatures were to be in the 90s across much of the
nation east of the Rockies, with readings near 100 degrees in the
central Plains and the middle Mississippi Valley. Highs were
forecast in the 80s in New England and from the northern high
Plains to Upper Michigan, 80s and 90s in the West, with readings
above 100 degrees in the Southwest deserts. Highs in the 70s were
forecast from the northern Rockies across Washington and northern
Oregon.
</TEXT>
