<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignNotebook     08-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Notebook,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Seeing Benefits _ and Disadvantages _ of Campaign Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has drawn some large
crowds in the two campaign swings he's taken since leaving Atlanta
as the Democratic presidential nominee. Invariably, he has
attracted protesters too.
   At virtually every stop in his campaign travels, Dukakis has
been confronted by demonstrators, sometimes numbering no more than
a dozen, but always vocal. Most carry signs and chant slogans
objecting to the right of women to have abortions.
   Often mixed with them are signs supporting Republican George
Bush, and there are occasional signs attacking Dukakis' record in
Massachusetts, such as the one in Sturtevant, Wis., last week that
said: ``Michael Dukakis, the criminal's choice, go home.'' It
referred to the program, since modified, allowing prison furloughs
for some convicted murderers in Massachusetts.
   The presence of anti-abortion protesters recalls the campaign in
1984 of vice presidential nominee Geraldine Ferraro, who faced
similar demonstrations at many speeches. Dukakis campaign staffers,
many of whom are veterans of the Mondale-Ferraro effort, say they
and their candidate are not bothered or surprised by the protesters.
   ``We expect them at every event,'' said Jim Steinberg, Dukakis'
senior issues adviser who travels with the candidate.
   The largest gathering, numbering 100 or more, confronted Dukakis
as he went to church on Sunday a week ago in St. Louis. In
Secaucus, N.J., last week, the dozen or so protesters positioned
themselves so close behind the stage that their chants were picked
up by the public address system _ and Dukakis had to walk right by
them as he left.
   In Sturtevant a day later, a larger group chanted slogans
throughout his speech, and Dukakis appeared to have been put off
his stride by the distraction.
   Was he rattled?
   ``Rattled? I didn't feel rattled. Did I look rattled? I didn't
feel rattled. Did I look rattled? Terribly rattled?
   ``Let me tell you, If you went through the kind of governorship
I went through in the first four years as governor of
Massachusetts, that's a day at the beach,'' added Dukakis. He was
turned out of office after that turbulent first term, in 1978, then
regained it four years later.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis' Greek heritage and sometimes bland style prompted
humorist Mark Russell to pin the name ``Zorba the clerk'' on
Dukakis. Last week in Wisconsin, Dukakis found a phrase on a
supporter's placard that he seemed to like better.
   ``Zeus on the loose,'' it said, in reference to the supreme
deity of the ancient Greeks.
   Dukakis picked that one out of the crowd as he stood on the
platform beginning his speech. ``I don't know what that means,'' he
told the audience. But he said he would tell his wife Kitty about
it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Since leaving Atlanta, Dukakis has rarely failed to mention to
audiences that 25-year-old snow blower of his. It was first
displayed to the nation by cousin Olympia Dukakis, the actress, in
a campaign film aired as part of the Democratic National Convention.
   It has become, he said, a symbol of the efficient frugality he
embodies. Mentioning the snow blower sometimes seemed a bit out of
place with the setting as he campaigned in 90 degree and 100 degree
temperatures, such as inside the hot Dorton Arena in Raleigh, N.C.,
on Saturday. But he did _ and noted that he not only still has the
machine, he still has its owners manual.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It may not be at the top of most voters' lists of concerns in a
president, but journalists always want to know what a new president
has in mind for frequency of news conferences.
   When asked that question in local television interviews in
Springfield, Ill., Dukakis said, ``I would expect two, three, four
times a week I would be meeting with the press, taking questions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
