<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FatalCarCrashes     08-01 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Car Crashes,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Accidents Kill 11, Injure 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A pickup truck in the wrong lane collided Sunday with a van in a
flaming crash that left five people dead and six critically injured
in Dallas, and six were killed in Indiana when a car flew out of
control and crashed during a drag race, police said.
   Police in Marion, Ind., said they were searching for a second
car involved in the race about 5:50 p.m. on a one-way, two-lane
corridor.
   In Dallas, five passengers of the van were dead at the scene,
while the four other people in the van and both occupants of the
pickup truck were critically injured, police said.
   The pickup was westbound in the eastbound lane at the time of
the collision about 4:45 p.m., police said. The van was knocked
backward off the road, then burst into flames, but passersby got
four of the occupants out of the vehicle, officials said.
   The dead were identified as Martin Becerra, 26, of Dallas; his
daughter, Julia, no age available; Remundo Rodriguez and his wife,
Erma Rodriguez, no ages available; and their son, Hermando
Rodriguez, 10.
   Also in the van were Ovuula Becerra, 27; Jessica Becerra, 2;
Martin Becerra Jr., 1; and Erica Rodriguez, 7, police and hospital
officials said. The occupants of the pickup were identified as
driver Mario Hernandez, no age available, and Elias Carapia, 20, of
Dallas.
   Investigators believe the Chevrolet Nova that crashed in Marion
went out of control and struck a utility pole, became airborne and
hit a tree before landing, officers said.
   Two people in the car were thrown from the vehicle when it
struck the tree, and the car landed on top of them, officers said.
   Jack Morris of Kokomo, Ind., said he was working on a truck
parked on the street when the vehicle that crashed missed him by
about 3 feet.
   ``The white car came skidding down the street (and) hit the
stump on the right side of the road,'' said Morris. ``He took out
the pole, he hit the tree, spun around, and I saw people flying.''
   The ages and the identities of those killed and the status of
the one person injured were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
