<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Powell     08-01 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Powell,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Supreme Court Associate Justice Enjoying Busy Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although he cited age and declining health
when he retired from the U.S. Supreme Court one year ago, Lewis F.
Powell Jr. shows little sign of slowing, says one associate.
   ``His idea of retirement is to stop working at 4 o'clock on
Saturday afternoon,'' said U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige
Jr., a longtime friend.
   Powell, who was a Richmond lawyer when he was tapped for the
Supreme Court in 1972 by then-President Richard Nixon, has returned
to his hometown and now maintains a modest office in the same
building as Merhige.
   Powell, who also keeps office hours in Washington, has sat with
appellate panels on three occasions since his retirement, and has
taught at the University of Virginia. This spring, he delivered
commencement addresses at George Mason University and Washington &
Lee, his alma mater.
   The only sign marking Powell's office at the U.S. Courthouse is
a room number scratched above a door frame. And the interior of his
office contains no plaques, citations or personal photographs.
   ``People wonder why I have such a Spartan office. I love it,''
Powell said last week. ``Very few people find me over here, which I
regard as a plus.''
   Powell, who turns 81 this fall, said he has no regrets about
stepping down from the nation's highest court, even though he
admits missing the intellectual challenge and the close association
with other justices.
   ``When you reach my ancient age, family is far more important
than any of the less personal things that happen to one over a long
lifetime,'' he said.
   Powell and his wife, Josephine, have four children and seven
grandchildren. Powell also describes his health as ``not
vigorous.'' Since 1979, he has undergone several operations,
including removal of a cancerous prostate in 1985.
   In June, he was hospitalized for almost a week for treatment of
a blood infection. Although his cancer has been in remission,
Powell said his health prevents him and his wife of 52 years from
extensive travel.
   Powell also takes a modest view of his role on the court,
although he was often seen during the 1980s as the moderate justice
who kept the rest of the court from drifting too far in either
direction. And last year, he was described by The New York Times as
a more powerful influence on the law than President Reagan or Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist.
   ``If I got into a footnote, I'd be surprised,'' Powell said.
   After Powell retired last August, he avoided comment as Robert
H. Bork and Douglas H. Ginsburg failed to win Senate approval as
his successor. Eight months later, Anthony Kennedy finally won
approval.
   Powell refuses to pinpoint blame but strongly denounced the
delays in replacing him.
   ``The disappointment to me was that for the first time in many
years, the process was prolonged to the point where it was a
disservice to the Supreme Court itself,'' he said.
</TEXT>
