<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0749 08-01 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0749,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rapid City Fire Nearly Out, Fires Slow In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Rapid City fire controlled,
add Oregon to list of states. Picks up 3rd graf pvs. Inserts one
graf after 8th graf ``Elsewhere in...' with details. Subs last 2
grafs with 3 grafs to UPDATE Idaho fire and add detail on Oregon
fire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Yellowstone National Park officials re-opened areas of the park
Sunday that had been closed because of forest fires, and
firefighters used hand tools to choke the last embers of a
controlled fire that destroyed 15 homes at Rapid City, S.D.
   Crews battled at least four new blazes in two national forests
in Wyoming, a wilderness fire forced evacuation of a ranger station
in Montana, and firefighters also were at work in the forests of
Idaho, Oregon and Washington.
   Fire activity in Yellowstone declined Sunday, said Costa Dillon,
fire information officer. That allowed officials to re-open the
park's south entrance north of Jackson, Wyo., closed one week ago
by the 10,100-acre Shoshone fire and the 10,600-acre Red fire.
   Officials also re-opened the park's West Thumb area Sunday,
closed Saturday when firefighters started controlled burns to
remove fuels before the Shoshone fire, which jumped the road from
the southern entrance, could reach the area.
   A controlled burn on the eastern and northeastern edge of the
11,300-acre North Fork fire, which at one point was six miles from
the tourist complex at Old Faithful geyser, had worked as planned
and flames headed north away from the geyser Sunday, Dillon said.
   Firefighters completed a containment line around 30 percent of
the fire and hoped for full containment by Wednesday, he added.
Because the fire was caused by man rather than lightning,
firefighters will attempt to control it.
   The largest fire in the park, the 68,035-acre Clover Mist, did
not grow significantly during the weekend, Dillon said.
   Elsewhere in Wyoming, two new fires in the Bighorn National
Forest kept firefighters busy, and crews in the Targhee National
Forest fought two lightning-caused blazes. The largest had covered
1,260 acres on Medicine Mountain in the Big Horn.
   A timber fire that burned 3,840 acres in the Black Hills on the
western edge of Rapid City over six days was declared controlled
Sunday night, as was a 35-acre fire that broke out nearby Saturday.
A fire is considered controlled when it is reduced to smoldering
patches.
   Mary Sue Waxler, a fire information officer, said about 584
firefighters were at the fire Sunday morning, about half the number
there 24 hours earlier.
   The remaining firefighters worked from the fire line to the
center of the burned area with hand tools and other equipment,
Waxler said.
   ``Basically, they're doing things like extinguishing embers and
turning over logs to make sure that things are out,'' she said.
   The Rock Creek fire in the Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness Area of
southwestern Montana jumped fire lines and covered about 3,000
acres Sunday, said Jack Kendley, fire information officer at the
Inter-Agency Dispatch Center in Helena. Although it was in a
wilderness area, the fire was being fought because it was
man-caused. Late Saturday, smoke from the fire could be seen in
Helena, more than 100 miles away, he said.
   In northwestern Montana, 10 to 15 people were evacuated from a
remote ranger station in the Bob Marshall Wilderness Area when the
Gates fire spread to about 8,000 acres, Kendley said.
   ``That fire increased 2,000 to 3,000 acres in size'' on
Saturday, Kendley said. ``The buildings (at the station) have been
covered with fireproof tarps, a gravity-feed sprinkler system has
been installed on a nearby ridge and personnel and livestock have
been evacuated from the station.''
   Also in the Bob Marshall, the Canyon Creek blaze had grown to
15,000 acres Sunday, he said.
   In Idaho, ground crews cleared landing areas for helicopters
around the 5,000-acre Willis Gulch fire so weary firefighters can
be flown back and forth from the remote fire line in the Boise
National Forest. The heliports cut the walk for firefighters from
four miles to about a half mile.
   Containment was expected Monday evening, and by late Sunday a
containment line had been thrown around 90 percent of the fire's
10-mile perimeter, forest officials said.
   Firefighters in Washington continued work Sunday on the
3,600-acre Falls Creek fire along the crest of the Cascades, about
12 miles northeast of Mount Rainier National Park, and a smaller
burn in the Cascade foothills.
   A 75-acre fire broke out late Saturday in the Mount Hood
National Forest in Oregon and and a lightning storm sparked nearly
70 small fires in southern Oregon, forest spokeswomen said.
</TEXT>
