<HEAD>River Overflows, Leaving Two Dead, 12 Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy weekend rains sent a river over
its banks and triggered a mudslide that destroyed nearly 100 houses
in a coastal resort and left two people dead and 12 missing,
officials said.
   The Chichiriviche river overflowed after a downpour Saturday
night, causing a mudslide that covered several of the houses ``up
to their roofs,'' civilian Defense Director Freddy Paris told the
official news agency Venpres.
   ``There is mud up to five meters (yards) high. It is likely
there are more victims in there and we are working to find those
missing,'' he said Sunday.
   Paris said the houses belonged to people vacationing in the
Caribbean resort 25 miles north of Caracas near La Guaira port.
   The flooding was the worst since last September, when a mudslide
caused by a downpour in another coastal area killed hundreds of
vacationers.
