<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     08-01 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Says Higgins Won't Be Freed; Church Of England Sends Envoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insisting Lt. Col. William Higgins used
his United Nations post as a cover to spy for the United States, a
pro-Iranian extremist group rejected a U.N. appeal for the American
hostage's release.
   Abbas Mousawi, a senior leader of the Shiite Moslem Hezbollah,
or Party of God, said Sunday that the group considers the U.N.
resolution ``part of a plot against the Moslems and Mujahedeen
(holy warriors) of this area.''
   ``We consider the arrest of this agent by the sons of this
nation as part of its defense of its dignity and existence,''
Mousawi said at a rally in the southeastern town of Mashgara.
   Hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella group for Shiite
factions holding most of the 18 foreign hostages, including nine
Americans, in Lebanon.
   Mousawi's speech was the first Hezbollah reply to resolution
passed unanimously Friday by the 15-nation Security Council
condemning the U.S. Marine's abduction and pleading for his
immediate release.
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was chief of a 76-member observer
group attached to the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon when he was
abducted Feb. 17. The Vietnam veteran also served as an aide to
former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger.
   Hezbollah has publicly defended the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth, which claimed responsibility for Higgins'
abduction.
   ``Everyone knows that when Higgins was seized by the oppressed
in south Lebanon he wasn't on a humanitarian mission, but,
according to even the American press and President Reagan, he was
engaged in a spying mission on Hezbollah in south Lebanon,'' said
Mousawi.
   There is no record of Reagan making such a statement.
   ``So it is within our right to say that the presence of Higgins
under the Security Council umbrella in south Lebanon is part of a
war waged by this arrogant body and America, the great Satan,
against our oppressed people,'' Mousawi said.
   His oration drew thunderous chants of ``Death to the Great
Satan!'' and ``No to the Security Council!'' from thousands of
fist-shaking Shiite Moslem zealots attending the rally.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth has repeatedly
charged that Higgins was a spy for the CIA, but U.S. and U.N.
officials deny it.
   Also Sunday, a Church of England bishop said he visited Lebanon
last week to inquire into the fate of four missing Iranians in
hopes his efforts might hasten the release of Western hostages, who
include Anglican envoy Terry Waite.
   Christian militiamen kidnapped the Iranians in July 1982. There
have been reports that they were killed, and Iran has been seeking
word on them.
   After arriving in Britain on Sunday, The Rev. John Brown told
reporters he hoped his mission to Lebanon had ``made a contribution
towards the overall picture, which I hope will lead towards the
release of all the hostages.''
   Brown, Anglican bishop in Cyprus and the Persian Gulf region,
went at the request of his church's head, Archbishop of Canterbury
Robert Runcie.
   He said he spoke in Lebanon to leaders of the Maronite Church
and the Armenian church, who ``promised to make inquiries.
   ``It's very important to us when we are talking to the Iranians
... to show them that we are concerned about their missing people
as well as ours,'' Brown told reporters.
   Runcie aide John Lyttle said Brown was ``well guarded'' during
his visit and did not venture out of the Christian part of Lebanon.
   Waite disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, while seeking the release of
American hostages in Lebanon. The longest-held hostage is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press,
who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
