<HEAD>Preparations Made For Annapolis Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of the first scheduled
presidential debate in Maryland's capital city Sept. 14 say
preparation have been made for everyone there to be cool, calm and
connected.
   Massive portable air conditioning units will be used to cool the
huge Naval Academy field house where Democrat Michael Dukakis and
Republican George Bush are expected to face off.
   Lights and cameras will be powered with an ample supply of
electricity, thanks to a new power line just laid down in the murky
waters of the nearby Severn River.
   And the roughly 2,000 to 3,000 news media representatives
expected to cover the event will tell the world of the 90-minute
face-off overly newly installed telephone trunk lines.
