<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-01 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Military Uses Millions of Substandard Fasteners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional committee is charging that
millions of substandard bolts and nuts are being used in everything
from military equipment and weapons to the space shuttle and
commercial trucks.
   ``The millions and perhaps billions of substandard fasteners
used by our military and sensitive industries make it a wonder that
we haven't had a major catastrophe,'' said Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee and
its investigations subcommittee.
   The panel issued its report this weekend after a two-year
investigation that uncovered millions of substandard bolts, nuts,
and screws _ many of them imported from Japan.
   Dingell said the problem could have wide-ranging effects and,
along with 50 other House members, has introduced legislation to
try to correct the problem. The bill would require laboratory
testing and greater documentation of fasteners to make it more
difficult to substitute cheaper and less effective parts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Death Sentences, Executions Highest Since Court Restored Penalty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government counted nearly 2,000 prisoners
on death row last year and 25 of them were put to death, both
record highs since the Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment
in 1976.
   The 25 prisoners executed last year in eight states had spent an
average of seven years and two months waiting for the sentence to
be carried out, the Bureau of Justice Statistics said on Sunday.
   State courts sentenced nearly 300 people to death in 1987, while
the death sentences of 79 were vacated or commuted, the report
said. A total of 1,984 men and women were on death row in 34 states
as of Dec. 31.
   More than 60 percent of the death row prisoners were held in
states in the South, 18 percent in the West, 15 percent in the
Midwest and 5 percent in the Northeast. The study said more than 57
percent of the death row inmates were white and 41 percent were
black.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>West Germany Topped U.S. Exports Again in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany was the world's largest exporter
last year for the second year in a row and is continuing to
outdistance the United States this year, according to the
International Monetary Fund.
   West German exports amounted to $294 billion, compared with $250
billion for the United States and $231 billion for Japan in 1987,
the IMF said.
   West German exports, which first jumped ahead of U.S. exports in
1986, also ran ahead of U.S. exports for the first two months of
1988: $46.7 billion for West Germany compared with $45.9 billion
for the United States.
   The IMF figures, in an IMF publication released Friday, show
total trade increased 10 percent in 1986 and 18 percent in 1987.
   The fund reported that trade among the biggest countries
remained far out of balance in 1986 and 1987. The United States
imported much more than it exported, while the reverse was true for
Japan and West Germany.
   U.S. imports in 1987 were $424 billion, compared with $228
billion for West Germany, $158 billion for France, $154 billion for
Britain and $151 billion for Japan.
</TEXT>
