<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     08-01 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers: `We've Hit the Brick Wall'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks to end the 22-week scriptwriters strike
have ``hit a brick wall,'' according to the producers' top
negotiator who is urging strikers to cross picket lines and end the
industry's second-longest walkout.
   ``We will get our production on schedule any way we can,''
Nicholas Counter III, president the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers, said at a news conference Sunday. ``What
individual writers choose to do is up to them.''
   A union spokeswoman predicted that strikers would remain
steadfast.
   ``To encourage writers to come back to work is an unfortunate
retrenchment at a time when both sides should resume negotiation
and settle this dispute,'' said spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden.
   The negotiations deadlocked Saturday after an 11-hour session.
   ``We've simply gotten to the end of the road, and we've hit a
brick wall,'' Counter said of the 217-member alliance. ``We will
redouble our efforts to produce as many programs as possible.''
   The major unresolved issue is how much the writers should get
from sale of TV shows and movies abroad and from domestic TV reruns.
   The strike, which began March 7, has left the fall television
season in chaos and has led to financial hardship for many of the
Writers Guild of America's 9,000 members, as well as
entertainment-related industries.
   Counter said production companies belonging to the alliance
would welcome strike-breaking union members and likely would offer
financial protection against any union reprisal. Guild officials
have said writers who go back to work risk fines of up to 110
percent of their compensation from the producers and expulsion from
the union.
   About 50 guild members, meanwhile, singled out Walt Disney
Studios on Sunday by picketing movie theaters in Hollywood and
Westwood showing the hit Disney film ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.''
   The demonstrators blamed Disney for blocking a tentative
settlement with the alliance, and held signs and passed out fliers
saying ``Who framed the writers guild?'' and ``Mickey Mouse is
stealing from our kids.''
   Rhoden called the demonstrations ``public outrage pickets,'' and
said more would be planned this week here and in other parts of the
country.
   She called prospects of a fall TV season ``doubtful and
improbable. They may put a few shows on the air, but it will not be
a full schedule.''
   The strike is only a week short of the entertainment's
industry's longest _ a 23-week walkout by the guild in 1960. That
strike won writers payments for television reruns.
   Also Sunday, Counter and Earl Bush, chairman of the basic crafts
unions, issued a joint statement Sunday saying the alliance and
behind-the-scenes workers agreed to extend their contracts on a
day-to-day basis. Those contracts were to have expired at midnight.
   ``The parties will resume discussions on Wednesday ... with the
expectation of negotiating to conclusion,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
