<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HashHouseHarriers     08-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hash House Harriers,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hashing: A Running Game Played From Malaysia to Maine</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRYANT POND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pack of runners darted through the
woods, bushwhacked up and down thicket-choked slopes, dashed along
railroad tracks and abandoned roads, forded knee-deep streams and
slogged through thigh-high mud.
   They closed out the day with beer, a barbecue and good
fellowship.
   Born in the rubber plantations and jungles of east Asia in an
era when the sun never set on the British empire, the sport known
as hashing has made its way halfway around the world to Maine,
where one devotee is writing a book about it.
   Hashing, a non-competitive form of cross-country running that
traces its roots to the game of hare and hounds, is enjoyed by
roughly 50,000 participants in more than 700 clubs in 124 countries
from Andorra to Zimbabwe.
   ``It's a way to get a little exercise and a little
sociability,'' said freelance writer Alice Johnson of Hallowell,
founder of the Hallowell Hash House Harriers, one of about 80 clubs
in the United States.
   California leads with 16.
   For her research on her forthcoming book, Johnson was recently
in Bali, site of the 1988 Interhash, known as the biennial Olympics
of hashing, and in Malaysia for the the 50th anniversary
celebration of the founding of the original Hash House Harriers,
known affectionately as ``the mother hash.''
   The group was founded at a Kuala Lumpur club by British soldiers
and expatriate businessmen who ran through the jungle to work up a
thirst. It selected the name from the institutional quality of the
club's food.
   At a midsummer hash that began at her lakefront cottage here,
Johnson briefed newcomers on the rules. Runners designated as hares
set the course in advance, marking it with flour; they are the only
ones who know where it will lead.
   At various points, hares draw circles indicating checkpoints
from which several possible routes fan out in different directions.
All but one are false trails that end with a marker telling the
runner to return to the checkpoint and try again.
   The runner who finally discovers the right trail shouts ``I'm
on!'' or ``On-on!'' The hares who follow the pack to keep track of
stragglers sound a horn, and all run toward the next checkpoint to
restart the process.
   The search for the correct trail provides time for slower
runners to catch up with those up front.
   ``It takes away a lot of the ego trip involved with track and
other competitive racing,'' said Noel Mount, an Irish-born former
rugby player who was one of the two dozen Hallowell hashers to run
the nearly six-mile course.
   ``You get ahead, but then you take the wrong trail and that
brings you back with everyone else.''
   Johnson's husband, Wick, along with summer neighbors Oliver
Greeves and Andrew Engelman, reconnoitered the area the previous
evening and spent three hours that morning laying out the route and
marking it with 10 pounds of flour. In the tropics, hares use paper
rather than flour to leave their marks.
   Greeves, a resident of Hong Kong, introduced the Johnsons to
hashing two years ago. While on a visit to Hong Kong, Wick Johnson
was invited by Greeves to participate in an all-male hash. He
returned exhausted but enthusiastic, telling his wife, a
recreational runner, that this was a sport she would love.
   Upon her return home that summer, Alice Johnson rounded up a
group of friends and neighbors from Hallowell, just outside
Augusta, and organized the area's first hash.
   ``The trick is getting the right people at the beginning. It has
to be people who don't take themselves too seriously,'' she said.
``Most are runners, but it is definitely not a requirement. You
just have to be fit enough to run approximately six miles _ with
stops.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0442 08-01 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says He Won't Try To Force Latin Agreement on Nicaragua</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 4th graf pvs, bgng ``We're not, to
add Honduras criticism of joint statement; Edits 5th graf pvs for
transition; picks up 6th graf pvs, The official.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz says his
visit to Latin America this week is not intended to force leaders
there into a confrontation with Nicaragua over democratic reforms.
   Shultz's 10-day journey to nine countries begins today in
Guatemala, where he will meet with the foreign ministers of four
Central American countries in an attempt to come up with a common
strategy on the leftist Sandinista government.
   Shultz on Sunday said a statement which he said was drafted
mostly by the foreign ministers of Guatemala, El Salvador, Costa
Rica and Honduras is still open to discussion.
   ``We're not trying to ram anything down anyone's throat,'' he
said on the CBS-TV program, ``Face the Nation.'' ``Having drafted
it, they are not so sure they want to issue it.''
   Honduras, meanwhile, harshly criticized Guatemala and Costa Rica
for insisting that the joint communique on Nicaragua to be issued
following today's meeting be softened, calling their action
``incomprehensible and strange.''
   The Hondurans, in a statement issued to reporters Sunday night,
said the Guatemalans and Costa Ricans had made a number of changes
in the document that was first agreed to a month ago, including
many provisions aimed at Nicaragua.
   A senior Reagan administration official who briefed reporters on
Friday said it was unclear whether the Guatemala meeting will
result in a joint statement of principles designed to prod
Nicaragua into complying with its stated commitment to move toward
democratic reforms.
   The official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said a
consensus on a common policy toward Nicaragua has been difficult to
reach.
   The special U.S. envoy to Central America, Morris Busby, has
been consulting on that issue with officials from the four Central
American nations.
   In Managua, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega urged the four
Central American countries to reject any U.S. attempt to condemn or
isolate Nicaragua.
   Ortega told reporters Sunday he hoped ``the Central American
governments will respond with dignity and firmness and reject the
proposal of the United States.''
   He said the United States is ``trying to escalate the war ...
with consequences for all the Central American countries, not just
for Nicaragua.''
   A Guatemalan legislator, meanwhile, accused the State Department
of trying to pressure the countries into signing a virtual
``declaration of war'' against Nicaragua.
   The legislator, Edmund Mulet Lesiur, representing a political
party known as the Union of the National Center, said President
Vinicio Cerezo rejected a demand by Busby to abandon Guatemala's
policy of ``active neutrality'' by agreeing to the document.
   Mulet said Honduras and El Salvador had agreed to sign it, while
Guatemala and Costa Rica turned it down.
   The U.S. Embassy in Guatemala City issued a statement Sunday
categorically denying Mulet's statements, made in an interview with
a Guatemala City newspaper.
   ``The United States has not `pressured' Guatemala or any other
country. The United States has not asked Guatemala to abandon
`active neutrality,''' the embassy said.
   A fragile cease-fire remains in place in Nicaragua, but there
has been no progress on a final settlement between the Sandinistas
and the Contra rebels. The impasse has produced calls by
conservative members of Congress for a renewal of military aid to
the rebels,
   In public statements this past week, rebel leaders have
maintained the truce has helped the Sandinistas by enabling them to
strengthen their overall military position while the Contras have
been denied lethal aid from the United States.
   The administration has contended the Sandinistas also have
stepped up internal repression since the truce went into effect
four months ago.
   In a commentary this past week in The New York Times, Assistant
Secretary of State Elliott Abrams said the situation in Nicaragua
deteriorated after Congress rejected a Contra military aid request
in February.
   Much of Shultz's trip will be devoted to highlighting the
democratic trend in the hemisphere. All of the nations on his
itinerary have elected governments and all, with the exception of
Costa Rica, became democratic over the past nine years.
   After Guatemala, Shultz will travel to Argentina, Uruguay,
Brazil and Bolivia before a return trip, lasting 24 hours, to
Central America on Aug. 8 for talks in Costa Rica, El Salvador and
Honduras.
   The trip ends on Aug. 10 when Shultz will attend the inaugural
ceremony of Ecuadoran President-elect Rodrigo Borja. While in
Quito, Shultz also will confer with President Jaime Lucinchi of
Venezuela and President Virgilio Barco of Colombia.
</TEXT>
