<HEAD>Explosion Causes Army Barracks To Collapse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Scotland Yard saying at least one dead, suspect
device found in car, firefighters withdrawn from area. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion caused a two-story army barracks in
north London to collapse early Monday, killing at least one person
and injuring at least seven, Scotland Yard said.
   Part of the Inglis barracks, which houses members of the Women's
Royal Army Corps., caught fire, London Fire Brigade officials said.
   Press Association said an army disposal unit was inspecting a
``suspect device'' found in a car in a parking lot adjacent to the
barracks in the Mill Hill neighborhood.
   It said firefighters were withdrawn from the area.
   The cause of the explosion was not immediately known.
   London Broadcasting Corp. radio had reported that two people
died and 20 were trapped at the Inglis barracks in the Mill Hill
neighborhood.
   Press Association, the domestic British news agency, reported
one dead and eight injured in the explosion, which occurred about 7
a.m. (2 a.m. EDT).
   The Ministry of Defense said the barracks also is used as an
army postal and courier depot.
   London Ambulance said the injured were taken to two hospitals.
   ``One of the injured is in a critical state with back and leg
injuries,'' said an ambulance spokesman, speaking anonymously in
keeping with British custom.
   The barracks are located in Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
parliamentary constituency.
</TEXT>
