<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PolPot     08-01 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pol Pot,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Reportedly Refusing to Allow Pol Pot Leave The Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in Bejing are refusing to allow
former Cambodia ruler Pol Pot to leave China, where the leader of
the murderous Khmer Rouge regime is hospitalized for unspecified
treatment, a magazine reported.
   The August edition of the Chinese-language Cheng Ming magazine,
seen today, also said China will offer political asylum to Pol Pot.
   While Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia from 1975-78,
hundreds of thousands of people died in vast slave-labor camps and
execution chambers as the government attempted to turn the country
into a primitive agrarian society.
   Vietnamese forces drove the Khmer Rouge into the mountain
jungles of western Cambodia and installed the current Phnom Penh
government in early 1979.
   Pol Pot has not been seen by outsiders in recent years and has
been reported to suffer from various ailments that sent him for
treatment to Bangkok, Thailand, and Beijing.
   Cheng Ming, in a brief report about Pol Pot, said he was being
treated at an unidentified Beijing hospital.
   The China-watching magazine said China had reached a tacit
agreement with the United States to stop supplying military aid to
Pol Pot and not to allow him to return to power in Cambodia.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest member in a coalition of three
guerrilla groups opposed to Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia.
   Coalition leaders and the prime minister of the
Vietnam-installed Phnom Penh government met last week in Indonesia
at unprecedented peace talks.
   The possible role of the Khmer Rouge in any future government
was a major stumbling block.
   Vietnam says it plans to withdraw its troops from Cambodia by
1991.
   Pol Pot officially retired in September 1985 as commander in
chief of the Khmer Rouge army and was named director of the party's
Institute for National Defense. The move was widely seen as an
attempt by the Khmer Rouge to clean up its international image.
</TEXT>
