<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Italy-Mafia 1stLd-Writethru a0433 08-01 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Mafia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0433,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass Resignation Raises Questions About Italy's War on Mafia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CLARIFY that resigning magistrates comprised `anti-Mafia
pool' and ADD details on heroin network, SUB grafs 6-8, `Falcone,
48 ... crime trial.' Picks up 9th graf, `The so-called ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the nation's top Mafia investigator, Giovanni
Falcone symbolized a new generation of brave, activist judges
dedicated to ending the reign of organized crime in Sicily.
   Now, he and eight fellow investigating magistrates have
resigned, spurring questions about the depth of the government's
commitment to fighting the Mafia. All nine had played a prominent
role in Italy's largest Mafia trial.
   In stepping down with the others on Saturday, Falcone said he
wanted to be able to freely testify before a judicial panel looking
into the government's anti-Mafia effort. He also suggested there
was something profoundly wrong with the war on organized crime.
   Following reports that members of Italy's dominant political
party had in an unrelated case arranged payment of a ransom to
underworld figures, the resignations shocked Italians and prompted
criticism of the government.
   ``The judges and all the others that have risked their lives
fighting the Mafia have felt increasingly abandoned by the state,''
the newspaper Corriere della Sera said in a front-page editorial on
Sunday.
   Falcone, 48, and the other eight resigning investigators had
together comprised a special ``anti-Mafia pool,'' which was formed
after the 1983 assassination of the chief investigating magistrate
in Palermo, Sicily's capital.
   The team, led by Falcone, pushed Italian law to its limit,
examining bank records of alleged Mafiosi and ordering sweeping
arrests.
   It was the dapper, mustachioed Falcone who persuaded mob figure
Tommaso Buscetta to detail the structure of the Mafia and how it
shipped heroin from Sicily to the United States, a breakthrough
that led to the nation's huge organized crime trial.
   The so-called maxi-trial ended in December with convictions of
338 Mafiosi, including 19 reputed members of the Cosa Nostra's
leadership commission.
   Since the trial, however, the anti-Mafia pool has been stymied
by its new director, chaos in the police force and government
indifference, according to prominent Sicilian prosecutor Paolo
Borsellino.
   Borsellino's declarations to journalists two weeks ago prompted
President Francesco Cossiga to order investigations by the
ministries of Justice and Interior and the Superior Council of
Magistrates, which oversees judges.
   As the judges' body began hearings in Rome on Saturday, Falcone
and his colleagues submitted their resignations and asked for
transfers.
   ``That which I had feared could happen unfortunately happened,''
Falcone wrote. ``The investigations into the Mafia have been
obstructed and (the anti-Mafia pool) ... is now stalled.''
   Another investigator who resigned, Giuseppe Di Lello, charged:
``The inattention of the government is palpable in the
disorganization of the investigating offices.''
   Falcone did not elaborate on how or why the investigations may
have slowed. But he said his views on prosecuting the Mafia
``diverge radically'' from those of the chief investigating
magistrate, Antonino Meli.
   Meli was appointed in February over the objections of Falcone
and others, who said he had no experience in Mafia probes.
   Borsellino, a former member of the anti-Mafia pool, told
reporters that Meli had removed Falcone as chief of major
anti-Mafia cases.
   Meli also divided the anti-Mafia work load among all
investigators, regardless of whether they were specialists,
Borsellino said, reverting to the system followed before the pool
was created.
   ``There have been serious attempts by the office of
investigations and the prosecutor of the republic of Palermo to
definitively dismantle the anti-Mafia pool,'' he said.
   Meli responded: ``The pool has not been destroyed, as Borsellino
says, and if anything it has been enlarged with the addition of
other judges.''
   Saturday's resignations prompted expressions of concern from
Italian politicians about the state of the war on the Mafia.
   ``There is a problem of management and administration of men; of
the types of judges; and it is more than a guess to think that the
difficulties have been exacerbated by the inopportune handling of
this government,'' said Virginio Rognoni of the dominant Christian
Democratic party who heads the justice commission in the Chamber of
Deputies.
   Last Thursday, an investigating judge released a report saying
some Christian Democrats helped gain the release of a kidnapped
colleague in 1981 by arranging ransoms for the Neopolitan Mafia and
Red Brigade leftist terrorists.
   Among those who may have been involved was Antonio Gava, the
current interior minister, the report said. Gava denied the charge.
   ``Today, we expected the resignation of Interior Minister
Antonio Gava,'' the Communist newspaper L'Unita said in a
front-page editorial Sunday headlined ``Honest Men and an Arrogant
Government.''
   ``Gava stays and Falcone leaves; it is not a good day for
Italy.''
</TEXT>
