<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietJews     08-01 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Jews,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emigration At Eight-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached a
new eight-year-high in July with a total of 1,639 allowed to leave
the country, the agency involved in their resettlement said today.
   The total represented the seventh straight monthly rise in the
number of arrivals at the Vienna, Austria, transit center, the
Geneva-based Intergovermental Committee for Migration said. Only
930 people opted for new homes in Israel, well below the recent
average, the committee said.
   Last month's figure compared with 1,767 who left the Soviet
Union in June 1980, and brought to 7,656 the number of Jews
emigrating in the first seven months of the year, the committee
said.
   The largest official exodus _ 51,330 _ was recorded in 1979
before the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan chilled East-West
relations.
   Nearly 270,000 Soviet Jews have emigrated since the resettlement
program began in 1971.
</TEXT>
