<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Crime     08-01 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Crime,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Murder And Assault Cases; 1,200 Officers Fired After
Corruption Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violent crime in the Soviet capital is down
overall but murders, assaults and juvenile crime are on the rise
and authorities probing police corruption have fired about 1,200
people, an official said.
   ``We don't hide that fact that in our ranks, there are
bribe-takers, money-grubbers, common criminals in police uniform,''
said Lt. Gen. P.S. Bogdanov, chief of Moscow's Administration of
Internal Affairs, which controls police affairs.
   ``But we will not stop until our ranks have been cleansed,''
Bogdanov told a recent news conference in remarks published Sunday
by Komsomolskaya Pravda, the national youth daily.
   He said that as a result of investigations in the first half of
1988, about 1,200 Internal Affairs employees in Moscow were fired.
   The official said that in the first six months of 1988, there
was a rise in murder, assault with intent to kill and assault
resulting in serious injury, compared to the same period last year.
   The newspaper report gave no specific figures or reasons for the
change.
   Bogdanov said, however, that the number of all crimes registered
in Moscow declined by 9.6 percent compared to 1987. Violent crime _
excluding murder and assault _ dropped by 4.2 percent, he said.
   He did not give the actual number of crimes registered.
   In the first six months of 1988, Muscovites aged 18 and younger
committed 25.6 percent of the crimes in the city, while juvenile
crime accounted for 22.6 percent of the city's unlawful acts during
the same period in 1987, the police general said.
   The juvenile crimes included robbery, rape, joyriding in someone
else's car and apartment break-ins, he said.
   Bogdanov said his ministry will continue to clean out corruption
in police ranks, a process begun more than a year ago under the
reforms of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
