<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-01 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Bakes Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   August got off to a blistering start in many central and eastern
states with unusually high temperatures early today, following a
record-setting day of triple-digit heat in six Midwestern states.
   A high pressure system was centered over southeast Missouri on
Sunday night, keeping much of the warmer air across the central and
eastern parts of the nation and bringing comparatively cooler
temperatures to the Pacific Northwest and northern Plateau regions.
   Temperatures early this morning were very warm across much of
the nation with readings in the 70s along much of the East Coast
into the southeast states and parts of the Ohio Valley; and in the
80s across the central and southern Plains into the middle
Mississippi Valley and from southern Wisconsin through much of
South Dakota into southeast Montana.
   Showers and thunderstorms were developing early this morning
across central and southern parts of North Dakota. Other showers
and thunderstorms were moving across eastern parts of upper
Michigan, as well as the Carolina coast and into northern parts of
Florida.
   In North Carolina, rain flooded low-lying roadways at Nags Head
and Collington. More than 2 inches of rain drenched New Hanover,
N.C., early this morning.
   Thunderstorms abated late Sunday night and early this morning
over the central and southern parts of the Rockies. But heavy rain
was reported Sunday afternoon at Prescott, Ariz., where 2\ inches
of rain fell.
   On Sunday, record-setting heat was recorded in Iowa, Wyoming,
Minnesota, Wisconsin, Illinois and South Dakota.
   In Illinois, several cities sizzled as temperatures climbed past
the 100 degree mark on Sunday. It was 103 degrees in Quincy, and
102 degrees in Peoria, which tied the record for the day set in
1890.
   Minnesota also sweltered. Temperatures reached 105 degrees in
the Minneapolis-St. Paul area on Sunday, the hottest reading in 52
years. Record highs also were reported in St. Cloud and Rochester,
both with 102 degrees. Redwood Falls topped the list with its
reading of 107 degrees.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the northern Rockies into the northern Plains and into the
southern Plateau, across the northern and central areas of the
Great Lakes region and from southern Texas through the Gulf Coast
region into parts of Mississippi and Alabama, through much of
Florida, across the eastern half of North Carolina; and mostly
sunny and hot weather through the remainder of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 90s across much of the
nation; in the 80s from the northern Rockies through the central
intermountain region into the southern Rockies; in the 80s from the
northern parts of the Great Lakes into the upper Ohio Valley and
New England; and from the upper 90s to 105 degrees from the middle
Mississippi Valley into the Central Plains and from the desert
Southwest into the California valleys.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 88 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 fair; Boston 71 foggy; Buffalo 62 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 79 cloudy; Cincinnati 70 foggy; Cleveland
65 fair; Detroit 67 fair; Miami 78 partly cloudy; New York 73
foggy; Philadelphia 76 hazy; Pittsburgh 66 fair; Portland, Maine,
65 foggy; Washington 77 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 70 thunderstorms; Chicago 79 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 81 fair; Denver 69 partly cloudy; Des Moines 78
fair; Indianapolis 73 hazy; Kansas City 80 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 80 fair; Nashville 75 fair; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis 81
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 70 cloudy; Anchorage 59 cloudy; Las Vegas 84
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 68 cloudy; Phoenix 86 partly cloudy;
Salt Lake City 78 fair; San Diego 69 cloudy; San Francisco 60
cloudy; Seattle 55 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 64 fair; Toronto 64 fair.
</TEXT>
