<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChemicalLeak 1stLd-Writethru a0492 08-01 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Leak, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Leak at Monsanto Sends 120 to Hospitals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to delete extraneous word `nearby' and fix typo.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAUGET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second leak of a noxious chemical in 3{
months from a Monsanto Chemical Co. plant sent more than 120 people
to hospitals, and at least nine were admitted though none had
serious injuries, officials said.
   Less than three gallons of phosphorous trichloride, a component
of the herbicide Lasso, escaped into the air when a ``rupture
disk,'' designed to break when pressure built up in the tank, gave
way Sunday morning, said Diane Bartolanzo, a Monsanto spokeswoman.
   The leak was plugged within five minutes, and no evacuation was
ordered, she said.
   On April 17, 22 square blocks of neighboring East St. Louis were
evacuated when about 250 gallons of the substance spilled during
loading onto a railroad tank car, officials have said.
   ``It's just a normal thing,'' Willa Dean Tooks, 40, who lives
about four blocks from the plant, said after Sunday's leak. ``We're
always getting fumes.''
   Most people who went to hospitals were released after treatment
for burning eyes, nausea, headaches, shortness of breath and
dizziness, but at least nine people were admitted, hospital
officials said.
   ``My chest was hurting and my eyes was watering and my throat
was ... dry and every time I breathed, it felt like my wind was
cutting out,'' said Danny Cleggett, 22, of East St. Louis. He said
he was at his mother's home, about a mile from the plant, when
fumes entered the home.
   Cleggett was in good condition at Centreville Hospital, said
Donna Weiss, a nurse there.
   Company officials began an investigation immediately after the
leak, Ms. Bartolanzo said.
   She also said that, as in April, the company will pay medical
expenses due to the spill.
</TEXT>
