<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachedWhale     08-01 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beached Whale,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sea World Experts Try To Save Calf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sea World officials put a 1,400-pound baby
sperm whale that beached itself near Sanibel Island into a special
pool as they worked to keep it alive long enough to return it to
freedom.
   The week-old male, which arrived Sunday at Sea World, was in
critical condition, said Jerie Jones, spokeswoman for the marine
attraction. ``For an animal like this, (research scientists) will
be on 24-hour watch.''
   The 12-foot-long calf was placed in a rehabilitation pool in an
area not open to the public.
   Beachings of sperm whales are rare, and there have only been
about a half-dozen in the last 25 years, said Jay Gorzelany,
coordinator of the Mote Marine Stranding Program. Very few survive
in captivity.
   The sperm whale, which grows to about 50 feet, is an endangered
species. It feeds primarily on squid and fish and normally lives in
water with depths in excess of 600 feet.
   The whale was found by two fishermen Saturday, beached on a
shoal just south of Sanibel Island and mired in ``ankle deep'' mud.
Florida Marine Patrol officials contacted Mote Marine experts.
   ``We checked him and found his heart rate to be erratic and
rapid, about 60 beats per minute,'' Gorzelany said.
   ``It took 14 people to lift him and carry him about 100 yards to
the truck,'' Gorzelany said. ``We could only move him about 10
yards at a time.''
   Officials don't know why whales beach themselves.
</TEXT>
