<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BarbaraJordan 1stLd-Writethru a0487 08-01 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barbara Jordan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Barbara Jordan Recovering</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Ms. Jordan...' to restore missing word `was.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Barbara Jordan was listed
in serious condition this morning, recovering from a near drowning
in her backyard pool, and a doctor says she could be out of the
hospital within a week.
   ``Right now, I think things look very good that she'll get
totally back to normal,'' said Dr. James Little, a neurologist.
``She's very close to normal right now. I think she will continue
to improve. As best as I can tell right now, she probably will
regain full mental functions.''
   Ms. Jordan's condition was upgraded Sunday afternoon from
critical to serious but stable, and she continued to improve Sunday
night.
   ``She started her liquid diet tonight. She is breathing on her
own. She is receiving supplemental oxygen, though,'' hospital
spokeswoman Kari Larsen said.
   Ms. Jordan, 52, gave the thumbs-up sign Sunday to her intensive
care unit nurse and was able to talk.
   ``She's in good spirits now because she knows she's going to get
well,'' said Dr. William J. Deaton, a pulmonary specialist.
   ``She's emotional about that and a little bit teary-eyed some of
the time, knowing what she's been through and how close she came to
a real catastrophic event. But she still also has her jovial
personality. She was joking a little bit this morning,'' Deaton
said Sunday. ``She is vastly improved.''
   Ms. Jordan, who gained national attention during the 1974
Watergate impeachment hearings, was flown by emergency helicopter
to Brackenridge Hospital on Saturday after being found floating
face-down in her pool.
   Ms. Jordan's live-in companion, Nancy Earl, called paramedics,
who restored her pulse and breathing.
   Deaton said she came ``within four to five minutes, 10 minutes
at most'' of suffering severe brain damage and possibly death.
   ``She does not know what happened and was clearly concerned
about it and had indicated that she didn't think she would go
swimming alone again,'' Deaton said.
   Ms. Jordan was breathing Saturday night only with the help of a
ventilator, but Sunday the device was gone and she was responding
to questions and talking, doctors said.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential candidate,
telephoned a message for Ms. Jordan, hospital spokeswoman Carolyn
Hinckley Boyle said. Ms. Jordan made a seconding speech for
Bentsen's nomination at the recent Democratic National Convention.
   Doctors said it isn't known what caused Ms. Jordan to lose
consciousness in the pool, but the lack of oxygen caused cardiac
arrest.
   Deaton said he expected Ms. Jordan to remain in intensive care
for 48 hours and to be hospitalized for about a week.
   The doctors said Ms. Jordan, who has been confined to a
wheelchair for several years, suffers from multiple sclerosis. She
swims as therapy.
   ``She has muscle weakness, and it would be difficult for her to
rescue herself from the swimming pool if she had any warning of any
event. ... I doubt, though, based on the suddenness of the event,
that she had any warning,'' Deaton said.
   Doctors were uncertain how long she was in the pool before being
discovered. Ms. Earl said she returned from a short errand to find
Ms. Jordan unconscious in the pool.
   Ms. Jordan in 1966 became the first black state senator in Texas
history. In 1972, she was the first Southern black elected to
Congress since Reconstruction, serving until 1978, when she left
politics after three terms in the House to teach at the University
of Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0838EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PierCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0468 08-01 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pier Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pier Collapses As Thousands Rush To Board Ferry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with new figures, say pier's top
tier had passengers while lower level for motorists; prime minister
visiting victims, ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of holiday travelers
rushing to board a ferry caused a pier to collapse, leaving at
least 31 people dead and injuring nearly 1,000, officials and news
reports said today.
   Survivors said the upper level of a two-tiered pier in
Butterworth, 180 miles northwest of Kuala Lumpur, fell without
warning Sunday afternoon.
   The upper section full of waiting passengers crashed onto people
in cars and motorcycles on the lower level waiting to board the
ferry.
   Victims were pinned beneath steel and timber while firefighters
and port workers tried to free them and search for others.
   Emergency officials said all of those killed were believed to be
Malaysian.
   About 300 people were on the pier and 3,000 were lined up behind
them when the rush to the ferry began, port commission Chairman
Syed Mohhamad Aidid told the national news agency Bernama.
   He said the 40-foot section that collapsed normally held about
200 people.
   The travelers were waiting to make the three-mile trip to Penang
island for the Kwan Yin (Goddess of Mercy) Chinese religious
celebration, held once every 60 years.
   ``Everything happened so fast, I could only scream for help,''
Gee Swee Cain, 41, a supervisor of the passenger ferry at the pier,
told Bernama.
   As soon as the crowd rushed forward, the pier's wooden upper
level gave way, sending hundreds of people plummeting to the lower
level, said Mrs. Gee, who suffered chest and face injuries and a
broken leg. Her husband and 5-year-old child were uninjured.
   ``I screamed for help and heard someone from above telling me to
be patient because at that time nothing could be done to help me,''
Mrs. Gee told Bernama.
   Cheong Ah Chey, 21, who saw the pier collapse, was quoted by the
news agency as saying, ``The crowd at the waiting area was moving
toward the gate to get into the ferry, which had just berthed, when
suddenly the platform below them gave way.''
   Three cars entering the ferry were crushed and a port commission
office was destroyed, officials said.
   The death toll from the collapse was considered likely to rise,
as many of the injured were hospitalized in critical condition,
Bernama quoted police and other officials as saying.
   Hospitals and clinics in the area initially reported 969 people
injured, with 502 admitted and 467 treated and released, Bernama
said. Officials today said 417 people remained hospitalized.
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad visited the injured at a
government hospital. He told reporters the government would give
$800 immediately to the family of each victim and that he would
consider further compensation.
   The port commission halted ferry service between Butterworth and
Penang pending an inquiry. Traffic jammed Penang Bridge, the only
vehicle link to the island from the mainland after the closure of
the ferry terminal.
   Despite the accident, Penang was crowded with thousands of
people watching the festive parades in the streets.
   The pier was built in 1956 and repaired from time to time,
Bernama reported. The platform that collapsed was last renovated in
1986, when its planks and bolts were replaced.
   The structure was built with pillars only at the sides of the
structure and not in the center, where the section failed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-600-MileMistake     08-01 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-600-Mile Mistake,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Goes Home After Getting Lost During 600-Mile Journey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 74-year-old man who got lost on his way to
the dentist and ended up 600 miles away says part of the problem
was he'd never been away from home.
   Frank Collier returned to Centreville, Ala., on Sunday following
a 17-hour journey that began at 5 a.m. Friday when he left for his
appointment north of Birmingham. Police stopped him at 10:15 p.m.
Friday as he was driving west in the eastbound lane near Muncie, in
central Indiana.
   ``They knew I didn't have no business on that street and so they
stopped me,'' he told The Indianapolis Star on Sunday from the home
he shares with his mother-in-law. ``I was glad the law stopped me.
I was so glad, I didn't know what to do. I hadn't eaten, I hadn't
drank any water.''
   Authorities gave Collier food and a place to stay until members
of his church arrived Sunday to take him home.
   ``It has been one of the strangest things I've ever been
involved with,'' said Delaware County, Ind., police Officer Dan
Hahn. ``I've been a policeman for 10 years and never had anything
like this. It's a miracle he ever made it up here.''
   Collier told police he was on his way to the dentist but
couldn't find the office. He said he turned around to head home.
   Instead, police believe, he wound up on Interstate 65, which
runs from Chicago to Mobile, Ala. From Indianapolis, I-65 continues
northwest toward Lafayette and Chicago. Muncie does not lie along
the interstate.
   Collier said he stopped to buy gasoline in Indianapolis, and
asked for directions home. But no one knew where Centreville was.
Centreville is in central Alabama, about 25 miles southwest of
Birmingham and about 600 miles from Muncie.
   ``So I just kept driving,'' he said. ``When the law stopped me,
they straightened me out. I hadn't ever been away from home. I
didn't know I was that far away until they told me. They treated me
mighty nice.''
   Collier's mother-in-law, Lula Irvin, 96, said she didn't know
what happened to him until police called her.
   ``He just got on the wrong road and he had never been nowhere,''
she said. ``I was worried when he was gone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
