<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Vietnam     08-01 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Vietnam,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Joint Efforts to Account for MIAs Could Start Within
3 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joint U.S.-Vietnam efforts to account for
1,761 Americans still listed as missing from the Vietnam War could
begin soon, a State Department official said today.
   David Lambertson, assistant secretary of state for East Asian
and Pacific Affairs, made that assessment following four days of
meetings in Hanoi last week between Vietnamese officials and
technical experts from the United States.
   ``While there are certain arrangments that will need to be
worked out, we anticipate that joint activities, surveys,
investigations and excavations could begin quite soon,'' Lambertson
said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' program.
   ``We anticipate a substantially higher level of activity over
the next three months,'' said Lambertson, who termed the talks
``quite productive.''
   He said the sites that will be examined remain to be determined.
   In the talks last week, the United States agreed to consider
Vietnam's humanitarian problems in exchange for Vietnamese
cooperation on the MIA matter.
   A leader of the effort to resolve the cases of those still
listed as missing in action said on the same program that her group
views last week's meeting as a sign the Vietnamese hope to put the
issue to rest.
   ``We hope the Vietnamese are serious,'' said Ann Mills
Griffiths, executive director of the National League of Prisoners
of War Missing in Southeast Asia.
   ``I believe this time they are (serious) and I think they've
recognized it's in their own national interest to cooperate in
resolving this,'' she said.
   Despite the increased cooperation, Lambertson said Vietnam's
continued occupation of Cambodia remains as a barrier to
normalization of relations between the two countries.
   ``I believe the Vietnamese understand quite clearly that
normalization is something the United States would be prepared to
enter into in the context of a Cambodian settlement that involves
the complete withdrawal of Vietnamese forces from that country,''
Lambertson said.
   ``We also want one which contains very effective guarantees
against a return to power of the Khmer Rouge,'' he said.
   Representatives from Vietnam, Laos, the Cambodian resistance and
other southeast Asian nations met in Indonesia last week to discuss
an end to the nine-year-old conflict. Vietnam has pledged to
withdraw its 120,000 troops by 1990.
   The Vietnamese withdrawal plan is ``a hopeful sign, but we also
look at it with due skepticism,'' said Lambertson.
   Mrs. Griffiths said talks are quickening with other southeast
Asian nations over MIAs.
   ``We have ongoing efforts with the Laos goverment. There are
encouraging signs there as well, that the pace and level of
cooperation is improving,'' she said. ``I think we'll shortly see
consultations again between Lao and U.S. officials.''
   Vietnam has denied allegations by some American private citizens
that it is holding Americans captured in the war as prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
