<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     08-01 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Claims To Push Iraqis Out Of Three Iranian Towns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its troops withdrew from three
Iranian border towns after disrupting supply lines and capturing
prisoners, but Iran said it repulsed the invaders.
   Iraq said Sunday it will ``maintain our finger on the trigger''
until there is peace. Iran said it will refrain from attacking
Persian Gulf shipping but will stay combat-ready after the
8-year-old war ends.
   Teams of U.N. experts were in the region to work out the
particulars of a cease-fire. U.N.-mediated talks in New York were
set to resume today.
   Tehran radio said Sunday that Iranian forces ``liberated'' the
towns of Qasr-e Shirin, Sar-e Pol-e Zahab and Sumar and
successfully countered what it described as a ``feeble enemy
offensive'' farther north, killing or wounding hundreds of Iraqis.
   On Saturday, Iraq announced its forces had withdrawn from the
three towns.
   The towns are not far from the border and have changed hands
several times over the past 10 days, according to Iranian and Iraqi
accounts.
   An Iraqi offensive Saturday night against the Iranian border
town of Mehran farther south was repulsed with heavy losses, Iran's
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   In Baghdad, the Iraqi capital, the army newspaper Al-Qadissiyah
said that until ``genuine peace'' was assured, ``we will maintain
our finger on the trigger.''
   Similar articles appeared in two other government-run
newspapers, Al-Jumhuriyah and Al-Thawra. The editorials appeared
aimed at dampening public expectations for peace soon.
   Iran and Iraq have been locked in dispute at the United Nations
over Iraq's demand for face-to-face talks before a truce under
terms of U.N. Resolution 598. Iran has rejected direct talks until
a cease-fire is achieved.
   In Tehran on Sunday night, President Ali Khamenei of Iran told
military commanders that even in time of peace, Iran must keep a
combat ready force so that enemies will not think of violating
Iran's rights, IRNA reported.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati of Iran, asked
whether his country would continue to attack neutral ships in the
Persian Gulf, said: ``We will try to do our best not to violate
anything ... so that Resolution 598 will come into reality.''
   Until last week, Iranian vessels had been attacking neutral
shipping in the southern gulf in retaliation for Iraqi attacks on
oil tankers plying Iranian ports.
   Besharati made his comments in Abu Dhabi, in the United Arab
Emirates. He is touring Persian Gulf nations in a bid to underscore
what he says is Iran's desire to cooperate with peace moves.
</TEXT>
