<HEAD>Urban League Leader Unhappy With Bush Refusal To Appear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the National Urban League said
today Vice President George Bush is ``passing up a significant
opportunity'' to win black votes in his presidential race by
turning down an invitation to address the group.
   A Bush spokesman has said the expected GOP presidential nominee
will not speak at the group's four-day national conference in
Detroit because of a scheduling conflict. Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis said he would speak to the conference.
   John E. Jacob, Urban League president, said in an interview from
Detroit that many black voters have not yet been swayed to either
candidate.
   ``I think he's passing up a significant opportunity to win some
black votes,'' Jacobs said on the ABC-TV ``Good Morning America''
program.
   Jacobs said Bush had a good civil rights record while in
Congress but has not sufficiently explained his positions on Reagan
administration policies on such issues as voting rights and
affirmative action.
   ``It seems to us we still need to know who the real George Bush
is. We offered him an opportunity to come and tell us who he is,''
said Jacob. ``The contradictions have to be dealt with.''
   The National Urban League is declining to endorse any candidate
for president.
   Jacob on Sunday lashed out at the Republican Party, saying he
questioned its claims of trying to woo black voters in this year's
presidential election.
   He said at a news conference opening the group's four-day
national conference that Bush declined an invitation to address the
gathering ``just as Ronald Reagan didn't come in 1984.''
   On Saturday, Bush spokesman Mark Goodin said a scheduling
conflict prevented the vice president from accepting the
invitation. He said Bush plans to spend this week examining
potential running mates and will deliver a major foreign policy
speech in Chicago on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
