<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 2ndLd-Writethru a0499 08-01 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0499,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Practice Countdown Completed Despite Leak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th, `A second...' to UPDATE with
launch director comments. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The firing...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle launch team
completed a practice countdown today despite a fuel leak that
raised the possibility of another postponment of a critical test
firing of Discovery's engines.
   The leak halted fueling of the shuttle's hydrogen tank after it
had been loaded with 254,000 gallons, 67 percent of capacity.
   After assessing the situation, launch director Bob Sieck ordered
the countdown to proceed to obtain data on other aspects of the
count. The liquid oxygen tank received a full load of 143,000
gallons and other procedures were rehearsed.
   The countdown was stopped as planned at 11 seconds before a mock
liftoff by a simulated problem, and the launch team began
practicing steps it would take to recover from a postponement _
making the shuttle safe, draining the propellants and turning the
vehicle around for another countdown and launch attempt.
   A second countdown is to end with the test firing of Discovery's
three main engines, with the shuttle bolted to the pad. The firing
had been scheduled for Thursday, but NASA officials said it might
have to be delayed another day or so because of the leak.
   A decision on when to schedule the firing probably would not be
made before Tuesday, Sieck said
   He said the launch team had done ``an excellent job'' in
completing the countdown despite the difficulty. ``We must now
evaluate the results and schedule the work that needs to be done
before the firing,'' he added.
   The firing already had been postponed four times in 10 days.
   A three-day delay was announced Friday because of a hydrogen
leak and a balky oxygen pump.
   The newest leak was in the same launch pad service mast as the
earlier one, but officials would not know if it was in the same
line until technicians traced it. They will not have access to the
pad until after the launch team completes draining the hydrogen and
oxygen Tuesday.
   NASA said that despite Sunday's leak, it was satisfied that most
requirements of the first part of the countdown had been met.
Objectives missed were to be picked up during a second fueling and
countdown for the test firing.
   Officials believe the practice countdown delays, combined with
an unresolved leak in Discovery's steering engine system, will slip
Discovery's launch date from mid-September into October.
   The purpose of the dual countdown test is to check modifications
made to the engines and launch pad and to provide countdown
practice for the launch team.
   The 20-second engine ignition is considered critical to
certifying Discovery for the first shuttle flight since Challenger
exploded shortly after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986, killing the crew
of seven.
   When the test is completed, officials of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration still must cope with the small
gas leak in a steering engine system that is separate from
Discovery's main engines.
   Engineers have come up with a plan to reach and repair the leak
by entering the shuttle's cargo bay and cutting a hole through the
rear bulkhead into the steering engine compartment.
   Another option, with a decision to be made after the
test-firing, is to take Discovery off the pad and back to a hangar
for repair, a move that could postpone the launch until November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0065 </DOCNO>
