<HEAD>`Colors,' `Hill Street Blues' Star Trinidad Silva Killed in Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITTIER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trinidad Silva Jr., who portrayed a gang
leader in the movie ``Colors'' and TV's ``Hill Street Blues,'' was
killed in a crash that also injured his wife and son, police said.
He was 38.
   Silva's pickup truck was broadsided Sunday at an intersection by
a car driven by a man who allegedly was drunk and who was arrested,
said police Sgt. Gene Horsfall.
   Silva, of Whittier, was pronounced dead at the scene, said Dave
Campbell of the Los Angeles County Coroner's Office.
   In NBC-TV's ``Hill Street Blues,'' Silva played the
wise-cracking gang leader Jesus Martinez, who taunted Capt. Frank
Furillo by calling him ``Frankie boy.''
   He also portrayed ``Frog,'' an older gang leader in ``Colors,''
a performance the Hollywood Reporter called ``mesmerically
engaging.''
   ``From what we can tell, the arrested man went through a red
light and broadsided Mr. Silva's truck, and Silva's truck spun
around and hit the other vehicle,'' Horsfall said.
   Silva's wife, Sofia, 28, and their 2-year-old son, Samuel,
suffered minor injuries and were treated, said Julie Maxwell, a
Presbyterian Intercommunity Hospital nursing supervisor.
   Douglas Robert Owens, 35, of La Habra, was booked for
investigation of felony drunken driving, felony hit and run and
vehicular manslaughter, Horsfall said.
   The driver of the other pickup truck was identified as Oscar
Valenzuela, 30. Neither he nor his 3-year-old son were injured, Ms.
Maxwell said. His wife, Norma Valenzuela was treated for minor
injuries.
   A fourth passenger in the Silva vehicle was not injured, Lt.
Jack Johnson said.
   Funeral arrangements were not announced.
</TEXT>
