<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Columnist Rowan Faces Court Date</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Pre-noon top expected</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated columnist Carl Rowan, a vocal gun
control advocate, was expected to plead not guilty to handgun
charges today in the shooting of a teen-ager who took an uninvited
dip in Rowan's backyard pool in June.
   A group of Rowan's supporters gathered outside the District of
Columbia Courthouse before 9 a.m. to protest Rowan's prosecution.
   Rowan, 62, was charged last week with possessing an unregistered
handgun and ammunition. He faces a penalty of up to two years in
jail and $2,000 in fines if convicted.
   His attorney, Raoul Carroll, told The Washington Times the
columnist planned to ask to have his case heard before a Superior
Court jury.
   ``We can communicate to them that Carl Rowan Jr., who owned the
gun, tried everything in his power to get the gun registered.
District officials did not allow him to do it,'' Carroll said.
   Rowan has said that his son, a former FBI agent, tried to
register the weapon in 1982 but was told that it wasn't necessary
because he was a law-enforcement officer at the time. The elder
Rowan said he later obtained the gun from his son, at a time he was
receiving threats.
   Except for law officers, District of Columbia law generally bans
posession of handguns and ammunition not owned prior to 1976.
   The charges stem from the June 14 shooting of Benjamin Smith,
18, of Chevy Chase, Md., who had climbed over Rowan's backyard
fence to take a late-night swim in the columnist's pool. Rowan told
police shot the intruder in the hand when he thought the teen was
lunging at him.
   Smith was treated and released the same day at from Georgetown
University Hospital. He was charged with one count of unlawful
entry, but prosecutors dropped the misdemeanor charge in exchange
for 40 hours of community service.
</TEXT>
