<HEAD>Charges Dropped Against Brothers in Oakland Bus Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murder charges have been dropped against
two brothers arrested shortly after men boarded a bus and opened
fire, killing the driver and wounding three passengers, police said
today.
   Sgt. Jerry Harris also said two new suspects have been arrested
in the slaying Friday of Billy Givens. He described the suspects
arrested Sunday night as a 17-year-old male and a 15-year-old male.
Neither was identified.
   Donald Palmer, 25, and David Palmer, 29, were arrested about two
hours after the shooting. Their mother, Ellen Palmer, 52, was
killed Thursday in a collision with a bus driven by a rookie driver.
   Officers talked to witnesses and ``determined that the suspects
were not either of the Palmer brothers, and at about 4 p.m.
(Sunday) we released them on the murder charges,'' Harris said.
   But the brothers ``still have some warrant problems,'' and it
was unclear if they had been released from jail, Harris said.
   Harris said police had determined the teen-agers knew the Palmer
family, but he said there was no indication anyone in the family
had a role in prompting the attack.
   Givens, 43, who worked for AC transit for 20 years, was struck
several times with bullets from a semiautomatic .22 caliber rifle.
   Witnesses said four young men had stepped aboard Givens' bus,
which carried 20 passengers, and shouted obscenities at the driver
before firing 12 rounds.
