<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     08-01 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trustee Plans Auction of Coins, Stamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PTL trustee plans to hold several
auctions this month to sell silver coins, stamps and other
valuables found in a vault at PTL headquarters.
   The sale comes as a Canadian real estate executive says he plans
to pursue his offer to pay $113 million for Heritage USA and
operate it as a theme park with no religious overtones.
   Trustee M.C. Benton said the auctions would be Friday, Saturday
and Aug. 12 at the Heritage Grand Hotel.
   Although the collection had been in the vault for some time,
Benton first saw the inside of the vault July 25. Benton said he
looked after deciding to sell assets to raise money for the
financially troubled ministry and Christian retreat.
   ``I started the program of auctioning things we don't need
several weeks ago. The things in this vault are another part of
that program,'' Benton said.
   An appraiser has not completed evaluating the collection.
   Benton said the use of any money raised would be determined by
U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds.
   PTL filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
bankruptcy laws more than a year ago. It owes creditors an
estimated $130 million.
   The 15-by-16-foot vault contains small bars of 99.9 percent pure
silver, a rack of fur coats, small statuettes of various metals and
old money and stamps.
   Benton said other items that will be auctioned include pieces of
heavy equipment Heritage USA no longer uses and automobiles donated
to the ministry.
   Canadian real estate executive Peter Thomas says Benton is ready
to work with him, according to the Vancouver Sun.
   Thomas, majority stockholder in Century 21 of Canada, told the
newspaper, ``I believe now they'll give it (Heritage USA) to me.''
   Thomas, 49, was born in London and grew up the Canadian province
of Alberta.
   In recent weeks, PTL founder Jim Bakker, who was forced from the
ministry in a sex and money scandal, has said he wants to buy back
PTL's assets and return as its leader. Also in the bidding is
Charlotte, N.C., sports executive George Shinn, who has said he
wants to build a sports complex adjoining Heritage USA.
</TEXT>
