<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ConstructionSpending     08-01 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Construction Spending,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Edged Up 0.1 Percent in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending edged up 0.1 percent in
June as continued strength in non-residential building offset
declines in housing and government projects, the government said
today.
   The Commerce Department said building activity rose to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $402.8 billion in June,
following a 0.8 percent increase in May. In April, construction
plunged 1.1 percent after soaring 2.8 percent in March. The June
level was 2.6 percent higher than a year ago.
   The strength came from a 2.5 percent increase in spending on
non-residential construction, which climbed to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $99.2 billion, led by big jumps in both
factory and hotel-motel construction. It was the fourth consecutive
monthly increase.
   Factory construction rose 5.7 percent and now stands 21 percent
higher than it was a year ago. U.S. manufacturers have boosted
investment on new factories because of a surge in export sales
caused by the weaker dollar.
   Hotel and motel construction increased 19.4 percent after
falling for two months.
   Construction of office buildings in June was off by 0.4 percent
from the May level. However, the small decline followed increases
in May, April and March, and the June rate was still 12 percent
higher than a year ago, something of a puzzle to analysts because
of lingering high vacancy rates in that sector caused by widespread
overbuilding in previous years.
   Residential construction fell 0.9 percent in June to an annual
rate of $188.1 billion, the third decline in a row. That sector has
been hurt by an increase in mortgage interest rates since the
spring. A 0.7 percent drop in construction of single-family homes
more than offset a 2.3 percent increase in apartment construction.
   Government construction projects fell 1.4 percent in June to an
annual rate of $78.6 billion with highway construction, the biggest
segment of the government sector, suffering a 1.6 percent decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
