<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Winner'sBlues     08-01 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Winner's Blues,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lottery Winner Charged With Trying To Have Daughter-In-Law Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who won $5 million in Canada's
lottery and allegedly owes as much to the Internal Revenue Service
has now been accused of trying to pay an undercover officer to kill
her daughter-in-law, police said.
   Hillsborough County Sheriff's spokesman Jack Espinosa said Mary
Ellen Futch, 64, on Saturday ``negotiated a contract with our
undercover detective for $5,000'' to kill Peggy Futch, 23.
   If convicted of soliciting for the first-degree murder, Mrs.
Futch could face up to a 30-year prison sentence. Mrs. Futch was
being held without bond at the Hillsborough County Jail.
   ``She never would let me have any friends,'' said Henry Futch,
28, whose mother won the money on Sept. 15, 1984. ``She would
always chase them off whenever I'd bring one home.''
   Mrs. Futch received her winnings in a lump sum and since has
frittered the money away, relatives say. She bought a house to be
near her youngest son, whom family members said she doted on. News
reports at the time said she once tipped a man $7,000 just to play
pool with her son.
   She also gave away some money, then made bad investments in
Canada. And she failed to pay any income tax in the United States,
authorities say.
   The IRS, which says the $5 million is due in back taxes,
interest and penalties, has seized her home and plans to auction it
Wednesday, her son said.
   Her son and Peggy Futch, who were married two years ago, both
were surprised at the charge.
   ``She was over here yesterday, laughing and drinking coffee,''
Peggy Futch said. ``We had our spats, but I would apologize to her
or she would apologize to me. That's why I was so shocked.''
   Futch said the money troubles left his mother distraught.
   Espinosa declined to disclose a motive for the alleged
contract-murder deal.
</TEXT>
