<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   08-01 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0525,0731</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Deports Palestinians, Arab Reaction to Hussein's Speech
Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout to add detail, quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel deported eight Palestinians today, the
military said, as fellow Palestinians in the occupied territories
held a commercial strike to protest the Israeli policy of
expulsions.
   The deportations came a day after Jordan's King Hussein
announced he was severing ties with the 850,000 Arabs in the
occupied West Bank he once ruled.
   The eight Palestinians were visited by their families at Jneid
Prison in the West Bank before being driven away, relatives said.
   A military spokesman said they were taken to Israel's northern
border with Lebanon.
   Among the deportees was a journalist with Jerusalem's Arabic
language Al Fajr newspaper, Loui Abdo, who was accused of leading a
Palestine Liberation Organization-linked youth group in the West
Bank city of Nablus, security sources said.
   Other deportees included a lecturer from the Bir Zeit University
near Ramallah and a labor leader from nearby El Bireh, they said.
   The expulsions brought to 29 the number of Palestinians deported
since the beginning of the eight-month Arab uprising.
   Some Palestinians denounced Hussein today as a traitor for
severing ties with them, but others praised the monarch for ceding
to the PLO as their sole representative.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Hussein's decision to divorce
himself from the occupied West Bank dealt a blow to the idea of a
united Palestinian nation.
   Hussein said in his speech he intended to cut legal and
administrative ties with the West Bank, which he ruled before
losing the area to Israel during the 1967 Middle East War.
   The decision was a setback for Foreign Minister Shimon Peres'
Labor Party, which had proposed resolving the dispute with the
Palestinians by negotiations with Jordan. A government official
today disclosed that Peres had tried through foreign intermediaries
to persuade Hussein not to break ties.
   In at least two West Bank cities, Arabs scribbled slogans on
walls denouncing Hussein. ``Down With Hussein, The Traitor,'' one
said in the city of Tulkarm.
   Other Palestinians disagreed.
   ``It's a good gesture for the Palestinians and it should start
the ball rolling in the direction of working out strategic
relationships between the PLO and Jordan on the future,''
Palestinian journalist Daoud Kuttab of the Nazareth daily A-Sinara
told Israel radio.
   Shamir, speaking to New Zealand's new ambassador, said Hussein
had ``dealt a blow'' to the idea of a Palestinian state by
differentiating between Palestinians living on the east bank of the
Jordan River and those in the West Bank.
   ``If as Hussein says one part of them has to set up a
Palestinian state and another part is Jordanian ... where then is
the one Palestinian people,'' an aide quoted Shamir as saying.
   ``It is possible to draw the conclusion that the whole idea of a
Palestinian people is an invention for the sake of propaganda,''
Shamir added.
   Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes territorial concessions
to the Arabs and believes the West Bank and Gaza Strip are integral
parts of the historic land of Israel.
   Peres said the effect of Hussein's announcement was still not
known because he had not said how he would carry out his decision.
But analysts said Hussein's speech may hurt the Labor Party in
November elections.
   The Likud ``can exploit this and claim Peres' concept of
negotiations with Jordan has collapsed,'' said Middle East expert
Aryeh Shalev.
   Hussein, while not ruling out the likelihood that Jordan would
take part in negotiations, made it clear the Palestinians must
speak for themselves.
   A government official close to Peres, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Peres had tried through foreign diplomats to
dissuade Hussein from making his speech, telling them Israel
``still believes in a need for peace talks with Jordan.''
   The Israeli daily Haaretz said one of the intermediaries was
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who it said passed a
message from Peres to Hussein last month.
   Editorials in Palestinian-owned newspapers voiced confusion over
Jordan's plans.
   Some were fearful Hussein could cancel Jordanian passports held
by many of the 850,000 Palestinians in the West Bank or even close
bridges connecting the West Bank to Jordan, a vital economic link
to the Arab world.
</TEXT>
