<2ND_LINE>PM-Qatar-Soviet,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Qatar Establishes Relations With Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOHA, Qatar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Persian Gulf state of Qatar today
announced it has established diplomatic ties with the Soviet Union,
less than a month after taking a similar step with China.
   A joint statement released in Doha and Moscow said the two
countries took the step to ``strengthen the bonds of friendship and
cooperation.''
   Qatar's diplomatic ties with China were announced July 9.
   The moves come after Washington in June formally protested this
central Persian Gulf state's refusal to hand over U.S.-made Stinger
missiles it bought on the black market.
   Qatar belongs to the six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council, an
economic and security alliance that also includes Saudi Arabia,
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman and the United Arab Emirates.
   In addition to Qatar, the other nations in the alliance who have
diplomatic relations with the Soviet Union are Kuwait, Oman and the
United Arab Emirates. All member states of the alliance have been
traditionally pro-Western.
   But after Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev came to power, he
activated contacts with the oil-rich Persian Gulf region and the
sale of arms became a growing factor in the relationship.
   The Saudi monarch, King Fahd, last week said that his country
was not against buying arms from communist nations, although Riyadh
later underlined its strong ties to Washington.
</TEXT>
