<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ComputerKids     08-01 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Computer Kids,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-agers Working For Chance To Win Supercomputer For Their
Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen teen-agers from four high schools
are burning the midnight oil and working Saturdays for a shot at
winning a $1 million supercomputer for their school.
   ``We had to twist their arms to let us stay until 2 a.m.,'' said
contestant Roland Feldmeier, 18, who just graduated from James
Logan High School in Union City, Calif.
   The teen-agers from Union City; Silver Spring, Md.; Tallahassee,
Fla., and Alexandria, Va., arrived in late June for the competition
at ETA Systems, a 5-year-old maker of supercomputers, where they're
using an ETA10-P supercomputer on projects they devised. A winner
will be announced Aug. 12.
   Each student is getting $3,000 for participating, and each of
the four high schools is assured of winning a $50,000 workstation
made by Control Data Corp., ETA's parent.
   The students' projects range from complex analyses of how to
design computer problems to a model of school hall traffic.
   All seek to take advantage of a supercomputer's capacity to make
millions of calculations far more quickly than other computers.
   Maneesh Agrawala, 16, is using the computer to create
mathematical models of proteins.
   Agrawala, who will be a junior this fall at Montgomery Blair
High School in Silver Spring, Md., is the son of a computer science
professor at the University of Maryland and began programming small
computers in the seventh grade.
   Asked whether the students at ETA could be considered
single-minded computer jocks, 17-year-old Troy Carroll replied:
``People could get that impression of me, but not of everybody
else. There are some real well-rounded people here.''
   Carroll, from North Florida Christian School in Tallahassee, has
had several personal computers and runs a computer bulletin board
from his home. He's working on a model of the international trade
economy, trying to show the long-range effects of small changes in
trade policy, such as higher tax rates.
   Feldmeier is simulating the hall traffic in his high school,
trying to determine a better way to assign students' lockers to
keep crowding between classes to a minimum.
   ``I've walked through those halls for four years,'' he said. ``I
know how bad it is. Our school superintendent is real excited about
the program.''
   The fourth team is from Thomas Jefferson High School for Science
and Technology in Alexandria, Va.
   The four schools selected on the basis of proposals from 99
semifinalists, chosen from a field of 1,500 applicants.
   ETA is struggling to reach profitability and acknowledges the
public relations benefits of the contest. But the contest, known as
Superquest, is also a personal project for company President Carl
Ledbetter.
</TEXT>
