<2ND_LINE>PM-Derailment,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freight Train Derails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OHIOPYLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nineteen cars, five of them containing
hazardous materials, derailed today as a 105-car freight train
rolled through a remote river valley, officials said.
   ``The report is that there is no leak from any of these cars,''
said CSX spokesman Lindsay Leckie in Jacksonville, Fla.
   None of the cars entered the Youghiogheny River, said Betsy
Mallison, spokeswoman for the state Department of Environmental
Resources.
   The Youghiogheny, a key recreation resource for southwestern
Pennsylvania, was closed for 10 miles, state officials said. A
biking trail and a hiking trail also were closed.
   None of the three train crew members was injured, Leckie said.
   Two boxcars containing pulp board, a raw material in paper
making, burned, he said.
   Amtrak's Capitol Limited, which uses the CSX line, was detoured
to Philadelphia, adding four hours to the Pittsburgh-to-Washington
run, said Amtark spokesman Clifford Black. Some passengers were
taken by bus.
   The CSX accident occurred around 3 a.m. at a site is accessible
only by rail, forcing hazardous materials teams to ride railcars to
the wreckage, about 50 miles southeast of Pittsburgh.
   The CSX train was en route from Cumberland, Md. to Willard,
Ohio, Leckie said.
</TEXT>
