<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Hostages     08-01 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hostages,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Says Hostages May Be Freed This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All Western hostages may be released from Lebanon
by the end of the year, an Australian archbishop predicted today
after a mission to the Iranian capital.
   Also today, the Foreign Office said Britain is reviewing its
relations with Iran, including the possibility of sending a
diplomat to Tehran.
   ``I would not be surprised if Terry Waite and the others were
released before the end of the year,'' Archbishop David Penman of
Melbourne told reporters in Canterbury.
   ``It's my intuition that it (the hostages' release) will come
after the U.S. and Israeli elections'' in November, said Penman,
who visited Tehran en route to England.
   Waite, the envoy of Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie,
disappeared in Lebanon on Jan. 20, 1987 while seeking the release
of American hostages.
   Eighteen Westerners, including nine Americans, are missing after
apparent kidnappings by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon. The longest
held is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said the review in relations with
Iran was prompted in part by Iran's acceptance of a United Nations
resolution calling for a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war against
Iraq.
   ``British ministers are reviewing the whole gambit of
Anglo-Iranian relations including the possibility of sending a
diplomat to Tehran for a short period of time,'' the spokesman
said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On Sunday, the Church of England disclosed that the Rt. Rev.
John Brown, bishop of Cyprus and the Persian Gulf region, went to
Lebanon last week seeking word on four Iranians who disappeared
there in 1982. They were presumed kidnapped by Christian militia
and some reports have said they are dead.
   Brown said he hopes his mission contributed to efforts to win
the release of foreign hostages.
   ``It's very important to us when we are talking to the Iranians
... to show them that we are concerned about their missing people
as well as ours,'' Brown said.
   He said he met with the leaders of the Maronite Church and the
Armenian church community and ``they have promised to make
inquiries of their own communities.''
   Iran's only diplomat in London, charge d'affaires Akunzadeh
Basti, had a meeting at the Foreign Office today and said afterward
Iran would use its influence to get information about the hostages.
   Basti said Iran hoped to normalize relations with Britain. ``I
think a better atmosphere is developing,'' he said.
   Britain and Iran recently settled a dispute over compensation
for damages to diplomatic buildings in each other's countries. A
delegation of British parliamentarians also visited Tehran to
discuss improving relations.
   Among the British hostages are journalist John McCarthy,
kidnapped in April 1986, and teacher Brian Keenan, who disappeared
the same month. Keenan also holds Irish citizenship.
   The Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a
New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors claim
they killed him. His body was never found.
</TEXT>
