<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson-Koch 2ndLd-Writethru a0526 08-01 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Koch, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0526,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson, Koch Say They're Willing to Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Koch quotes, subbing lead and inserting 4 grafs
after 9th graf pvs, The leaders</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson and New York Mayor Edward I. Koch
said today they are willing to meet and try to heal or at least set
aside the differences that have simmered since Koch's strong
criticism of Jackson before the New York primary.
   Jackson, who lost the April primary and later the Democratic
presidential nomination to Michael Dukakis, said Koch called him at
his Chicago home early today ``and said he would like to meet.''
   ``I have always kept open the door to communications. I believe
that people should talk,'' Jackson said in a telephone interview
from his home.
   He said he was ``concerned that in New York because of (Koch's)
attacks, we missed a great opportunity to discuss urban policy in
this country.''
   Koch's criticism last April included a statement that Jews would
be ``crazy'' to vote for Jackson, who supports Palestinian
self-determination.
   ``My feelings toward the mayor are always open and respectful,''
Jackson said. ``His toward me were very hostile.''
   Jackson said Koch ``used race and religion as litmus test and
divided the city and helped to lower the moral tone of the
campaign.''
   He said he told Koch that if they are to meet, it should be
arranged through David Dinkins, Manhattan borough president, and
Rep. Charles Rangel, and the meeting should include black leaders
such as those two, both of whom are Jackson supporters.
   ``The leaders ought to meet and work out a common agenda,''
Jackson said.
   In New York, Koch said he would call Dinkins to arrange a
meeting with Jackson ``as soon as possible so we could get behind
Dukakis.''
   Koch said he was not trying to line up support among blacks _
through Jackson _ for his own re-election campaign next year.
   ``I'm not in contention this year,'' he said. ``And if you
really believe as I do that it's important to have a Democrat in
the White House, you set aside those differences.''
   The mayor said he told Jackson, ``I would want to meet with him
as soon as possible. We had the same goal,'' the election of
Dukakis.
   Because of Koch's statements before the New York primary,
``There was no focus on the crisis of homelesses nad the
relationship between drugs and AIDS as a growing killer epidemic,''
Jackson said.
   ``I would think the Democratic leadership must come together
from various walks of life,'' he said.
   Jackson said Sunday he had accepted New York Gov. Mario Cuomo's
request to smooth over differences with Koch, The New York Times
reported today.
   ``Governor Cuomo has expressed interest in the relationship
being healed,'' Jackson told the Times. ``I think that's good.''
   Koch said in a statement: ``I agree that in the interest of
party unity and the election of Michael Dukakis, it would be good
to meet with Jesse Jackson.''
   Cuomo said Sunday he talked with Jackson on Friday, and that he
had told Jackson and Koch ``how important I thought it was to put
things together again.''
   Koch and Cuomo said a first meeting should be attended by only
the three. Koch added Sunday that he ``would have no hesitancy in
sitting down with Jesse Jackson and any black leaders he would like
to bring.''
   On the WCBS-TV Sunday program ``Newsmakers,'' Koch said: ``It's
hardly likely that Jesse Jackson and his intimate supporters _ you
know, the ones closest to him _ are ever going to support me. We
have fundamental differences.''
   But he said they could work together, noting that ``there are
probably wider differences between Jesse Jackson and (Democratic
vice-presidential nominee) Lloyd Bentsen than between Jesse Jackson
and me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
