<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech 1stLd-Writethru a0484 08-01 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Jury Deliberations Delayed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf with deliberations delayed.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury is weighing the evidence at
the Wedtech corruption trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi and six
co-defendants charged with racketeering.
   The panel, which is not sequestered, went home at 5:30 p.m.
Sunday and was to resume deliberating this morning, but because of
a communications mixup which sent their transportation to the wrong
address, three jurors had not arrived at the courthouse by noon.
   The jury began deliberations Saturday after more than four
months of testimony and a week of closing arguments by the
prosecution and defense.
   Biaggi, D-N.Y., former Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon and
five other people are charged with turning the now-defunct Wedtech
Corp., a Bronx-based defense contractor, into a racketeering
enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in bribes to obtain
no-bid government contracts.
   The others co-defendants are Biaggi's oldest son, Richard;
Biaggi's former law partner, Bernard Ehrlich; Peter Neglia, a
former regional head of the Small Business Administration; and
Richard Betso, a former policeman and friend of Neglia's.
</TEXT>
