<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gangs 1stLd-Writethru a0513 08-01 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gangs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead In First Gang Killing Since Truce Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead and inserts 1 graf after 5th, `A second...' to
UPDATE with second fatal shooting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN CALLISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three days after warring gang members ended
truce talks with a call for a week of peace and prayer, two people
were killed and at least five other people were injured in
gang-related violence, police said.
   Police said William Douglas Randle, 18, of Los Angeles, was the
first person to die since members of two street gangs, the Crips
and the Bloods, met last week and called on other members to
refrain from violence for one week and observe seven days of prayer.
   Randle died Sunday, about an hour after he was shot while
standing with a group of people in a parking lot, said police Sgt.
Steve LaRoche.
   An estimated 15 shots were fired from a passing car police
believe was filled with suspected Crips gang members, LaRoche said.
   A second person was wounded. Edward Domingus, 17, of Los
Angeles, was in critical condition today at Daniel Freeman Memorial
Hospital in Inglewood, according to a nursing supervisor.
   In another drive-by, gang-related shooting, Douglas Henegen, 21,
of Merced was killed Sunday night at Hansen Dam Park, said police
Detective Albert Ferrand. No arrests were made, he said.
   In another incident Sunday, two men were injured, one
critically, when they were struck by shots fired from a passing
car, police said.
   An unidentified 20-year-old was in critical condition and
undergoing surgery at Harbor-UCLA Medical Center today, according
to nursing supervisor V. Pascua. The second victim's identity and
condition were not immediately known.
   Sgt. Tony Rosa said the violence was believed to be gang-related.
   A shooting earlier Sunday left one man in critical condition
with a wound to the head at Memorial Medical Center of Long Beach.
Los Angeles County Sheriff's Deputy Van Mosley said authorities
don't know if that shooting was gang-related.
   In a shooting about 5 a.m. Sunday, a juvenile was listed in
serious but stable condition today at Harbor-UCLA Medical Center
after being injured in a gang-related shooting, Rosa said.
   Another man was injured in a drive-by shooting Saturday night.
The victim was hospitalized in stable condition with wounds to the
thigh and hand.
   The police anti-gang task force has arrested 9,000 people
identified as gang members in four months. There were at least 174
killings by gang members in the first half of this year in Los
Angeles County. Last year, there were 387 gang-related slayings,
the highest ever.
</TEXT>
