<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HoseaWilliams     08-01 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hosea Williams,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hosea Williams Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights activist and City Councilman Hosea
Williams was arrested at City Hall today on a weapons possession
indictment from neighboring Clayton County.
   Stanley Tuggle, chief of administrative operations for the
Clayton County Sheriff's Department, said Williams was arrested by
sheriff's officers who went to Atlanta after Williams held a news
conference to deny he had been notified of the charges.
   Williams was taken away in handcuffs.
   At the news conference about two hours before his arrest,
Williams said he never was notified about the indictment and denied
reports that he had promised to surrender over the weekend.
   ``The racist white press of Atlanta is again out to destroy my
image as a black leader who is unbought and unbossed,'' he said.
   Tuggle was quoted over the weekend as saying: ``We have been in
contact with Mr. Williams and he has indicated he will turn himself
in.''
   The indictment stems from an incident at Hartsfield Atlanta
International Airport in March.
   Tuggle said today that Clayton County authorities contacted
Williams indirectly last week through the Fulton County Sheriff's
Department and that Williams told those officers he would handle
the matter over the weekend.
   ``He is being truthful when he says he didn't talk directly with
us, but he's not being truthful when he says he didn't know
anything about it,'' Tuggle said.
   Williams was stopped March 6 at a security checkpoint at the
airport as he tried to board a plane. Police said they found a
.38-caliber handgun and five bullets in his briefcase.
   The civil rights activist told reporters he placed the gun in
his briefcase while cleaning his car and forgot it was there when
he dashed to the airport.
   Williams was given a copy of the charges and was allowed to
board the plane after the pistol and bullets were confiscated.
   He initially was charged with two misdemeanor counts of carrying
a weapon without a license and carrying a concealed weapon. The
charge was upgraded to a single felony count after a review of
Williams' criminal record, according to Tuggle.
   Williams was arrested numerous times during his work for civil
rights, but also has faced a string of traffic-related charges.
</TEXT>
