<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Dangler, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0539,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man In Wheelchair Dangles From Brooklyn Bridge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with man having paralyzed legs, other
details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with paralyzed legs who said he is
``America's No. 1 Stuntman'' carried explosives onto the Brooklyn
Bridge today, lowered himself in his wheelchair and dangled for
more than an hour over the East River, police said.
   He was finally talked down onto a police launch in the river.
   The man, Raymond Mesa, 40, of the Bronx, was charged with
disorderly conduct and unlawful dealing with fireworks, said Sgt.
John Clifford.
   Mesa carried business cards that proclaimed, ``Living on the
edge is my business _ America's No. 1 Stuntman,'' Clifford said.
   Mesa was taken to Beekman-Downtown Hospital Center for
psychiatric observation. He told reporters he performed the stunt
to show that handicapped people can ``do anything.''
   Alerted by the crew of a tugboat, a police harbor unit,
emergency service officers and ambulance personnel rushed to the
landmark 105-year-old bridge, which connects Manhattan and Brooklyn.
   Bomb squad officials were also called after a report the man may
have been carrying a couple of pipe bombs. Mesa was carrying two
bags which contained six super M-80's, each the equivalent of
quarter-stick of dynamite, Clifford said.
   The bridge was reopened when Mesa surrendered, but closed again
briefly later while the police bomb squad checked for explosives
that might have been left on the bridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
