<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid 1stLd-Writethru a0460 08-01 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Propose Renewed Contra Aid if Nicaragua Violates Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Byrd, Dole, Wright, White House comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd said today
he hopes to reach bipartisan agreement this week on a new aid
package for Nicaragua's Contra rebels, but it remained unclear
whether the measure would include new weapons.
   Byrd, D-W.Va., said the matter could come before the Senate by
mid-week, when lawmakers will take up a supplemental money bill, or
late in the week when they begin work on a Pentagon funding measure.
   ``The Democrats have not finalized a plan yet,'' Byrd told
reporters. ``I hope we can reach consensus among Democrats and then
go to the Republican leader and see if we can get bipartisan
agreement.''
   Meanwhile, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said it was an
encouraging sign that the Democrats are working on a proposal to
give military aid to the Contras if the Sandinista government does
not honor its peace pledges.
   It ``certainly does seem to signal that the Democrats and others
are concerned about the recent actions of President (Daniel)
Ortega, that they recognize the fact Ortega has turned his back on
the peace process and has started clamping down on all these
various freedoms,'' said Fitzwater.
   He said the administration would work with Democrats and others
``to get an acceptable plan.''
   Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., has proposed a $47 million aid
package for the anti-Sandinista rebels, including $20 million in
standby military aid that could be triggered by a later
congressional vote. The package has been endorsed by President
Reagan, for whom the Contras have been a top foreign policy
priority.
   Dole today pronounced himself ``eager to hear what (the
Democrats) have in mind'' and urged Democratic drafters to include
a reliable delivery system in their aid plan.
   While diplomatic negotiations are the key to peace in the
region, Dole said, sustaining the rebels as ``a credible presence
at the bargaining table'' is essential to the success of any talks.
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias is at work on a plan to bring
the two sides back together following the breakdown of negotiations
in June.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee and a consistent supporter of the rebel military effort,
said Sunday Democrats are at work on a proposal to give military
aid to the Contras if the leftist Managua government does not honor
the peace pledges it has made.
   ``There's an effort right now going on among Senate Democrats to
come forward with our own proposal,'' Boren said Sunday on NBC-TV's
``Meet the Press.''
   ``As I said, one that would be balanced, that would hold out the
stick, the possibility of a resumption of military aid if the
Sandinistas continue to violate the peace pledges they've made.''
   The Washington Post said in Monday's editions that the
Democratic plan calls for a release of $18 million in frozen
military aid to the Contras if the Sandinistas violate provisions
of the regional peace plan reached almost exactly a year ago.
   But prospects for ultimate passage of any new aid remained
clouded. House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said today the House
would wait to see what senators agree on before taking any action.
He added: ``I still tend to doubt there will be votes in the House
to resume the war.''
   The prospects for renewed aid in Congress generally reflect the
increased polarization in the region, where the Sandinistas have
cracked down harshly on opponents and a newly reconstituted Contra
leadership has taken a harder line.
   Boren told the Post the Democratic plan would prohibit further
votes on the Contra-aid issue this year. That would in large part
remove the controversial issue from the presidential campaign.
   Under the proposal being drafted by the Senate Democrats,
according to the Post, $18 million in lethal aid already
appropriated but frozen would be released if the Sandinista
government made an unprovoked attack on the Contras.
   Dole said the $18 million figure did not square with information
he has received from the administration, and that actual residual
weapons stores were less. The exact figure is classified.
   The paper quoted Boren as saying the lethal aid already exists
in warehouses outside the United States. The president would
determine when an unprovoked attack is made.
   Congress voted $100 million in military aid to the Contras in
late 1986 _ $60 million to be delivered beginning in February 1987,
the rest in 1988. Congress froze delivery on Feb. 29 to ensure the
United States did not subvert the regional peace plan signed by all
five Central American presidents, including Ortega.
</TEXT>
