<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChildAbductions 2ndLd-Writethru a0552 08-01 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Abductions, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Kidnapping Youngsters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT that molestation charge concerns one
child.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man awaiting sentencing for kidnapping
and raping a youngster has been charged with abducting two boys,
molesting one, and trying to abduct a girl during a 24-hour spree
through two states.
   Richard E. Gardner, 21, of Weymouth, Mass., had been free on
$3,000 bail while awaiting sentencing for the rape and kidnapping
of a boy in Hingham, Mass., said Rhode Island Attorney General
James O'Neil.
   ``I think this well demonstrates the need for bail reform,''
O'Neil said at a press conference Sunday.
   Gardner's mother, Sylvia, said he had received psychiatric
treatment as an outpatient and had gone to a counseling session
Thursday.
   ``There was no indication that anything was wrong,'' she said.
   Gardner was arrested Saturday night shortly after a 6-year-old
boy was returned to his home here. The boy had been pushed into a
stranger's car Friday evening while walking home from a library
with his older brother and a friend.
   Gardner was being held at the Adult Correctional Institutions in
Cranston. He was ordered held without bail at arraignment today in
Kent County District Court on charges including two counts of
kidnapping, burglary, child molestation, assault with a dangerous
weapon, possession of a stolen vehicle, reckless driving and
eluding arrest, said Detective Capt. Roger Burlingame. No plea was
entered, said Cmdr. John J. Mulhearn.
   The spree began early Friday when a man broke into a Warwick
house, pointed a flashlight in the eyes of a sleeping 10-year-old
boy, and forced the boy at knifepoint to leave with him, Burlingame
said. The boy's parents were sleeping. The child was molested and
then released to find his way home, Burlingame said.
   Later Friday, a man tried to abduct an 11-year-old girl in
Bellingham, Mass., police said. He grabbed the girl by the arm, but
she broke free, and he drove off.
   The man returned to Rhode Island, pulling the 6-year-old off the
sidewalk two blocks from his home, police said.
   That abduction triggered a search of the Warwick area by about
125 local, state and federal authorities, aided by civilian groups.
When the boy was returned, police chased the suspect who fled by
car and then on foot.
   Burlingame said all three children have identified Gardner. The
detective also said police in several other communities are
interested in questioning Gardner in connection with abductions
within the last six weeks.
   In the Hingham case, Gardner pleaded guilty June 2 to abducting
a 12-year-old boy in November 1987, tying him to a tree in a state
park and molesting him.
   Mrs. Gardner, who lives in Weymouth, said her son was ``a
confused child who was raped when he was 12.''
   Steve Hudson, 17, who lives near the Gardners in the
middle-class neighborhood near downtown Boston, called Gardner ``an
introverted person.''
   ``He always hung around by himself. He never had any friends his
own age, never any girlfriends or anything like that. No one his
own age ever went near him,'' Hudson said. ``He was like a social
outcast.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
