<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     08-01 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Confirms Arrest of Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Burma announced
Monday it had detained 10 people, including the country's most
outspoken dissident, to protect itself from attack.
   The announcement came less than a week after new leader Sein
Lwin, a hardline former general known for ruthless suppression of
dissent, came to power. He replaced Ne Win who ruled Burma for 26
years.
   Official Rangoon radio, monitored in Bangkok, said action would
be taken against prominent dissident Aung Gyi and nine other
detainees ``according to criminal law procedures.''
   ``In order to prevent an attack against the state, as
preventative measures, authorities concerned detained Aung Gyi and
his associates ... as from July 29, 1988,'' the broadcast said.
   It was the first official word of the arrests, which had been
reported last week by Western diplomats in Rangoon, Burma's
capital, and the U.S. State Department.
   The radio did not mention the fate of Associated Press
correspondent Sein Win and others the diplomats said also were
detained.
   Those listed by the radio mostly were retired military officers,
many of whom supported Ne Win during his early years in power. Most
are in their mid- to late 60s.
   Aung Gyi, 70, emerged this year as the most outspoken critic of
Burma's authoritarian regime through a series of letters decrying
economic and political conditions in the country.
   He singled out new leader Sein Lwin for ``turning a blind eye''
to gross human rights abuses during bloody student riots in March
in which more than 100 people are believed to have been killed.
   Sein Lwin, chief of the ruling Burma Socialist Program party and
the country's president, is widely believed to have commanded the
troops that suppressed the student riots.
   Aung Gyi, giving gruesome details of rapes and beatings, claimed
that 283 people died.
   A private businessman, Aung Gyi was once allied with Ne Win and
was regarded as his possible successor. But the two disagreed over
economic policy and the more pragmatic, liberal Aung Gyi resigned
from the government in 1963. He was subsequently jailed.
   The state radio broadcast identified the other detainees as Kyi
Han, Tun Win, Ba Shwe, Khin Nyo, Kyi Maung, Tun Shwe, Chit Ko Ko,
Aung Win and Zaw Win.
   Retired colonels Kyi Muang and Khin Nyo were in Ne Win's
Revolutionary Council after he seized power in 1962. Kyi Maung left
Ne Win's government in 1963 and Khin Nyo was fired in 1965.
   Han Kyi has once served as military attache in Washington and as
ambassador to Manila. Ba Shwe is an ex-ambassador to India.
   Diplomatic sources said that Aung Shwe, a former general who
once served as ambassador to Australia, also was held.
   Rangoon was reported quiet Monday, but leaflets circulated by
student groups called for a nationwide anti-government strike Aug.
8, Western diplomatic sources said.
   The sources, who asked not to be further identified, said some
of the leaflets came from the All Burma Universities Students
Democratic League, which has demanded the removal of Sein Lwin and
the release of student detainees.
   Virtually all the country's academic institutions were closed
after the last student riots in June. They are scheduled to reopen
in mid-August.
   The U.S. Embassy in Burma, meanwhile, reportedly made an
official inquiry Monday into the status of AP correspondent Sein
Win, who diplomats said was being held with the others at Insein
prison on the outskirts of Rangoon.
   Sein Win, 66, once a publisher of the English-language newspaper
The Guardian, was awarded the Golden Pen of Freedom by the
Paris-based International Federation of Journalists in 1963 for his
work in fostering a free press in Burma. He was jailed for three
years in the 1960s along with thousands of other political
prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
