<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlienTrial     08-01 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alien Trial,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Arguments Begin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor told jurors today the case
involving a Lutheran minister and a free-lance journalist is not
about the sanctuary movement or freedom of the press.
   Instead, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Rhonda Backinoff, it is a
case involving the exploitation of two pregnant Salvadoran women
who came to the United States seeking a better life. The issues of
sanctuary or the First Amendment were only smokescreens raised by
the defendants to protect themselves, she said.
   Ms. Backinoff outlined the prosection's evidence today as she
presented her final arguments. Defense attorneys were to give
closing statements later today.
   ``Why the defendants did what they did is really not an issue
here,'' she said. ``The bottom line is the immigration law was
avoided.''
   U.S. District Judge John Conway on Friday denied defense motions
to dismiss the case against the Rev. Glen Remer-Thamert, 44, and
Demetria Martinez, 28.
   Ms. Martinez faces one count of conspiracy to violate
immigration laws and one count each of transporting and inducing
Ines Campos-Anzora and Cecelia Elias-Alegria to enter the United
States. Remer-Thamert faces one count of conspiracy and two counts
each of transporting, harboring and inducing the women to enter the
United States.
   Ms. Backinoff told the jurors that Remer-Thamert and Ms.
Martinez conspired to bring the women into the United States
illegally in August 1986.
   She said Remer-Thamert bought the women's tickets to Chihuahua,
Mexico, by airplane and to Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, by train. She
said both Remer-Thamert and Ms. Martinez met them in Juarez and
both were present when Remer-Thamert arranged for the women to be
taken illegally into El Paso, Texas.
   Ms. Backinoff also said both defendants were present on the trip
by car from El Paso to Albuquerque.
   Remer-Thamert has testified he believed former Gov. Toney
Anaya's proclamation declaring New Mexico a sanctuary state would
allow him to bring the women into the country without visas.
   The prosecutor said Ms. Martinez never wrote about the case.
   Ms. Martinez, who writes religion articles for the Albuquerque
Journal and other publications, has said she was present as a
reporter. She said she never wrote about the women because she
began to fear that could jeopardize the safety of the women or of
their families in El Salvador.
   Ms. Backinoff said the women were used as props by the
defendants to support their own beliefs about Central America.
   She also said the defendants never intended for the women to
remain in the United States. She said a contract between the women
and a Salvadoran attorney called for them to give up their children
for adoption and return to El Salvador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
