<DOCNO> AP880801-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     08-01 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Proposes Contacts With North to Ease Tension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea on Monday proposed
preliminary contacts with North Korea to set up a joint
parliamentary session that would draft a non-aggression pact and
other tension-easing measures.
   National Assembly speaker Kim Chae-sun said in a letter
addressed to his North Korean counterpart, Yang Hyung-sup, that the
working talks be held next week in Panmunjom, a border village
about 35 miles north of Seoul.
   Also on Monday, radical students tried unsuccessfully to deliver
another letter to North Korea as part of their plan to march to the
border Aug. 15 for separate talks with northern students on
national unification.
   In his letter, sent to North Korea through Panmunjom, Kim said:
``We hope you will respond affirmatively to our proposal for
holding representatives' talks as soon as possible.'' North Korea
has not responded.
   The South Korean letter came after two North Korean proposals
last month calling for a joint session of the two countries'
legislatures to draft a non-aggression pact and to discuss North
Korea's possible participation in the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 Olympic Games
in Seoul.
   In a letter delivered July 21, North Korea proposed that the
parliaments hold the joint session by the end of this month. In a
second letter, sent five days later, North Korea said the joint
session should also discuss Pyongyang's bid to be a co-host of the
Olympics.
   North Korea suggested that both sides skip the working sessions
and convene a full parliamentary session in the capital of
Pyongyang, but Seoul officials said preliminary talks are needed to
set an agenda and discuss other details.
   South Korean officials said North Korea's demand to be a co-host
of the Olympics could be a stumbling block, but said they want to
open contact.
   Officials in Seoul, who have expressed concern that North Korea
might resort to terrorism to disrupt the Olympics, said privately
that resumption of contacts between the two sides would help ensure
the safety of the Olympics.
   North Korea has said it would boycott the Olympics unless it is
allowed to be a co-host. The International Olympic Committee has
rejected the North Korean demand, saying the Olympics are awarded
to one city and cannot be shared.
   An unknown number of students left Seoul on Monday for Panmunjom
to deliver a letter to their North Korean counterparts concerning
the proposed Aug. 15 talks.
   A spokesman for the group said in Seoul the students were
determined to deliver the letter in the village, which is
off-limits to civilians.
   Authorities deployed about 2,000 police around bus and train
stations on the Seoul-Panmunjom route and checked travelers going
to the border area. No arrests were made.
   An attempt by students to march to the border June 10 also was
blocked by police.
   Communist North Korea and South Korea have remained bitter
rivals since the country was partitioned by the United States and
the Soviet Union at the end of World War II. The division was
followed by the Korean War of 1950-53.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
