<DOCNO> AP880801-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-01 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT OLIVER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aldona and Diane Zilinskas have led
lookalike lives as twins for 37 years. So when Aldona decided to
get a nose job, Diane did, too.
   ``I could see I had no alternative except to persuade Diane to
do it, too,'' Aldona said. ``She was hesitant at first. ... I had
to talk to her like a twin. So I said, `No fear. No hesitancy.
Don't even think about doing it Diane. We're going into surgery
together.'''
   The Zilinskas underwent plastic surgery March 4 at Pittsburgh's
Shadyside Hospital, according to Monday's Pittsburgh Press.
   The women, who live at home with their father, are pharmacists
who work at the Veterans Administration Hospital in Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's an age-old remedy for a 5-year-old with
behavior problems: Pack him up and ship him off to boarding school.
Maybe he'll monkey around less _ or more.
   That's what the Dallas Zoo did in 1987 with Kanda, a lowland
gorilla who was having trouble after his mother died while giving
birth to him.
   Kanda was shipped off to the Cheyenne Mountain Zoo in Colorado
Springs, Colo., to learn how to act more like a gorilla, instead of
aping the humans who had been hand-raising him.
   Reports from Colorado, where Kanda lives with three other
gorillas, are encouraging, Dallas primate keeper Luther Punch said
Sunday.
   ``He integrated into that group especially well,'' said Karen
Murray, marketing and development director for the Colorado zoo.
``He used to walk up on his legs. Now he is not doing it as
frequently.''
   But Kanda won't be coming home on holiday soon. Colorado
officials expect to keep him until he reaches maturity at age 10.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years ago, a boy
vacationing with his family on an island near Nassau stuffed a note
into a champagne bottle and dropped it in the Atlantic Ocean.
   Last week, Nick Biddle got a reply to his message, from a
60-year-old Briton who found the broken bottle on a beach in
southern Wales.
   Nick's bottle had had his name and address inside and this
message for the finder: ``Please, when you find this, could you
write me back?''
   Alan Bennett was vacationing near The Mumbles, a coastal town in
southern Wales about 60 miles west of Bristol, England, when he
found the bottle. In a straight line, that's a distance of more
than 4,400 miles.
   ``I was very surprised to find the bottle had traveled such a
long way,'' the retired British Airways employee said in a
telephone interview Sunday. ``I thought the least that I could do
was write this gentleman back.''
   ``Dear Sir (Nick),'' his letter began. ``Whilst walking on the
beach one morning, I saw in a rock pool an old champagne bottle
which, I imagine, must have been five or six years old judging by
the marine growth it had collected.
   ``I can only assume that it was possibly a young boy's treasure
bottle, so I am writing to let you know it has been found after all
this time even though sadly it had to be broken.
   ``Yours truly, A. Bennett.''
   Nick, now 10, said he never forgot about the bottle and was
thrilled to get a response.
   ``I always had it on my mind, but when I heard about the letter,
I got really excited,'' said Nick, a fifth-grader at Gulf Beaches
Elementary School.
   Nick plans to write back to his new pen pal, who lives in the
Welsh town of Treharris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
