<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewImage     08-01 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Image,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marketing Company Phasing In A New Carol Wright
^With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They're making a new woman out of Carol
Wright.
   Wright is the fictional character whose cameo picture appears on
packets of manufacturers' coupons mailed to millions of U.S.
households each year.
   A consumer survey found that she appeared outdated, so Donnelly
Marketing Inc., the direct marketing agency that created her, is
gradually transforming her 19-year-old look into something more
contemporary.
   ``They (consumers) said she looked like Beaver Cleaver's mother,
that she was too perfect in every way, and that she probably did
windows while wearing an apron and pearls,'' said Joe Fenton,
director of marketing for the Carol Wright coupon program.
   Fenton said consumers thought Wright looked old-fashioned; her
hairstyle was outdated, for example, and the wide collar of her
blouse gave away her age.
   Donnelly Marketing has commissioned a series of new portraits to
bring her into the 1980s.
   The portraits, to be phased in between now and November, will
make gradual changes in Wright's appearance, including darker hair,
a new hairstyle, and slight variations in her eyes, earrings and
neckline.
   Fenton said the overall effect is to present a ``modern woman
concerned about her career as well as about her husband and
children.''
</TEXT>
