<HEAD>Town Begins Program to Get Rid of Stray Cats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RESTORES dropped first reference to councilman in last graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HARPERS FERRY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stray cats are wandering through
town using lawns for litter boxes and clawing through thin walls,
prompting officials to set traps for the pesky felines.
   The only cats that will be excused once caught are those with
registrations and tags, Mayor Bill Brawley said Monday.
   Unregistered cats caught in the box-like traps will be taken to
the Animal Welfare Society. They will be eligible for adoption, but
killed if no one takes them.
   ``We gave people a deadline of (Sunday) to get their cats
tagged,'' Brawley said. ``They next couple of days we'll be setting
out traps and baiting them with cat food. There's no harm to the
cat at all.''
   Councilman Robert Johnson said the increasing number of cats has
created a nuisance for the town's 361 residents.
</TEXT>
