<DOCNO> AP880801-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SellingWarhol Bjt   08-01 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Selling Warhol, Bjt,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warhol Products, Including Clothes And Jewelry, To Hit Stores Next
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If, as Andy Warhol said, everyone will be famous
for 15 minutes, they'll be able to time their moments in the sun
with a Warhol-designed watch, record the event in a
Warhol-decorated diary and wear clothes inspired by the late pop
artist.
   A line of Warhol products ranging from business planning
calendars to watches costing several thousand dollars should appear
in retail stores early next year, said Roger Schlaifer, president
of Atlanta-based Schlaifer Nance & Co., which owns the marketing
rights to Warhol and his work.
   Schlaifer, whose company until earlier this year marketed
Cabbage Patch Kids dolls, said the Warhol products are still being
developed. But he said they would include clothing, bedding,
jewelry and paper products, such as calendars, posters and diaries.
   ``We're targeting a young, thinking audience where the Warhol
attitude and image is reflected,'' Schlaifer said.
   Some of the items will bear Warhol's likeness or that of his
work, while others will aim to capture the spirit of the artist,
Schlaifer said.
   Moderately priced items will be sold in ``better department and
specialty stores,'' Schlaifer said, while the expensive products
will be availble only through more exclusive outlets.
   Schlaifer, who commissioned Warhol to do a series of portraits
of the Cabbage Patch Kids, said he proposed to the artist a massive
marketing effort in 1985 and made a formal presentation a year
later.
   The talks slowed down but were revived only a week before Warhol
died on Feb. 22, 1987, at the age of 58, Schlaifer said. The deal
giving Schlaifer the marketing rights was finalized later with the
Warhol estate, he said.
   Schlaifer said Warhol, a former ad man who well known for his
silver-wigged celebrity status as well as for his works of art, was
enthusiastic about the idea.
   ``With his sense of commerce, and what we outlined in terms of
exposure, he was very excited,'' Schlaifer said. ``Andy Warhol was
unique in how he designed himself. In a way, he made himself as
unique as his art.''
   Despite Warhol's flair for publicity and his unconventional
approach to art, Schlaifer acknowledged there may be criticism of
such blatant commercial use of the artist's work.
   But he defended his plans, saying Warhol was not averse to
commercialism and noting that even the most respected museums have
gift shops.
   ``Virtually anything anyone does is subject to criticism,'' he
said. ``The question is, is it appropriate? Andy had a strong
commercial instinct.
   ``All museums have huge product enterprises that help support
the museum and educate the public. I'm not sure where that
criticism has validity, other than the position that art should
only be in the museums or in books.''
   Schlaifer said Warhol did not limit himself to creating museum
pieces. Warhol also made movies, started ``Interview'' magazine and
designed album covers for a number of rock and roll bands.
   ``He was commercial in a non-commercial way _ that was the
inherent irony in everything Warhol did,'' Schlaifer said.
   Schlaifer is banking on continuing fascination with Warhol and
his work.
   ``There's sort of an automatic excitement with anything
connected with the Warhol name,'' he said.
   He noted that an auction earlier this year of artwork and other
items owned by Warhol drew crowds and large sums of money, and said
displays of Warhol art, particularly a traveling exhibit planned
next year by New York's Museum of Modern Art, should heighten
interest.
   ``If anything, the acceptance is higher now than when we
originally proposed this,'' Schlaifer said. ``He's a major artist
by any definition. He gets more press dead than most celebrities do
alive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Carlucci Bjt   08-01 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci, Bjt,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Tells Kremlin Brass He Doubts Adoption of Defensive
Doctrine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci told 200 top
Soviet officers Monday he has seen no evidence for the Kremlin's
claim that it has adopted a defensive military strategy.
   At the start of a four-day visit expected to offer a glimpse of
secret Soviet equipment and bases, Carlucci spent two hours with
Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov and addressed senior officers at
the General Staff's Voroshilov Academy.
   About 1,800 miles away in Central Asia, four missiles were blown
apart to begin the Soviet program of destroying more than 1,700
weapons under the superpower treaty banning intermediate-range
nuclear rockets, the official news agency Tass reported.
   Carlucci called the destruction of the missiles a ``great
event.'' Tass said the short-range missiles, known in the west as
SS-12s, were destroyed in the presence of U.S. inspectors at the
Saryozek test range in Kazakhstan.
   At the end of the day, Carlucci told reporters his talks with
Yazov ``went very well.'' He praised the academy staff for showing
him the classrooms and laboratories where Soviet military strategy
is developed.
   The tone of his speech to the officers was one of doubt about
the extent to which the Soviet military machine has been redirected
toward defense.
   Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, the Soviet chief of staff, and
other senior officers say Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev is
switching to defense as a military doctrine from the traditional
predominance of offensive weapons.
   ``We have difficulty in reconciling a defensive doctrine with
what we see in Soviet force structure and operational strategy as
an emphasis on the offensive,'' Carlucci said in his speech. ``We
see no shift of emphasis to the kind of forces traditionally
associated with defense.''
   ``We also have difficulty reconciling the U.S.S.R.'s pledge not
to be the first to use nuclear weapons with your continuing
emphasis on heavy ICBMs, such as the SS-18,'' he said. Carlucci
described the Soviet armory as ``a capability more compatible with
a military doctrine that emphasizes pre-emptive nuclear strikes.''
   He criticized the Soviet government for not making military
spending public and said Western analysts estimate 15 percent to 17
percent of the nation's wealth goes to defense. The current U.S.
military budget is 5.9 percent of the gross national product.
   ``No one begrudges you the need for a strong and capable army,''
Carlucci said. ``What troubles us is when the U.S.S.R. continues to
develop forces far in excess of what it needs for purposes of its
own defense.''
   He said the U.S. space-based defense project, formally named the
Strategic Defense Initiative and popularly called ``Star Wars,'' is
a step toward greater stability that ``does not represent the
slightest threat to the U.S.S.R.''
   In a 20-minute question-and-answer session after the speech,
Carlucci defended the size of the U.S. Navy and the Pentagon's
doctrine of deterrence through adequate armed forces and weaponry.
   To reporters, he expressed pleasure that his schedule would
include access to Soviet defense installations and equipment, such
as the secret Blackjack bomber and the Sevastopol naval base on the
Crimean Peninsula.
   ``It's a unique experience for a U.S. defense secretary,'' he
said on arrival in Moscow. ``The American people through me can see
what the Soviet military is doing and can learn about their
attitudes and doctrine.''
   Carlucci said he believed he and Yazov could be more candid with
each other than other high-level officials because ``we are
soldiers.''
   They first met in Bern, Switzerland, in March and renewed the
acquaintance during the Reagan-Gorbachev summit at the end of May.
Both have called their active schedule of meetings as an
opportunity to ease tensions and solve problems.
   Among those traveling with Carlucci are Ron Lehman, assistant
secretary of defense, and representatives of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff and State Department.
   The Americans will see the Taman army base and Kubinka air
field, both near Moscow, on Tuesday. They are to visit the Crimea
on Wednesday and leave for Turkey the next day after touring a ship
of the Black Sea fleet at Sevastopol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
