<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two California men have agreed to stop
claiming that a solution of hydrogen peroxide that they sell can
prevent cancer and ease arthritis pain, the U.S. Postal Service
announced.
   The Postal Service said Kurt W. Donsbach, founder of DRK
Supplements of Huntington Beach, and his nephew, Richard Donsbach,
had signed an agreement promising to stop falsely representing
their product in mail-order sales.
   The agency said the elder Donsbach heads a group called National
Health Federation. He visits health conventions and writes books
and articles promoting hydrogen peroxide, an antiseptic sold by DRK
Supplements, it said.
   According to postal officials, the Donsbachs promoted sales of
their product with claims that it could prevent or stop the spread
of cancer and that it provides relief from arthritis pain.
