<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Koch     08-01 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Koch,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson, Koch Say They're Willing to Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson and New York Mayor Edward I. Koch
spoke by telephone Monday and agreed to meet in an effort to
resolve their differences and unite the Democratic Party behind
Michael Dukakis in the fall election.
   ``I have always kept open the door to communications. I believe
that people should talk,'' said Jackson, who lost New York's
Democratic primary in April and subsequently lost the nomination.
   Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, a Jackson supporter
and now co-chair of the Dukakis campaign in New York state, said
the meeting would be ``sometime in August'' but is ``not likely to
be this week.''
   Dinkins said the meeting would involve himself, Jackson, Koch,
New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, Rep. Charles Rangel, and Stanley Hill, a
black labor leader in New York. He said it likely would take place
in Cuomo's Manhattan office.
   Koch criticized Jackson during the primary race, saying Jews
would be ``crazy'' to vote for Jackson, who supports Palestinian
self-determination.
   Jackson said Koch called him at his Chicago home early Monday
``and said he would like to meet.''
   Koch later issued a statement saying, ``I agree that in the
interest of party unity and the election of Michael Dukakis, it
would be good to meet with Jesse Jackson.''
   ``The Democratic Party is built on the premise that people with
different ideologies can come together under one tent. That's what
gets us elected.''
   But Koch added, ``I don't in any way recant my policy
differences with Jesse Jackson. They are there.... I hope to work
in support of Dukakis and then we'll continue the ideological
battle at another time.''
   ``My feelings toward the mayor are always open and respectful,''
Jackson said of Koch. ``His toward me were very hostile.''
   Jackson said Koch ``used race and religion as a litmus test and
divided the city and helped to lower the moral tone of the
campaign.''
   Both Dinkins and Rangel have been mentioned as possible
opponents to Koch in his re-election bid next year.
   Koch said he was not trying to use Jackson to gain support among
blacks for his own mayoral campaign.
   ``I'm not in contention this year,'' Koch said. ``And if you
really believe as I do that it's important to have a Democrat in
the White House, you set aside those differences.''
   While Dinkins said he welcomed the meeting, he questioned its
impact on the Dukakis campaign.
   ``The Dukakis campaign and the Jackson camp have come together
pretty well in forging an integrated policy and campaign staff'' in
New York state, Dinkins said.
   The New York-based American Jewish Committee said it hoped the
meeting would help heal the rift between blacks and Jews.
   ``We are in favor of anything which would dampen tensions and
heighten communications between the two communities,'' said AJC
Program Director Gary Rubin.
   The meeting ``will make a step toward doing that and the degree
to which it would reduce tension, we would welcome it,'' he said.
   Cuomo, who helped arrange the meeting, said ``I think it is a
commendable thing for Jesse Jackson, who feels insulted and who was
insulted by what was said, to say, `OK, you insulted me. You hurt
me. But in the interests of a truth greater than me or you, I will
sit down with you. Because we have urgent problems. ... Because
Dukakis and Bentsen are the only ones committed to dealing with
those urgent problems.' ''
</TEXT>
