<HEAD>Composer Hamlisch Named to Arts Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marvin Hamlisch, a composer and pianist who is
a favorite of Nancy Reagan's and who frequently performs at the
White House, was named by President Reagan on Monday to be a member
of the National Council on the Arts.
   Hamlisch has written numerous scores for movies and Broadway
musicals, including ``They're Playing our Song'' and ``Chorus
Line,'' which won a Pulitzer Prize and a Tony Award. He frequently
has been the host of a broadcast concert series presented at the
White House.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Hamlisch would succeed novelist
Allen Drury on the arts council, the chief advisory arm of the
National Endowment for the Arts, the independent federal agency
that underwrites a wide variety of artists and arts institutions.
</TEXT>
