<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Givirtz     08-01 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Givirtz,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biblical Scholar, Teacher of Rabbis, Dead at 59</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanley Givirtz, a biblical scholar and
author who trained many rabbis, has died after a six-month bout
with cancer. He was 59.
   Givirtz, who died Friday, was a professor of biblical studies at
Hebrew Union College in Los Angeles, a rabbinical school for Reform
Judaism. He was well-known for his studies of ancient Near Eastern
languages and biblical Hebrew, said former classmate Dr. William
Bondareff, a University of Southern California psychiatry professor.
   ``He was an extraordinarily influential teacher of Hebrew and
probably responsible for the teaching of more rabbis in this
country than anyone else,'' Bondareff said.
   Givirtz, born in Brooklyn, New York, received his bachelor's
degree from Brooklyn College. He earned a Ph.D. at the University
of Chicago, where he taught from 1958 until 1972, when he joined
the faculty of the Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of
Religion here.
   In addition to teaching rabbinical students, Givirtz wrote a
book, ``Patterns in the Early Poetry of Israel,'' and had numerous
articles published in scholarly reviews.
   Givirtz is survived by his wife, Marianne; children Elihu, Sarah
and Aliza, and a sister, Frieda.
</TEXT>
