<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DeSillersFingerprints 1stLd-Writethru a0608 08-01 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers Fingerprints, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0608,0534</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to update with fingerprints not matching,
picking up at the 10th graf previous beginning ``The burglary.''
Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers was cleared Monday of any
connection with fingerprints found at the scene of a year-old
burglary at an elementary school in which $4,000 in donations for
her late son's liver transplant were stolen.
   The still unsolved theft generated an avalanche of publicity and
prompted President Reagan and others to donate a total of $689,000
for her son's three unsuccessful operations. After her son's death,
Ms. DeSillers was accused of misusing the funds.
   Fort Lauderdale police said last week they had received
unspecified information linking Mrs. DeSillers to the break-in, and
issued a search warrant for her fingerprints.
   She submitted to fingerprinting under protest Monday, and Fort
Lauderdale police quickly cleared her of any connection with a
print left in the school closet where the money was held, said
police spokesman Ott Cefkin.
   ``She is not a suspect and we have no physical evidence linking
her to the burglary,'' Cefkin said. ``But we would have been remiss
if we had not pursued it.''
   He refused to reveal what information led to the demand for
fingerprints, and said the investigation was continuing.
   Ms. DeSillers was not at home, but her attorney Roy Black said
he spoke to her after the police announcement.
   ``She was mad,'' said Black. ``She feels that she's been
humiliated and held up to scorn once again. There's a lot of people
out there now who think she stole that money.''
   Earlier Monday, a Dade County Circuit Court judge refused Ms.
DeSillers' request to block the police search warrant seeking her
fingerprints.
   ``We found enough probable cause to have a judge approve a
warrant,'' Assistant Dade State Attorney Richard Shiffrin said
after the hearing. ``There's probable cause to suspect her in
criminal activity.''
   The burglary at St. Anthon's Roman Catholic school in Fort
Lauderdale prompted people across the country to donate money for
the operations on her son, Ronnie.
   Among the $689,000 raised for the boy was a $1,000 donation from
President Reagan and his wife Nancy and a $200,000 gift from Miami
Beach millionaire Victor Posner.
   Fort Lauderdale police said a thief broke into a closet at the
accounting office of the school and took the money, which was
raised by Ronnie's classmates through bake sales, flower sales and
other fund-raisers. Most of the money was in change and small bills.
   Ronnie DeSillers died in April 1987 while awaiting a fourth
liver transplant at Pittsburgh's Children's Hospital. Ms. DeSillers
has refused to pay $262,000 in medical bills to Children's Hospital
in Pittsburgh, saying her son received improper care.
   A court-appointed caretaker of the donated funds said Ms.
DeSillers improperly used $200,000 of the money on luxury items
ranging from jewelry to a BMW sports car.
   On Thursday, a Dade circuit judge ruled that she is not entitled
to the remaining $240,000 of the donated money and that it should
instead pay medical bills, debts and help other needy ill children.
</TEXT>
