<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Swaggart     08-01 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swaggart Says Satan Behind Anti-Israeli Revolt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defrocked preacher Jimmy
Swaggart visited the birthplace of Jesus in the occupied West Bank
on Monday, and said the Palestinian uprising was the work of the
devil.
   Swaggart, who also toured a Jewish settlement, told The
Associated Press nothing could destroy Israel because the prophets
predicted its establishment.
   ``The prophets ... foretold of the nation of Israel once
becoming a state and the people coming back to Israel,'' Swaggart
said in Bethlehem, where he videotaped two 20-minute TV programs.
``God's arch enemy, Satan, does not want these prophecies to be
fulfilled and will do everything he can to end it and to cause
difficulties.
   ``That's how the political unrest enters in it today,'' he said,
referring to the nearly eight-month uprising in the occupied lands.
   Swaggart and his entourage then proceeded to Tekoa, a Jewish
settlement about nine miles south of Jerusalem, and got a taste of
the uprising when their black Mercedes limousine drove around a
burning tire that blocked the road.
   Jewish settler Bobby Brown received Swaggart and his wife,
Frances, on a vine-covered patio typical of the flourishing lush
settlement.
   Quoting from the Old Testament's Book of Amos, Brown told
Swaggart the Jewish settlers were reviving a land that had laid
barren and empty for thousands of years.
   ``Do you think this is a fulfillment of the prophecy?'' Swaggart
asked.
   ``I believe that,'' Brown said.``The work we're doing is God's
work.''
   Swaggart, who brought 350 followers to Israel at a time when
many tourists are shunning the country, has been welcomed with open
arms. But a columnist in the Hebrew Davar newspaper warned Monday
that Swaggart's support of Israel was a double-edged sword.
   According to Swaggart's theory, the state of Israel is merely a
vehicle to the coming of the Second Kingdom, when all Jews will
have to convert to Christianity, wrote columnist Yoram Perry.
   ``No, Jimmy Swaggart does not love us,'' Perry wrote.
``Certainly not love for its own sake.''
   Swaggart, who runs a television ministry that reaches 2 million
viewers from its base in Baton Rouge, La., stepped down from the
pulpit in February after admitting he sinned against his wife.
   A prostitute said he paid her to strip and perform lewd acts for
him during visits to a motel.
   The Lousiana Assemblies of God denomination revoked his ministry
credentials after he returned to the pulpit against their wishes in
May.
   Swaggart has refused to discuss the scandal except to say that
he has put it behind him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
