<DOCNO> AP880801-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     08-01 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Demand Truth About World War II Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Poles marking the 44th
anniversary of the Warsaw uprising against the Nazis demanded
Monday that the Soviet Union end its silence over alleged
atrocities against Poles during World War II.
   Speakers also called for less interference from Moscow and
demanded the right to hold free elections.
   ``Moscow has to realize that we fought on all fronts of the war,
but we still have not regained our freedom,'' said Wojciech
Ziembinski, an independent opposition activist.
   Crowds filled Warsaw's Powazki military cemetery to pay homage
to those who fell during the 63-day revolt against Nazi occupation.
   The Nazis crushed the uprising. More than 245,000 people were
killed and 85 percent of the city was destroyed.
   While scores of Poles lighted candles and laid flowers on the
graves of friends and family members, hundreds of others gathered
around a granite monument to Polish officers murdered in the Katyn
forest near the Soviet city of Smolensk.
   The massacre remains one of Poland's most bitter wartime
memories and a sore spot in its relations with the Soviet Union.
   The Soviets have never acknowledged responsibility for the
incident, in which 4,300 Polish military officers were shot to
death and left in a mass grave.
   Western historical sources indicate the Poles were murdered on
the orders of Soviet dictator Josef Stalin in the spring of 1940.
But official Soviet and Polish histories claim that the Nazis
killed them in 1941.
   A banner draped across the monument Monday read: ``Give us
truth, Katyn 1940.'' Later, a group of youths raised a banner which
read: ``Solidarity will prove the truth about Katyn.''
   Last year an official commission was established by the Polish
and Soviet governments to investigate the incident.
   To the disappointment of many Poles, Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev did not mention Katyn during a speech to the Polish
parliament in July. However, he did make a general pledge to
continue to pursue the elimination of gaps in official histories.
   Although the Katyn memorial was the emotional focus of Monday's
tribute, the gathering quickly turned political in tone.
   ``We want the renewal of Poland, but not for communism,'' said
Seweryn Jaworski, an activist of the outlawed Solidarity trade
union, in a reference to the government's reform plans.
   While none of the Solidarity leadership was visible at the Katyn
monument, the crowd repeatedly flashed the union's two-fingered
V-sign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
