<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Mafia     08-01 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Mafia,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detective Chief In Palermo Resigns, Deepening Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of police detectives in this
Sicilian capital resigned Monday, deepening a crisis in Italy's
battle against the Mafia.
   The resignation of Antonio Nicchi came two days after Italy's
top investigator of organized crime, Giovanni Falcone, and eight
fellow magistrates resigned from the ``anti-Mafia pool'' in Sicily,
asking to be transferred.
   A prominent Sicilian prosecutor, Paolo Borsellino, two weeks ago
charged that Mafia investigations were being blocked by top
judicial officials, an inefficient and chaotic police department,
and an indifferent state.
   ``In Palermo you can't work in peace any more,'' Nicchi told
journalists Monday.
   Borsellino said detectives had not produced any significant
reports on the Mafia since 1982.
   But Nicchi told the Palermo newspaper L'Ora: ``I've been in this
office since 1985 and I have presented a dozen reports, on the
Mafia, on drugs, on homicides, even on the new balance of power
between the (crime) families.''
   Borsellino's declarations to journalists prompted President
Francesco Cossiga to order the ministries of Justice and Interior
and the Superior Council of Magistrates, which oversees judges, to
investigate problems in the anti-Mafia unit in Sicily.
   On Monday, politicians and newspapers called on the state to pay
more attention to the war on organized crime.
   ``People ought to know that judges alone cannot fight the Mafia
phenomenon and that the battle against the Mafia will never be won
without an adequate commitment from political forces and in first
place those of the government,'' said the president of the National
Association of Judges, Raffaele Bertoni.
</TEXT>
