<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a r AM-GoldenDome     08-01 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Golden Dome,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Notre Dame Regilding Famed Golden Dome and Statue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Notre Dame's famed
golden dome is getting a facelift this summer with the painstaking
application of micro-thin layers of gold leaf.
   The administration building dome and its 19-foot cast iron
statue of the Virgin Mary have been campus landmarks since 1882,
when the building was erected to replace one destroyed by fire.
   The statue has been gilded at least four times, but never
stripped down to the cast iron before any reguilding, said Ronald
Gruenke, a restoration export with the Wisconsin company handling
the $300,000, seven-week project.
   ``It had a surface like alligator skin _ crackled and scaled,''
he said.
   The workers have a perspective on the statue not available to
those on the ground, 158 feet below.
   ``Mary's kneecaps come up to about eye height, and her
outstreched hands are each the size of a table,'' said worker
Robert Pettis.
   For the dome, this latest regilding will be the ninth, and the
first since 1961.
</TEXT>
