<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lyng-Drought     08-01 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lyng-Drought,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Head Says Farmers Could See Financial Relief By October</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought-stricken farmers may get some
federal aid by the October harvest, but only if Congress passes a
relief bill in the next two weeks and gets it past President
Reagan, Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng said Monday.
   Separate versions of the bill, which will cost between $4
billion and $6 billion to implement, have passed in both houses of
Congress, but Lyng warned that the Senate version contains some
provisions he considers extravagant.
   ``I am hopeful they will be able to reconcile their differences
and take out some of the more extravagant provisions that do not
really apply to those farmers that have suffered in the drought,''
Lyng said at a news conference before addressing the annual meeting
of the Soil and Water Conservation Society.
   If that reconciliation comes in the next two weeks, financial
assistance could be on its way to farmers ``close to the first of
October. I would hope that we could do it around the time that
would coincide with the normal harvest,'' he said.
   Lyng said a joint conference committee is to meet Wednesday to
discuss both versions of the bill.
   He said he considers amendments in the House version alloting
assistance to farmers who produce their own feed for their
livestock more feasible than the Senate version, which broadens aid
to include livestock and poultry farmers who do not grow their own
feed.
   Lyng said he would not disclose what his own recommendations to
Reagan will be, nor would he predict if the measure will be vetoed.
   Lyng also said recent rain has helped the cornbelt, but not
enough.
   ``The economic damage is very severe in the cornbelt, unlike
anything we have ever seen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
