<DOCNO> AP880801-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1751EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SobrietyCheckLanes     08-01 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sobriety Check Lanes,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says Anti-Drunk Checklanes Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roadblocks to check drivers for signs of
intoxication are ineffective and unconstitutional, the Michigan
Court of Appeals ruled Monday in upholding a lower court's ruling
against the state.
   ``While the goals of the sobriety checkpoint program are
laudable, the program fails to qualify as a reasonable seizure
under the Fourth Amendment,'' the three-judge appeals panel wrote
in a unanimous opinion.
   The state attorney general's office did not immediately have a
comment about the ruling or any plans for further appeals. The
Michigan Supreme Court in 1975 refused to rule on the
constitutionality of systematic roadblock stops.
   Monday's ruling upholds the conclusions of Wayne County Circuit
Judge Michael Stacey, who issued a permanent injunction stopping
the roadblocks on the grounds that they violated both the federal
and state constitutions.
   Howard Simon, executive director of the ACLU's Michigan chapter,
praised Stacey's 60-page opinion as ``the most extensive,
definitive, best-reasoned analysis in the country of the alleged
effectiveness of sobriety roadblocks and the extent to which they
intrude upon the civil liberties of innocent motorists.''
   ``I'm glad it was upheld,'' he said. ``Now the state should do
what we suggested all the time, namely get down to the business of
cracking down on drunken driving without violating the rights of
innocent motorists.''
   The program devised by state police followed a blueprint drafted
from check lane laws in 37 other states and the District of
Columbia. Its prime model was Maryland's program, and the opinion
noted the testimony of a Maryland State Police lieutenant who said
checkpoints there yielded few drunken driving arrests.
   Gov. James Blanchard, who pushed through the program and made it
one of his top priorities in 1986, would not comment until his
staff had time to review the decision, spokesman Tom Scott said.
   The issue of anti-drunk checkpoints has come up in courts in
about half of the states with mixed results, according to the
Michigan appellate opinion.
   State courts in Virginia, Illinois, Florida and Massachusetts
have upheld the roadblocks while they have been struck down in
Oregon, Washington and New Hampshire.
   The U.S. Supreme Court hasn't ruled on anti-drunk roadblocks but
implied in a 1979 case that they are acceptable. The high court
said police may not selectively stop drivers who are not suspected
of breaking any law, but mentioned roadblocks among possible
acceptable alternatives.
   In 1986, the high court refused to hear arguments in a case
challenging Virginia's roadblocks. That decision had the effect of
letting Virginia continue the checkpoints.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
