<HEAD>Four-Year Term on Guilty Plea to Voluntary Manslaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former bodyguard for the rap music group
Run-D.M.C. was sentenced to four years in prison Monday for
involuntary manslaughter in the death of a man at a concert two
years ago.
   Garfield Brown originally was charged with murder but pleaded
guilty to the lesser offense of manslaughter in the death of Alex
Baldwin, 21.
   Police said several fights broke out during a Run-D.M.C. concert
at Selland Arena in Fresno on Aug. 15, 1986, and Brown and two
other bodyguards left the stage to help restore order.
   Brown was charged with throwing Baldwin to the concrete floor
and kicking him. Baldwin died of head injuries two weeks later, and
Brown was arrested in New York City.
   Superior Court Judge Steve Vartabedian ordered that the
manslaughter term begin after Brown completes a nine-year prison
sentence in New York for robbery and burglary.
