<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r n AM-DrugProsecutors     08-01 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Prosecutors,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Cite Little Success in Drug War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of 181 local prosecutors interviewed by a
weekly legal affairs newspaper said they are having little or no
impact in the war against drugs, despite higher spending, the paper
reported Monday.
   The prosecutors called for more money for their efforts and
rated some federal drug-fighting policies as little help, the
National Law Journal said.
   It said a quarter of the prosecutors favored decriminalizing
marijuana.
   Sixty-five percent of the prosecutors who were interviewed said
their resources were inadequate to fight drugs. As well as more
money, most called for laws making it easier to seize property from
drug offenders.
   But more than seven in 10 of those interviewed called the
federal government's ``zero tolerance'' program ``not very
important'' or ``not important,'' the Journal said. That program
includes moves to seize property in which federal agents find even
a minuscule amount of illegal drugs.
   Dean St. Dennis, a Justice Department spokesman, said Monday he
believed prosecutors would favor the zero-tolerance program if they
knew fully about it. He also said the department strongly opposed
marijuana decriminalization.
   The Journal said it interviewed the chief prosecutors or their
top drug deputies in 181 of the 250 largest local jurisdictions in
the country this month. The local prosecutors were promised
confidentiality. Statewide and federal prosecutors were not
interviewed.
   When asked about the effect of their work, six in 10 of those
interviewed said they had very little or no impact in reducing the
illegal drug supply; about as many said they had little or no
impact raising the price of drugs; and 57 percent said they had
little or no impact deterring drug use.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
