<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MIAIdentified     08-01 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MIA Identified,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Air Force Colonel are Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army laboratory in Hawaii has positively
identified the remains of an Air Force colonel from Utah missing
from the Vietnam war, the Pentagon said Monday.
   The remains of Col. Mark L. Stephensen were among a group of 27
repatriated to the United States on April 6.
   Three of the remains from that group were identified earlier
this summer by the Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu.
The others are still undergoing analysis.
   Stephensen was flying an RF-4C reconnaissance jet over North
Vietnam when he disappeared on April 29, 1967. At the time, he was
36 years old and listed his home of record as Salt Lake City.
   ``The remains will depart Hickam Air Force Base in Hawaii with a
full military honors ceremony on Tuesday and travel to Travis Air
Force Base, Calif., for their final journey home,'' a Pentagon
statement said.
   With the latest identification, 2,393 Americans continue to be
listed as missing in Indochina as a result of the Vietnam war, of
whom 1,757 are listed as missing in Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 162 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the
laboratory since the end of the war.
</TEXT>
