<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Maugg     08-01 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Maugg,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wine Cooler Adman Happy to Keep Quiet</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   LONGVIEW, Wash. _ Most actors make their living as smooth
talkers, but as the silent partner of the Bartles & Jaymes wine
cooler ads, Dick Maugg earns his fee by keeping his mouth shut.
   The silent act is a key ingredient of an ad campaign that helped
establish the Gallo Winery product in the market and brought Maugg
``more money than I ever thought I'd make.''
   In a recent interview, Maugg said his laid-back appearance
belies the tense atmosphere that surrounds each taping of the
folksy commercials.
   ``They take a lot of time to do very little. It can get
nerve-racking standing around so much,'' he said.
   Maugg is spending part of his earnings on a Kalama River cabin
he's building near the Western Washington city of Longview where he
was born and raised.
   Maugg joined David Rufkhar _ who has the speaking lines _ on the
wine cooler's pitch team just 10 days before the first ads were
shot.
   A San Francisco ad agency went to Maugg's home where they ``put
a baseball cap on me, started shooting film and told me to say,
`Hello there,' a couple times,'' he said.
   He lost his lines, but gained a spot in 180 different
commercials, of which about 70 have been broadcast.
</TEXT>
