<DOCNO> AP880801-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anglicans     08-01 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anglicans,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglican Bishops Reject Call To Keep from Consecrating Women
Bishops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's Anglican bishops on
Monday rejected a call to refrain from consecrating women bishops
and accepted a compromise resolution that such elevation of women
should not divide the Anglican Communion.
   On a show of hands, the bishops voted 423-28 with 19 abstentions
to maintain links with any of their 27 self-governing churches
which consecrate a woman bishop, even if they disagree.
   The U.S. Episcopalians and the Canadian and New Zealand
Anglicans say they may consecrate a woman bishop by the end of this
year.
   The resolution preserving the unity of the 70 million-member
Anglican Communion was drafted by conference participants who
considered it for most of the first two weeks of the three-week
Lambeth Conference.
   It is the bishops' first gathering in 10 years.
   On a secret ballot, the bishops voted 277-187 against a
resolution proposed by Archbishop of Sydney Donald Robinson that
the churches should ``refrain from consecrating a woman as bishop''
to avoid further damage over the issue of women priests and bishops.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual leader of the
Church of England and leader of the Anglican Communion, said after
the two votes that despite differences of opinion, the conference
acted in a spirit of unity.
   Runcie said before the vote that however the count went, he
agreed with its recommendation that he appoint a commission to
prepare guidelines for relations among the churches once women
bishops are appointed. He said his commission would ``start
meetings well before the end of this year.''
   Runcie said of the compromise resolution, ``It wasn't a fudge _
it was very carefully worked out respecting of differences and the
determination to live together. ... Tell me what other way you hold
a communion together when it is deeply divided about something
which is of great importance to some people and of little
importance to others in the mission of the church.''
   Robinson, metropolitan of New South Wales, said his resolution
simply invited the conference to express its mind.
   ``It is contrary to the explicit teaching of the New Testament
that women be given responsibility for the authority of the
Scriptures in the congregation,'' he said.
   But Presiding Bishop Edmond L. Browning of the U.S. Episcopal
Church, which has ordained hundreds of women priests in the past 11
years, differed.
   ``Restraint is not a true option,'' Browning said. ``When we
heard or read that it is only a matter of time before women will be
elected bishops in U.S. Episcopal Church, this is not a statement
of defiance. It is simply looking into our future as a province
(church) based on our past and our present.
   ``Ordained women are already a feature of our church life. Our
people have been blessed by the priestly ministry of ordained women
for more than a decade. Therefore, the people of our diocese move
ahead toward calling women to be bishops in a way that is authentic
to our experience.''
   Many of the Anglican bishops, clergy and laity oppose ordaining
women. About 1,200 women priests have been ordained by a minority
of the churches, mostly by the U.S. Episcopalians. Opponents call
the practice contrary to Scripture and tradition. They say they
could not accept a woman bishop though they might eventually accept
women priests.
   Bishops are regarded as the successors of the Apostles of Jesus
Christ. All were men.
   Bishop William Pwaisiho of Malaita in the Pacific territory of
Melanesia, denounced ordaining women as ``Satanic.''
   ``I think you are not listening to us _ and my color doesn't
help, either,'' said Pwaisiho, who is black.
   ``No woman should be consecrated for the sake of the unity we
seek,'' appealed another African prelate, Bishop Benjamin Nwankiti
of Owerri, Nigeria.
   But a black prelate from Washington, D.C., Bishop John T.
Walker, said white men who had long prevented blacks from becoming
bishops were now using the same arguments against women.
   ``In Christ there is neither male nor female,'' Walker said.
</TEXT>
