<HEAD>Embargoed For Release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Slams Dukakis Talk Of Changing National Direction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan asserted Monday that
``America is in a new era of opportunity'' and said the voters will
decide whether to switch direction by electing Democrat Michael
Dukakis as president.
   Without mentioning Dukakis' name, Reagan, in a speech prepared
for a fund-raiser for Sen. William V. Roth,R-Del., tweaked the
Massachusetts Democrat for declaring in his nomination acceptance
speech that ``the Reagan era'' is ending.
   ``Does he want to end the era of lower tax rates and higher real
income for families, record numbers of jobs, low inflation and
interest rates, steady growth and respect, not just lip-service for
families,'' Reagan asked.
   ``The American people may have a thing or two to say about
that.''
   Reagan said ``that same candidate'' claims he has balanced 10
budgets in a row.
   But the president said that the Dukakis budget for Massachusetts
``includes almost a half a billion dollars of new borrowing,
drawing reserves and tapping pension funds, and the kind of
creative accounting that nearly sent New York City to the poor
house a few years ago.''
   ``America this year has come to a divide in the road,'' Reagan
said. ``Take one fork and we continue in the direction that Bill
Roth has helped chart.''
   ``Take the other, and in four years, all of us may be picking up
the pieces. Today, America has peace and prosperity, growth and
opportunity. We can re-elect them or turn to the liberal
alternative,'' he said.
</TEXT>
