<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UPSHero     08-01 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UPS Hero,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Face Trial in Holdup Foiled by UPS Deliveryman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Members who published MOUNTAIN VIEW, Colo.-dated UPS Hero,
sent as a0517 on June 18, may want to use the following. At that
time, it appeared Swartz might be disciplined by his employer.
Since then he has been honored by his employer.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deliveryman who foiled a robbery by
ramming his truck into a getaway car says he just wanted to get the
thieves' license number _ but he was angry, too.
   ``I was a little mad that I walked in for a delivery and I was
getting robbed, while I was at work,'' said Tom Swartz, 30, a
driver for United Parcel Service.
   At a preliminary hearing last Friday, Swartz identified the
suspects, Gillie Garcia, 50, and Edmund Herrera, 31, as the men who
were robbing City Surplus Paint Co. when Swartz made a delivery to
the store in the Denver suburb of Mountain View on June 16.
   The intruders had bound three employees in a back office,
emptied the cash register and robbed several customers when the UPS
driver walked in, authorities said. Swartz said he, too, was robbed.
   As the men fled with about $400, Swartz followed them out. ``I
decided to go get the license number,'' he said.
   He got into his UPS truck and drove around to the side of the
store, where he saw a Cadillac coming at him with one robber
inside. He rammed his truck into the car, Swartz said.
   Police arrested Herrera at the scene, and later took Garcia into
custody in nearby Lakewood.
   The episode received national attention because an initial
report quoted witnesses as saying Swartz's UPS supervisor had
``cursed'' him for damaging the company truck and threatened to
take away his good driving record, a basis for promotions.
   Swartz and the company later said the supervisor had not cursed
Swartz, and UPS praised the driver's actions, saying the collision
would not be charged against his record. The company honored Swartz
for heroism at a reception June 24.
   In Friday's hearing, Jefferson County Judge Robert Morris
concluded there was sufficient evidence to try both suspects on six
counts each of aggravated robbery and one count each of felony
menacing.
   The men, both held on $100,000 bonds, are to be arraigned Aug.
15 in Jefferson County District Court.
</TEXT>
