<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Denby-Nicaragua     08-01 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denby-Nicaragua,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Nicaraguan Captive Trying To Retrieve Airplane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARLINVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Illinois farmer who was shot down
over Nicaragua last year and imprisoned there for 56 days has
returned to Central America in hopes of retrieving his airplane,
his brother said Monday.
   William Denby said his brother James is trying to clear a lien
that was placed on the plane to ensure payment of fees to the
lawyer who represented him in Nicaraguan courts.
   ``All he said was, `Hey, I'm going to Nicaragua,''' said William
Denby, who said his brother had been in Central America for ``a
couple of weeks.''
   On Dec. 6, James Denby was flying to a farm he owns in Costa
Rica when his single-engine Cessna was hit by rifle fire and he was
forced to land on the Nicaraguan coast.
   Nicaraguan officials said they found documents linking Denby to
U.S.-backed Contra rebels fighting the country's leftist Sandinista
government.
   Denby denied the allegations, although he said in a 1987
interview with The Associated Press that he had ferried wounded
Contras to hospitals in his plane.
   He was acquitted by a Nicaraguan court in early February.
   At the time, Denby said in news interviews he would be very
reluctant to return to Nicaragua. ``They would have to send an
aircraft carrier,'' he said.
   But William Denby indicated his brother had received assurances
that he would be safe.
   ``I'm sure he was not concerned about his well-being in
Nicaragua,'' William Denby said
   He said that during this visit, his brother ``said he was
treated better in Nicaragua than in Costa Rica,'' where officials
had not been formally notified that the Nicaraguan charges had been
dropped.
   Though he said his information was sketchy, William Denby said
his brother ``apparently has gotten or is getting his aircraft back
from the government.''
   Telephone calls to James Denby's family home near Carlinville
were not answered Monday.
</TEXT>
