<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hinckley     08-01 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hinckley,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Ordered to Justify Hinckley Field Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mental hospital where John W. Hinckley Jr.
is being held was ordered Monday to justify its plan to allow the
presidential assailant to join a day-long field trip outside the
hospital with other patients.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker granted a request by
federal prosecutors for a court hearing on the proposal by St.
Elizabeths Hospital to let Hinckley go on a supervised
``recreational'' day trip away from the guarded facility.
   Parker gave the hospital until Friday to file with him all
treatment records and other documents to support its conclusion
that Hinckley would ``benefit therapeutically'' from the trip and
that he could participate ``without posing a danger to himself or
to others.''
   Hinckley, who shot and wounded President Reagan and three others
on March 31, 1981, has been held at St. Elizabeths since 1982, when
he was acquitted of criminal charges by reason of insanity.
   Last year, the government successfully opposed an attempt by
hospital authorities to allow Hinckley to visit his parents over
the Easter weekend.
   The proposal was withdrawn after it was disclosed in court that
Hinckley had corresponded with convicted multiple murderer Theodore
Bundy, who is on Florida's death row.
   The Secret Service said it opposed the hospital's latest plan,
which was outlined in a July 19 letter to the judge.
   The letter did not specify what sorts of activities the field
trip would involve. Hospital officials said they might include
bowling, a picnic or music.
</TEXT>
