<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Hostages     08-01 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Hostages,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Churchman Predicts Hostage Release This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church of England envoy Terry Waite and the other
foreign hostages held in Lebanon may be released by the end of the
year, an Anglican archbishop back from discussions in Iran
predicted Monday.
   Britain, meanwhile, said it is reviewing its strained relations
with Iran, further fueling hopes of freedom for hostages believed
held by pro-Iranian extremists in Lebanon.
   The news followed a weekend in which Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher spoke of improving British-Iranian relations and the
Church of England announced it had sent a church official on a
hostage mission to Lebanon.
   David Penman, the archbishop for Melbourne, Australia, and an
expert on Islam, said after his trip to Tehran that ``intuition''
leads him to believe the hostages will be released from Lebanon
after Israel's Nov. 1 elections and U.S. elections a week later.
   ``I would not be surprised if Terry Waite and the others were
released before the end of the year,'' Penman told a news
conference in Canterbury, where he is attending an international
conference of Anglican bishops. He visited Tehran on his way to
England last month.
   Penman said he had discussions about Waite in Tehran ``with some
of my hosts, but I cannot talk about them.''
   Waite disappeared in Beirut Jan. 20, 1987, while seeking the
release of American hostages. No one has claimed to hold him.
Seventeen other foreigners, including nine Americans, are believed
held in Lebanon.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, 40, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was abducted March 16,
1985.
   Waite's brother, David, said he hoped Penman was right about the
hostages' release, but warned ``the moment you start talking about
it being over by such and such a date, and that date passes, it is
a big anticlimax.''
   Mrs. Thatcher expressed hope for improved relations in a letter
to David Waite which was made public Saturday.
   Two London newspapers, The Independent and Daily Telegraph,
reported Monday that Penman was on a mission for Runcie, but Penman
said he was invited by the Iranians and the trip's primary purpose
was to discuss Iranian-Australian relations.
   Bishop John Brown, whose diocese includes Cyprus and all Persian
Gulf nations except Iran, went to Lebanon at Runcie's request last
week to speak to Lbanese Christian leaders about four Iranians who
disappeared while traveling in a Christian-controlled zone outside
Beirut in July 1982.
   They were presumed kidnapped, but no one claimed responsibility.
There have been unconfirmed reports that they were killed.
   Brown said Sunday that he hoped his mission contributed
``towards the overall picture which I hope will lead towards the
release of all the hostages.''
   The Foreign Office said Britain's review of relations with
Tehran follows Iran's acceptance of a U.N. resolution calling for a
cease-fire in Iran's 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   ``British ministers are reviewing the whole gamut of
Anglo-Iranian relations, including the possibility of sending a
diplomat to Tehran for a short period of time,'' said a Foreign
Office spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Britain and Iran all but broke off diplomatic relations last
summer after an Iranian envoy was arrested for shoplifting in
England and a British diplomat was arrested and beaten in Tehran.
   Britain left its mission in Tehran vacant, but Iran has kept its
charge d'affairs, Akunzadeh Basti, in London.
   Basti said Monday, following an hourlong meeting at the Foreign
Office, that ``a better atmosphere is developing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
