<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Saudi     08-01 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Saudi,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudis Say They Still Want US Weaponry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia wants to keep buying weapons from
the United States, although it also will build its stock with
purchases from elsewhere, the Saudi embassy said Monday.
   Seeking to dispel any notion of a U.S.-Saudi rift, the embassy
released a statement on the Saudi decision to buy $17 billion worth
of military equipment, including 50 Tornado jet fighters, from
Britain.
   ``The kingdom would like to reiterate its desire to obtain its
military requirements, including advanced aircraft and defense
arms, from American plants, with the full conviction of our
peaceful intentions..,'' the statement said. It was attributed to
an unnamed source who was quoted by the Saudi Press Agency.
   The State Department has complained that the deal was not in the
interest of the United States.
   For decades the Saudis relied mainly on the United States to
supply weapons, but supporters of Israel in Washington have blocked
the sale of some sophisticated weapons, claiming they could be used
against the Jewish state.
   The statement said the British sale ``will not affect, either in
the short-term or long-term the strength of ties between''
Washington and Riyadh.
   Although the Saudis will continue trying to secure weapons from
the United States, they will buy from any country as long as there
are no restrictions, the statement said.
   Last week, King Fahd said Saudi Arabia will not hesitate to
purchase weapons from communist suppliers.
</TEXT>
