<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HighwayRobbery     08-01 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Robbery,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Toll Taker Opened Her Own Lanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida Turnpike toll booth
manager who opened her own lanes allegedly kept as much as $15,000
paid by motorists, a state transportation official said.
   Lorna J. Hoff, 33, was arrested April 2 after a stakeout by
Department of Transportation and state attorney's office
investigators at the Palm Beach Gardens Interchange. She had $844
and 750 toll tickets with her when she was stopped, authorities
said.
   According to Tim Valentine, a state attorney's investigator who
headed the operation, Ms. Hoff subsequently admitted to having
pilfered ``several hundred dollars'' worth of tolls on ``two or
three'' occasions following her promotion to manager March 4.
   Ms. Hoff's admission led to dismissal from her $17,394-a-year
job, and she was charged with grand theft.
   Her 10-year tenure with the DOT coupled with the fact that she
had no prior record led prosecutors to agree to drop the charge
when she agreed to pay back the $844 and take part in a pre-trial
intervention program.
   But the DOT refused to consent to the pre-trial deal, leaving
the grand theft charge standing. And DOT chief of toll facilities
John Berry now says she may have stolen as much as $15,000.
   Subsequent investigation into Hoff's activities has led the
state to believe the former toll manager may have milked a single
toll lane about 14 times, he said.
   ``We've been working reconstructing certain reports and
determined it's a lot more than $844,'' Berry said.
   Berry said evidence indicated that Hoff, who as manager was not
actually supposed to work a toll booth, had kept toll funds on days
she took regular attendants off the work schedule and put herself
on an operating lane.
   He said this was noticed because the regular attendants were
logged in for the day's work, but their end-of-day receipts were
not reported.
</TEXT>
