<2ND_LINE>AM-Car Satisfaction, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honda's Acura Leads Satisfaction Survey for Second Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with one graf to include number of responses.
SUBS 9th graf, `Here is ...,' with 1 graf to clarify that figures
are strictly comparative. Also moved on the financial wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AGOURA HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda's luxury Acura cars ranked
highest in customer satisfaction for the second consecutive year in
a consumer survey that found only two American nameplates in the
top 10.
   The rankings released Monday by J.D. Power and Associates, an
auto industry research group, were based on questionnaires
completed by 25,200 motorists one year after they bought their cars.
   Ranked in order, the top 10 models were Acura, Mercedes-Benz,
Honda, Cadillac, Toyota, Lincoln, BMW, Volvo, and, tied for ninth,
Mazda and Audi.
   The survey covered 158 car models from 34 automakers and
measured customer satisfaction with both the product and with the
dealers that sell and service them.
   Acura, the luxury division of American Honda Motor Sales Co.
that sells two models, also placed first in the 1987 survey, the
first year it was included. Honda itself ranked third this year,
and Mercedes-Benz was second.
   Satisfaction with the industry overall improved in 1988, J.D.
Power and Associates said, attributing the improvement to increased
reliability of the cars and efforts to improve dealer service.
   Ranked by country of origin, Asian carmakers scored highest,
followed by European automakers, with the U.S. car industry ranked
last.
   J.D. Power, which conducts its survey primarily for sale to
automakers for their internal use, does not release survey results
on cars or automakers that rate poorly.
   Here is how the top 10 were rated in the survey in three
categories _ overall customer satisfaction, handling, and repair
and reliability. The numbers, derived from answers to the
questionnaires, have comparative meaning only.
   1. Acura, satisfaction 144; handling 141; reliability 131.
   2. Mercedes-Benz, satisfaction 138, handling 148, reliability
123.
   3. Honda, satisfaction 135, handling 125, reliability 132.
   4. Cadillac, satisfaction 126, handling 137, reliability 114.
   5. Toyota, satisfaction 122, handling 115, reliability 121.
   6. Lincoln, satisfaction 121, handling 125, reliability 113.
   7. BMW, satisfaction 120, handling 120, reliability 114.
   8. Volvo, satisfaction 118, handling 119, reliability 113.
   9. (tie) Mazda, satisfaction 117, handling 106, reliability 121.
   9. (tie) Audi, satisfaction 117, handling 131, reliability 108.
</TEXT>
