<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand     08-01 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Opens Newly-Elected Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Bhumibol Adulyadej opened the new
Parliament on Monday and is expected to name a 66-year-old former
general as prime minister.
   Elections were held July 24 for the 357-seat House of
Representatives and a five-party coalition was formed because none
of the 16 parties won a majority.
   A majority of the membership nominated Chatichai Choonhavan, the
former general who leads the Chart Thai (Thai Nation) party, for a
four-year term as premier. The Chart Thai won more seats than any
other party.
   Last week, Chatichai gave the king a declaration signed by 215
members of Parliament who support him to become prime minister. The
king is expected to name Chatichai to the post this week through a
royal decree.
   Bhumibol will install Chatichai, who has been a deputy premier,
to replace Prem Tinsulanonda, 67, who resigned after serving for
eight years. Thailand is a parliamentart democracy and Bhumibol has
little direct power, but is the symbol of national unity.
   Prem, a former army commander, called the elections 24 months
early after disbanding his fractious coalition.
   Chatichai was left with no rival after Siddhi Savetsila, foreign
minister and leader of the Social Action Party, dropped out of the
running Sunday and said he would support Chatichai.
   The new prime minister is expected to follow a conservative,
pro-Western policy and emphasize economic development.
</TEXT>
