<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane-Robbery,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Force Plane to Land, Steal Gold, Rob Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men with pistols and grenades forced
an airliner to land on an abandoned runway Monday, where they
seized a gold shipment and robbed the 22 passengers, Medellin
police said.
   A police statement said the propeller-driven Twin Otter plane of
the Colombian airline ACES was on a flight from the northwest town
of El Bagre to the industrial city of Medellin when forced to land
near Campamento village, about 60 miles southwest of El Bagre.
   Six other gunmen joined the two hijackers and took the gold and
passengers' jewelry, money and other valuables, the statement said.
   The cargo of gold came from a mine near El Bagre and was valued
at $500,000, police said.
   The gunmen smashed the plane's radio, kicked the co-pilot in the
face, warned the pilot not to take off for an hour and then fled
into the jungle, police said.
   The plane took off from the grass runway after an hour and
landed safely in Medellin.
