<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Sihanouk,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Tells China Chances Very Slim For Peace in Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian Prince Norodom Sihanouk went to North
Korea Monday after informing Chinese officials of the unfruitful
efforts to end the war in Cambodia.
   And a magazine said authorities in Bejing are refusing to allow
former Cambodia ruler Pol Pot to leave China, where the leader of
the Khmer Rouge regime is hospitalized for unspecified treatment.
   Sihanouk, who resigned last month as head of the Cambodian
resistance coalition, flew to North Korea for a ``short visit,''
the Korean Central News Agency reported in Pyongyang, North Korea's
capital. Sihanouk is to go to Tokyo Monday for a week.
   During his two-day visit to Beijing, Sihanouk told Chinese
leaders the prospects for peace in Cambodia were ``very slim.''
   He advised the Chinese about last week's talks in Indonesia that
involved Cambodia, Vietnam and the three-member Cambodian
resistance alliance made up of the radical communist Khmer Rouge,
anti-communist forces and Sihanouk's followers.
   Sihanouk did not participate in the talks but was represented by
his son.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the Khmer
Rouge and installed another communist regime. The Khmer Rouge then
began guerrilla warfare against the estimated 100,000 Vietnamese
troops in Cambodia.
   The Khmer Rouge, under Pol Pot, gained power in the spring of
1975 with the collapse of the U.S.-backed government. Hundreds of
thousands of Cambodians perished during the Khmer Rouge's harsh
efforts to turn Cambodia into a communist agrarian society.
   China backed the Khmer Rouge while the Soviet Union supports the
Vietnamese.
   Sihanouk met Sunday with Vice Premier Wu Xueqian, who said the
Indonesian meeting marked the beginning of a search for a political
settlement in Cambodia but accused Vietnam of being insincere.
   Upon his arrival in Beijing Saturday night, Sihanouk criticized
both Vietnam and the Khmer Rouge, the strongest member of the
resistance coalition.
   Vietnam has insisted that the Khmer Rouge must not be allowed to
return to power. China, although it had supported the Pol Pot
regime, has said Sihanouk should lead a future Cambodia government
that should not be dominated by the Khmer Rouge.
   In Hong Kong, the Chinese-language magazine Cheng Ming said
Chinese authorities will not allow Pol Pot to leave China. It said
Pol Pot is being treated at a Beijing hospital for unspecified
ailments.
   The magazine said China will offer political asylum to Pol Pot.
   It reported there was a tacit agreement between China and the
United States that China would stop supplying military aid to
groups loyal to Pol Pot and would not allow him to regain power in
Cambodia.
   Pol Pot officially retired in September 1985 as commander in
chief of the Khmer Rouge army and was named director of the party's
Institute for National Defense. The move was seen as an attempt by
the Khmer Rouge to improve its international image.
   Sihanouk was deposed by the military as Cambodia's head of state
in March 1970 and the monarchy was abolished that October.
</TEXT>
