<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Biaggi-Wedtech     08-01 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi's 1987 Brooklyn Conviction Upheld; Jury Still Out in
Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Monday upheld the 1987
conviction of Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., while a jury deliberated
racketeering charges against him in the Wedtech corruption trial.
   U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley immediately
sequestered the jury in the Wedtech case at the request of Biaggi's
lawyer, who called the appeals court ruling ``a great problem for
us.''
   Motley had planned to sequester the jury beginning Tuesday night
after late arriving jurors on Monday were confronted by
demonstrators outside the courthouse, chanting ``Down with
political corruption'' and ``Compensate Wedtech workers.''
   The jury ended its third day of deliberations Monday without a
verdict.
   Monday's ruling by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld
Biaggi's Sept. 22, 1987, conviction for obstructing justice and
accepting an unlawful gratuity. Biaggi was convicted of accepting
free Florida vacations with a female companion from former Brooklyn
Democratic leader Meade Esposito.
   The appeals panel also upheld the conviction of the 80-year-old
Esposito.
   Biaggi, 71, a 10-term congressman from the Bronx, was convicted
by a U.S. District Court jury in Brooklyn on three felony counts:
accepting an illegal gratuity, traveling across state lines to
accept the gratuity and obstruction of justice.
   U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein sentenced Biaggi to 30
months in prison and a $500,000 fine. Biaggi has been free pending
appeal, and his attorney James LaRossa said Biaggi would try to
pursue his appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The original jury acquitted Biaggi and Esposito of the more
serious charges of bribery and conspiracy.
   Prosecutors said Esposito paid for one vacation and arranged to
pay for another in exchange for the congressman's efforts on behalf
of a Brooklyn ship repair company that was a major client of
Esposito's insurance brokerage.
   In the current trial, Biaggi and six defendants are charged with
turning the now-defunct Wedtech Corp. into a racketeering
enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in bribes to obtain
no-bid government contracts.
   The House ethics committee recommended in February 1988 that
Biaggi be expelled for ``criminal conduct ... going to the heart of
his representational responsibilities.'' In an unusual maneuver,
however, congressional leaders decided to delay action while Biaggi
defended himself in the Wedtech trial.
   John Davison, a spokesman for the ethics committee, declined to
comment on what effect the appeals court ruling would have.
</TEXT>
