<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Transplant     08-01 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Transplant,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Quits In Animal-To-Human Transplants Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British surgeon involved in a plan to use pigs'
organs for human transplants abruptly quit the project Monday in a
dispute with colleagues, but said research would continue.
   Dr. Michael Bewick said fellow researchers at Dulwich Hospital,
in south London, told him to ``shut up or get out'' following a day
where battle lines were drawn between scientists and animal rights
activists.
   Bewick, 52, a kidney transplant specialist, said the research
team was furious that without their consent he had announced the
hospital intended to study the feasibility of transplanting
kidneys, livers and hearts from pigs into people.
   Animal rights groups responded to the press coverage by labeling
the idea a ``horror fantasy'' and ``gross abuse of animal life.''
They asked the government to ban the project.
   Bewick said the research team feared the controversy might harm
its chances of obtaining facilities to carry out the work.
   ``For the sake of the group and the work they are doing, I
decided it would be right for me to leave,'' Bewick said. He
stressed the group had ``the brains and technical skills'' to
proceed without him.
   A hospital spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
he would meet with Bewick and the research team Tuesday to assess
the situation.
   Bewick was quoted in the Independent newspaper Monday, as saying
in earlier comments that the program posed ``no ethical problem. .
.. Animal kidneys could save the lives of thousands of people who
die because we do not have an off-the-shelf kidney.''
   Before withdrawing from the project, Bewick had offered to meet
with animal rights groups to discuss their concerns. He said he
feared attacks on his personal property and the hospital.
   Attempts to transplant animal organs into humans, including
sheep, baboon and chimpanzee hearts, have failed.
   In what was probably the most publicized case, Dr. Leonard
Bailey transplanted a baboon heart into a 12-day-old infant, dubbed
Baby Fae, at the Loma Linda medical facility in California in 1984.
She died 20 days later.
   A year after the California baby's death, Bailey said she died
not from rejection of heart tissue but from another form of
rejection which he said he believes is possible to avoid.
   Bewick said over the weekend that the hospital research team
found a way to filter out antibodies that cause humans to reject
donor organs. He said the new technique had helped 20 patients
accept human kidneys more easily.
   Researchers had planned experiments this fall to see whether the
technique worked between different species of animals _ pigs and
sheep. If successful, Bewick had estimated pig-to-human transplants
could begin within three years.
   But the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection condemned
the research program as a ``gross abuse of animal life and waste of
health care resources.''
   ``The experimental animals will undoubtedly suffer greatly both
physically and mentally despite the fact that anesthetics will be
used,'' an unidentified spokesman said.
   Bewick had said pigs were the most suitable animals because
their organs physiologically most resemble those of humans.
   Another pressure group, Animal Concern Scotland, said animal
research would be unnecessary if more people agreed to donate their
organs after death.
   ``The idea of breeding pigs as living organ banks owes more to
sick horror fantasy than medical science'' said a spokesman, who
refused to be identified. ``I hope the (government) will use some
common sense and ban this approach.''
   The Sunday Times quoted Bewick as saying he had obtained
approval for the experiments from the hospital's ethics committee.
   A spokeswoman for the British Medical Association, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said that panel's approval made the project
acceptable if it seemed likely to yield some benefit.
   She said society ultimately would decide the future of
animal-to-human transplants. The controversy highlighted the need
for a national ethics committee, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
