<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Prison 1stLd-Writethru a0651 08-01 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Prison, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Ends Prison Siting Inquiry Without Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `Cloherty also,' to add
comment from Dukakis spokesman.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Dukakis Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary FBI inquiry into allegations the
Dukakis administration gave developers confidential information
about prison-siting plans has ended with no charges filed.
   Law enforcement sources, speaking only on condition they not be
named, said the investigation turned up no evidence of federal
violations.
   FBI spokesman John Cloherty said, ``The FBI is conducting no
further investigation with regard to the placing of a state prison
at New Braintree, Mass., and-or the procurement of land for that
prison.'' He declined to characterize the outcome of the inquiry
other than to say no charges had been filed.
   Cloherty also declined to say whether any evidence had been
forwarded for grand jury review. However, two law enforcement
sources said the inquiry found no evidence that federal laws had
been broken.
   Stephen Crawford, deputy press spokesman for the Massachusetts
governor, refused to say whether law enforcement officials had
informed the administration that the inquiry had ended.
   But when told of the FBI statement and law enforcement comment,
Crawford said: ``It was always our contention that this was an open
process, above the board. We will go forward with the
implementation of the New Braintree plan.''
   Gov. Michael Dukakis in 1986 formally announced plans to build a
500-bed, medium-security prison in New Braintree at the site of a
defunct religious academy. The site had been discussed informally
for a prison or other state institution beginning in 1984.
   Prison opponents, largely residents of the rural town of 800
people, complained that the inmate and staff population would
overrun their farming community. Later, some opponents alleged that
the Dukakis administration, unable to buy the land directly because
the church that owned it had agreed with town officials not to sell
it for projects including a prison, leaked its interest in the site
to two developers who bought it and then offered it to the state.
   The allegations have been cited by Dukakis critics to attack the
good-government pledges that are a major theme of his presidential
campaign. National publicity followed the FBI's confirmation June
23 that a preliminary inquiry was under way. At that time, the
agency said Dukakis himself was not a target of any investigation.
   The developers, Daniel Striar and Gary Jacobson, offered the
land to the state for $9.5 million. But the state has offered only
$5 million, citing three appraisals, commissioned by the state,
that listed its value at or just below $5 million.
   Striar and Jacobson have rejected the state's offer as too low
but the state notified New Braintree officials in a letter mailed
last week that the purchase would go forward.
   Jack Bradshaw, associate deputy commissioner of the state
Division of Capital Planning and Operations, said the state will
take the land by eminent domain if the owners do not change their
stance. The seizure likely will take place in mid-October or
November, he said Monday.
   Bradshaw said his agency had not been informed that the inquiry
had ended.
   ``None of my people were questioned as part of it and we haven't
talked to them today either,'' he said. ``We didn't feel it was
necessary for any investigation. However, the FBI has a role to
complete and if they have done that and feel there is no evidence
of wrongdoing then I'm certainly happy.''
</TEXT>
