<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marines-Homosexual 2ndLd-Writethru a0678 08-01 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marines-Homosexual, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0678,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corps Punishes Two Who Testified In Lesbianism Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix writethru designation. INSERTS one graf
after 14th graf `They were' to elaborate on content of testimony.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps has punished two
female Marines because they testified at a court-martial on behalf
of a female sergeant who was accused of lesbianism at Parris Island.
   And a specialist in military legal affairs said the action may
have damaged future efforts to prosecute female Marines accused of
lesbianism.
   Staff Sgts. Gloria H. Gurule and Christine R. Hilinski, who
testified as character witnesses at Sgt. Cheryl Jameson's
court-martial July 14, were removed from the drill field July 18
and reassigned to other areas.
   Also, their military occupational specialities were voided,
which means their permanent records will show they had an
unsuccessful tour of duty on the drill field. Ms. Hilsinki wasn't
actually assigned to the drill field when she was removed but was
on a routine six-month ``quota,'' in this case serving as a depot
inspector.
   Jameson pleaded guilty to engaging in indecent acts and charges
of sodomy and obstruction of justice were dropped. She was
sentenced to a year in prison, reduced to private and dishonorably
discharged.
   Air Force Maj. Carol DiBattiste said military judges could throw
out any more cases that go to trial if they believe the Corps tried
to frighten potential defense witnesses. Ms. DiBattiste is an
instructor in the military justice division at the Air Force Judge
Advocate General's School's at Maxwell Air Force Base.
   ``The problem is when you start trying to scare witnesses,''
said Ms. DiBattiste. ``If they can prove it ... the accused might
have a successful claim.''
   Attorneys charge that by removing the two women from their jobs,
and by holding ``informational briefings'' with other female
Marines to explain the actions, Corps officials have frightened
others from coming forward to testify for their clients.
   ``The word is out: You don't testify for women accused of being
a homosexual,'' said Vaughan Taylor, an attorney for several women
accused in the investigation.
   The Uniform Code of Military Justice, which governs all branches
of the military, prohibits illegal command influence, which
``involves anyone in a position of command who tries to influence
the outcome of a court-martial.''
   That section of the code has been interpreted by the U.S. Court
of Military Appeals to mean, for example, that commanders can't try
to persuade potential witnesses not to testify, according to court
opinions.
   But Parris Island officials, who acknowledge punishing the women
for their testimony but don't acknowledge holding the briefings,
said they've done nothing improper or illegal.
   A spokesman for the Marine Corps Recruit Training Depot at
Parris Island, 1st Lt. A.J. Kozloski, said the women were relieved
of their duties as drill instructors because of their testimony.
   ``They were relieved as a result of loss of confidence by thir
superiors based on the content of their testimony under oath in the
Jameson case,'' Kozloski said. ``This is purely an administrative
action. No one is being punished merely for testifying.
   Gurule and Hilinski testified they would be willing to work with
Ms. Jameson.
   ``The fact is that if a Marine in a position of high
responsibility such as a drill instructor makes a statement under
oath that (shows) he or she doesn't understand or support an order
directly governing his or her duties, it is within the discretion
of the commander to consider removing that individual from that
specific postion.''
   Ms. DiBattiste said that although officers could be
court-martialed if found guilty of engaging in illegal command
influence, such charges are usually dropped.
   ``All I can tell you is I think that's an appropriate allegation
for defense council to make,'' Ms. DiBattiste said. ``I would not
render an opinion to you whether they would win or lose.''
</TEXT>
