<HEAD>FEC Asks Court To Reject GOP Claim On Dukakis-Bentsen Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission on Monday
asked a federal appeals court to reject a Republican claim that
full funding for the Democratic presidential campaign should be
blocked because Sen. Lloyd Bentsen was benefiting unfairly.
   The Republicans fail to show there is anything illegal about
Bentsen's decision to run for both the vice presidency and
re-election to his Senate seat, as allowed under Texas law, the FEC
said.
   Blocking the Democrats from spending their federal money would
``irreparably harm'' their campaign, the FEC said.
   Bentsen's Senate campaign opponent, Republican Rep. Beau
Boulter, and the National Republican Senatorial Committee, which
helps GOP Senate candidates win election, complained that the dual
campaign gave Bentsen an unfair financial advantage.
   Because of the dual campaign, Bentsen would be able to spend the
$4 million in private money raised for his Senate contest on top of
the federal money for his vice presidential campaign, which is
limited for both parties.
   The committee asked the FEC to withhold the $46 million in
federal funding due the Michael Dukakis-Bentsen ticket, but the
commission two weeks ago voted 6-0 to reject that request. The
money was then transferred from the Treasury to the campaign.
   The GOP is now asking the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District
of Columbia to block the Democrats from spending the money.
   Bentsen's attorneys also filed a brief on Monday asking that the
GOP request be rejected.
