<HEAD>Atlanta Councilman Hosea Williams Arrested At City Hall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JONESBORO, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta City Councilman Hosea Williams was
arrested and led away from Atlanta's City Hall in handcuffs Monday
on a 5-month-old weapons charge stemming from an incident at
Hartsfield airport.
   Williams was held briefly at the jail in neighboring Clayton
County, where Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport is located,
then released on his own recognizance.
   His arrest by Clayton County Sheriff Bill Lemacks came about two
hours after a news conference during which he said he had never
been notified of the charges against him.
   He was indicted last week by a Clayton County grand jury on one
count of possession of a weapon by a convicted felon.
   Williams was stopped March 6 at a security checkpoint at
Hartsfield as he tried to board a plane. Police said they found a
.38-caliber handgun and five bullets inside his briefcase.
   According to police, Williams said he had placed the gun in his
briefcase while cleaning his car and forgot it was there when he
dashed to the airport.
   Williams was given a copy of the charges and allowed to board
the plane after his handgun and ammunition were confiscated.
   Williams first was charged with two misdemeanor counts _
carrying a weapon without a license and carrying a concealed
weapon. The charges was upgraded to a single felony count after a
review of Williams' criminal record, said Stanley Tuggle, chief of
administrative operations for the Clayton County Sheriff's
Department.
   If found guilty, Williams could face one to five years in jail.
   Williams has been arrested numerous times during his work for
civil rights, and also has at least 25 traffic-related convictions.
   At his news conference, Williams denied reports that he had
promised to surrender over the weekend.
   ``The racist white press of Atlanta is again out to destroy my
image as a black leader who is unbought and unbossed,'' he said.
   Tuggle had been quoted over the weekend as saying, ``We have
been in contact with Mr. Williams and he has indicated he will turn
himself in.''
   Tuggle said Monday that Clayton County authorities had contacted
Williams indirectly last week through the Fulton County Sheriff's
Department, and that Williams had told those officers he would
handle the matter over the weekend.
   ``He is being truthful when he says he didn't talk directly with
us, but he's not being truthful when he says he didn't know
anything about it,'' Tuggle said. ``He knew what was going on.''
</TEXT>
