<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthernAfricaTalks     08-01 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Africa Talks,0587</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Soviets Say Southern Africa Settlement Possible in `Future'
^By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official said Monday there is a good
chance four-way talks that resume Tuesday will produce a peace
settlement soon in southern Africa.
   Anatoly Adamyshin, Soviet deputy foreign minister, made the
comments after two days of consultations with Chester Crocker, U.S.
assistant secretary of state for African affairs.
   Crocker is mediating the talks among South Africa, Angola and
Cuba, which began three months ago and resume Tuesday. Agreement on
guidelines for a settlement was reached during last month's round
in New York.
   ``We think there are chances of success in these negotiations,''
Adamyshin told a news conference. ``It appears that all sides are
serious about seeking a settlement. ... It is possible that there
will be a settlement in the nearest future.''
   Asked to be more specific, he said a target date of Sept. 29 had
been mentioned. That is the 10th anniversary of U.N. Security
Council Resolution 435 on independence for Namibia, also known as
South-West Africa, which South Africa has controlled since World
War I.
   All negotiators accepted the resolution as a basis of the
``Principles for a Peaceful Settlement in Southwestern Africa''
agreed upon July 20.
   The list of 14 principles, the first document to which the three
countries have agreed, link independence for Namibia to withdrawal
of the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola.
   Cuban soldiers have helped the Marxist government against rebels
of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or
UNITA, who have fought since Angola became independent of Portugal
in 1975. The movement, led by Jonas Savimbi, is supported by South
Africa and the United States.
   The agreement on principles emerged from three rounds of talks
held since May in London, Cairo and New York. Military commanders
of South Africa, Angola and Cuba met in Cape Verde and were said to
have made progress on disengaging Cuban and South African soldiers
who face each other along the Angola-Namibia frontier.
   Crocker has called the list of principles ``an important step''
but says hard bargaining remains. The Soviet Union has assigned a
special observer, although it is not a participant in the
negotiations.
   Adamyshin was asked about a U.S. official's statement that the
superpowers find increasing common ground on southern Africa, and
acknowledged there is ``more understanding.''
   He added, however, that U.S. military aid to UNITA ``is unlawful
and must be stopped. On that point, we differ with the United
States.''
   Later in the news conference, he said the aid issue must be
settled between the United States and Angola. It is not covered in
the list of principles.
   According to Adamyshin, the Soviet Union ``will be satisfied
with whatever satisfies Angola, Cuba, and SWAPO.''
   SWAPO, or the South-West Africa People's Organization, has
fought a guerrilla war in Namibia since 1966, when the United
Nations abrogated a League of Nations mandate under which South
Africa governed the former German colony.
   It has welcomed the agreement on principles and a SWAPO
spokesman described prospects for a settlement as ``reasonably
brighter.''
   President Fidel Castro of Cuba said last week the parties were
on the ``threshhold of a political solution.''
   South Africa has been more cautious. Its government radio said
Monday recent Cuban reinforcements and deployment of Angolan and
Cuban soldiers on the Namibian border ``place a question mark over
the real intentions'' of the two governments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
