<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-Ties     08-01 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Ties,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Officials Discuss Jordan's West Bank Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Jordan-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO foreign relations chief was quoted
as calling on Monday for maintaining Palestinian rights in Jordan
following King Hussein's decision to cut administrative ties with
Palestinians in the West Bank.
   Farouk Kaddoumi made his comments Monday at a closed meeting of
the Central Council of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
according to other PLO officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The council is the upper branch of the PLO's bicameral
legislature, the Palestine National Council.
   Kaddoumi praised Jordan's ``distinguished'' relations with the
world's 5 million Palestinians and the PLO and said, ``These
relations will remain,'' the PLO officials reported.
   But they said Kaddoumi emphasized the importance of maintaining
``all the rights acquired by the Palestinian people in Jordan.''
   Hussein over the past week suspended Jordan's Parliament, half
of whose members were Palestinians, and canceled a development plan
for the Israeli-occupied West Bank to dramatize PLO responsibility
for the occupied lands.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   PLO officials said Chairman Yasser Arafat ordered a muzzle on
all public comments by his organization about Hussein's move until
the PLO Executive Committee _ the equivalent of a Cabinet _ has
time to study it.
   Hussein's actions appeared to please several of the Central
Council members who spoke to reporters. But PLO officials said
Arafat canceled a trip planned to the Jordanian capital next week.
The trip had never been formally announced.
   Jordan is a lifeline for the 850,000 Palestinians in the West
Bank, most of whom carry Jordanian passports, use Jordanian money
and worship in Jordanian-supported mosques. More than half of
Jordan's own people are refugees or immigrants from Palestine and
the king's action has fueled rumors about a posible loss of some
rights.
   Kaddoumi also was quoted as saying that support for the
Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories by some Arab
governments was ``below required levels.'' He also accused Syria of
undermining the insurrection by sponsoring attacks by PLO dissident
factions on Beirut refugee camps held by Arafat loyalists, PLO
officials reported.
   ``Syria's role in the attacks against Palestinian camps is clear
as the sun itself,'' Kaddoumi was quoted as saying.
   ``If they are really after strategic parity (with Israel), they
should have dropped their anti-PLO policies, especially during the
uprising.''
   The PLO officials said Kaddoumi took a swipe at Arafat's chief
spokesman, Bassam Abu Sharif, for publishing a moderately phrased
newspaper article urging Arab-Israeli coexistence.
   ``Political initiatives should not flout the resolutions and
declared policy of the PLO,'' Kaddoumi was quoted as saying.
   ``All personal interpretations or judgments by any of the
organization's officials or responsible cadres should adhere to the
declared national objectives.''
   The Central Council extended its sessions into Tuesday. It had
been scheduled to end its meetings Monday night.
</TEXT>
