<HEAD>IPI Calls On Burma To Free Newsman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Press Institute on Monday urged
the Burmese government to free Associated Press correspondent Sein
Win, who was arrested last week along with 10 dissidents.
   The arrests were made Friday and Saturday by the government of
Burma's new leader, former Gen. Sein Lwin.
   IPI, which has a worldwide membership of about 2,000
journalists, editors and publishers, protested Sein Win's detention
in a letter to Sein Lwin, said Peter Galliner, director of the
institute.
   He said the letter ``strongly urges the immediate release'' of
Sein Win, 66, a Burmese national.
   Burma on Monday released the names of 10 men it said were
arrested ``to prevent an attack against the state'' but Sein Win's
name was not on the list. The govenment has made no public mention
of Sein Win's detention.
   The U.S. Embassy in Rangoon reportedly made an official inquiry
Monday into the status of the AP correspondent.
   Sein Win, who is married and has four children, has worked for
AP for two decades and is a former publisher of the
English-language Rangoon newspaper The Guardian. He was jailed for
three years in the 1960s, along with thousands of other political
prisoners.
