<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Ozone 2ndLd-Writethru a0664 08-01 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ozone, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0664,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Wants Government to Get Profits From Cuts in Chemical
Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd graf bgng ``But the agency ... ''
to move up graf saying EPA expects shortage of CFC compounds will
enable producers to raise prices with no increase in production
costs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Monday it wants the government to capture expected windfall
corporate profits that could reach $7 billion during future cuts in
production of chemicals that destroy the Earth's protective ozone
layer.
   But the agency said it had not decided how to do that, and one
major producer said it doubts that there will be major windfalls as
the chemicals _ chlorofluorocarbon or CFC compounds _ are cut back.
   Under EPA's expectations, the shortage of CFC compounds will
enable producers to raise prices with no increase in production
costs.
   EPA disclosed that it was considering regulations that could
require manufacturers to pay fees to the government equal to their
extra profits; could require recycling or other controls on
manufacturing processes; or could require companies to buy
manufacturing rights from the government at auctions open to anyone.
   The agency announced final adoption of detailed regulations,
including production quotas, to carry out last year's treaty
obliging major nations to cut CFC production 50 percent by 1998.
   EPA expects enough countries to ratify the treaty for it to take
effect next Jan. 1. Eleven nations accounting for two-thirds of
world production must ratify; six including the United States have
done so.
   Eileen Claussen, acting deputy EPA administrator for air
programs, said the agency leans toward fees, perhaps supplemented
by direct controls, as a way of capturing windfall profits. The
president's Office of Management and Budget, on the other hand,
favors auctioning the production rights.
   EPA's authority to proceed without legislation is cloudy, Ms.
Claussen said.
   An auction, she said, could be administratively unworkable if
10,000 small companies participate. ``If it was judged to be
illegal, we would have nothing. We wouldn't be in compliance with
the Montreal protocol,'' she said.
   And she said, ``There's a lot of concern about hoarding,'' in
which large companies like auto manufacturers would keep smaller
concerns, such as those making plastic foams for furniture
cushions, from getting production rights.
   EPA wants to the government to get the increased profits because
``our concern is the incentive producers might have for keeping an
existing product in production,'' delaying the switch to
environmentally harmless alternatives, said John Hoffman, project
officer for the regulations.
   The largest producer of CFCs, Du Pont Co., said it believed no
action was needed to take extra profits away from the producers
because they would be small or nonexistent.
   ``One producer after another is announcing progress with
substitutes,'' said Joe Steed, environmental manager for CFCs for
Du Pont. Substitution ``is the driving force we're going to see ...
if we can fund development at the rate we think we need, we'll be
doing well.''
   EPA said the increase in profits over the 1986 level could range
from $1.8 billion if user companies rapidly find alternatives to
$7.2 billion if CFC compounds are kept on the market as long as
possible.
   The Montreal treaty binds participating countries to a reduction
of 20 percent in CFC production in 1993 and a further 30 percent
cut in 1998, all calculated from a 1986 base.
   The long-lived CFC compounds ascend to the ozone layer 15 to 25
miles high, where since about 1960 they have destroyed about 2.5
percent of the ozone protecting humans from skin cancer from the
sun's ultra-violet rays normally blocked by ozone.
   EPA estimates that every percent decrease in ozone results on
43,000 additional skin cancer cases in the United States. Currently
there are about 500,000 cases a year.
   The regulation will prevent about 3.7 million early deaths among
people now alive in the United States or to be born by the year
2075, EPA estimated.
   Financially, ``The impact on the consumer will be very small,''
because CFC use is such a small part of the cost of production, and
large price increases will be easily absorbed even if the increase
is five- or six-fold, EPA's Hoffman said.
   CFCs are widely used as refrigeration fluids, solvents and
plastic foam blowing agents. They are banned as U.S. aerosol
propellants but still used as propellants abroad. A new car
typically contains 2.5 pounds of a CFC compound used as air
conditioning fluid, costing about $1.50.
   EPA's regulations, if triggered by the treaty going into effect,
mean that in the 12 months beginning July 1, 1989, the five U.S.
manufacturers will be bound by these manufacturing quotas, to the
nearest million pounds: Du Pont Co., 336 million pounds;
Allied-Signal Corp., 171 million; Pennwalt Corp., 86 million;
Kaiser Chemicals Co., 62 million and Racon Inc., 30 million.
   Similar quotas apply separately to the sum of production plus
imports minus exports: Du Pont, 308 million pounds, Allied-Signal,
163 million; Pennwalt, 84 million; Kaiser, 61 million; Racon, 30
million and 10 companies whose imports totaled almost 13 million
pounds.
   Related compounds called halons used in fire extinguishers will
be subject to similar quotas starting in 1992.
   The companies may transfer these quotas among themselves.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BridgeDangle     08-01 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bridge Dangle,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paralyzed Man Dangles in Wheelchair on Brooklyn Bridge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paraplegic in a wheelchair, carrying fireworks
and samurai swords, lowered himself on a rope Monday from the
Brooklyn Bridge and dangled 75 feet above the East River for more
than an hour.
   Ramond Masa, 40, of the Bronx, who called himself ``America's
No. 1 Stuntman,'' claimed he had dangled from the 105-year-old
landmark for seven hours.
   His stunt forced traffic on the bridge to be halted as the
morning rush hour began. About 30 officers from the police harbor
unit, emergency service officers and ambulance personnel rushed to
the bridge, which connects lower Manhattan and Brooklyn, after a
tugboat operator spotted Masa.
   He was eventually persuaded to lower himself to the river, where
he was guided onto a police launch.
   Masa said he did it because ``I wanted to inspire these guys (in
wheelchairs) to get up from the hospital, and do something for
their communities and their families.''
   He refused medical attention at New York Infirmary-Beekman
Downtown Hospital and was taken to a police station, where he was
booked on charges of disorderly conduct, unlawful carrying of a
knife, and unlawful dealing with fireworks, according to police
spokesman Sgt. John Clifford.
   Masa, a large man with huge biceps and broad shoulders who also
uses the name El-Shah Muhammed El-Ratuli, was given a summons for a
Sept. 19 court date and released.
   The man, whose legs are paralyzed, initially told reporters his
name was ``Megaman.'' He handed out red, white and blue business
cards that proclaimed, ``Living on the edge is my business _
American No. 1 Stuntmen.''
   Masa said he lost the use of his legs when he was shot by a
sniper in 1977. He said his dangle off the Brooklyn Bridge was his
first experience as a stuntman.
   ``I planned for three months to do something real crazy to get
into the Guinness record book,'' he said. After a short vacation,
Masa said he plans to ``hang on the Statue of Liberty or the World
Trade Center. Maybe I'll take a shot at the Eiffel Tower in
France.''
   Masa said he was dropped off in the center of the span at about
midnight by his brother, whom he refused to identify.
   Dragging his wheelchair and two nylon bags containing the swords
and firecrackers behind him, Masa crawled to the edge of the span,
where he tied a nylon cord around his waist, through the wheelchair
and secured it to a five-inch thick piece of bridgework. Then, he
pushed the wheelchair off the bridge and shimmied down the rope
after it.
   He was noticed by a passing tugboat, which notified police about
dawn.
   ``He had looped it in some way that he could go down the rope
sitting in a wheelchair,'' said police Capt. William Plackenmeyer.
   Masa said he had planned to don a Ninja costume, light the six
super M-80's _ the equivalent of about 1{ sticks of dynamite _ and
hold the two samurai swords, each about three feet long, before he
jumped into the East River.
   He abandoned that plan after the two nylon bags containing his
gear fell into the river during the rescue effort.
   Masa expressed no remorse over the traffic jam. ``This is New
York. They (the commuters) like the excitement on Monday morning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2044EDT</FILEID>
