<DOCNO> AP880801-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru a0718 08-01 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0718,0946</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Seeks Consensus In Central America, Finds Discord Among
Allies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 22 grafs UPDATING with meeting ending, ministers
issuing communique, Shultz comments. EDITS to conform and TRIM.
PICKS up 14th graf pvs bgng, Eliminated from the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S Secretary of State George P. Shultz
and four Central American foreign ministers issued a joint
declaration Monday calling for peace and democracy in the region
but without mentioning Nicaragua.
   Shultz, however, used a closing news conference to take several
verbal swipes at Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government and to
put in a plug for congressional approval of additional aid to the
Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras.
   Nicaragua was not invited to the meeting.
   The joint communique, issued at the end of a three-hour meeting,
was a watered-down version of an earlier declaration drafted
shortly after Shultz's last visit to Costa Rica, Honduras,
Guatemala and El Salvador in late June.
   Honduras said Sunday that Guatemala and Costa Rica had demanded
changes in the proposed communique.
   The initial draft was said to be 10 pages long and to contain a
harsh criticism of Nicaragua for its failure to live up to a
Central American peace agreement signed by it and its four
neighbors a year ago.
   But as issued, the declaration contained only 10 paragraphs,
reafirming the respect of the five countries ``for peace,
democracy, security, social justice and economic development'' in
all of Central America. While obviously aimed at Nicaragua, it did
not mention the country by name.
   The final version also said the United States and the four
Central American nations agreed on the need to establish
``authentic democratic governments in the entire region as
indispensable for peace.''
   It said the five countries ``reafirmed that authentic democracy
requires, among other requisites, political pluralism, freedom of
association, freedom of the press, an impartial justice system that
guarantees due process, an apolitical armed forces, an honest and
open electoral system and respect for human and individual rights.''
   At a news conference closing their meeting, Shultz said the
Contras ``are an important element, expressing a strong desire for
freedom and democracy in Nicaragua and we continue to support them.
   ``I didn't come here basically to discuss that subject, and we
didn't have very much discussion of it, although I certainly hope
that we will extend funding for the Contras,'' Shultz said. ``I
think it is very important.''
   Shultz said his discussions with the foreign ministers centered
on economic development ``and how we might organize ourselves to
pursue that more systematically.''
   Upon arriving in Guatemala, Shultz said the United States,
Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador and Costa Rica shared common goals
of democracy, the rule of law and economic progress. But he
acknowledged problems in reaching those objectives.
   Shultz spoke with reporters before meeting with Guatemalan
President Vinicio Cerezo and later with the four foreign ministers.
   He contrasted what he described as democracy and growing
prosperity in the four Central American nations with Nicaragua,
where he said nine years of Sandinista rule and continuing warfare
have virtually destroyed the economy.
   The United States has backed the Contras since 1981 in their
fight to overthrow the Sandinista government.
   In Nicaragua, President Daniel Ortega said Shultz was trying to
escalate action against his govermment.
   Speaking at a ceremony marking the ninth anniversary of the
Sandinista air force Monday, Ortega said of the meeting:
   ``We hope that common sense might predominate, because to want
to sign a death sentence against Nicaragua, because the United
States wants one, would be the equivalent of signing a death
sentence against Central America.''
   ``We hope that these (Central American) governments might be
sufficiently reasonable and pragmatic so as not to fall in the trap
that the United States is laying in Guatemala,'' he added.
   The meetings in Guatemala were part of Shultz's quest for a
united effort to isolate Nicaragua politically and economically
from its Central American neighbors.
   In a statement distributed to reporters in Guatemala City
Sunday, the Honduran government said it found the demand for draft
changes by Guatemala and Costa Rica ``incomprehensible'' and
``strange'' and that the softening of its contents were at the
insistence of those two countries.
   Eliminated from the original statement, the Hondurans said, were
sections that would have:
   _Criticized Nicaragua for not separating its army, known as the
Sandinista Popular Army, from the governing political party.
   _Denounced ``subversion against democratic governments'' by
Nicaragua.
   _Called for a regional security system and continued
consultation between the United States and the four Central
American nations.
   Shultz said in Washington Sunday that the original document had
been drafted ``mostly ... by the Central American foreign
ministers, not by us. Having drafted it, they were not so sure they
wanted to issue it.''
   President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, who won the 1987 Nobel
Peace Prize for designing and promoting the peace plan signed last
Aug. 7, has promised his own progress report soon and there was
speculation that his government decided the Guatemala declaration
might undercut Arias' review.
   Guatemala, unlike Costa Rica, El Salvador and Honduras, does not
share a common border with Nicaragua and pursues what it calls a
policy of ``active neutrality.''
   Shultz was to fly on to Argentina Monday night for his second
stop on a 10-day trip that will take him to nine Latin American
nations. He will return to Central America Aug. 8-9 for meetings
with the presidents of Costa Rica, Honduras and El Salvador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
