<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0724 08-01 1046</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0724,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Reagan Idle On Civil Rights</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES to show speech as delivered, subbing 3rd ``We're
going...Dukakis said., 19th, ``Fifteen billion.... haven't tried.''
, and 20th graf, ``Hundreds of...haven't tried ''; DELETES 4th
graf, He commented...governor left, to delete reference to prepared
copy; SUBS 8th graf, Bush was...running mate, to give Bush absence,
Dukakis reception; EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said Monday the Reagan
administration, with ``cramped ideals and limited ambitions,'' has
spent huge amounts of money on wasteful projects rather than
helping blacks and poor people. President Reagan suggested that if
Dukakis is elected, ``all of us may be picking up the pieces.''
   Dukakis, in a speech, did not mention by name his expected
presidential election rival, Republican George Bush. But he made it
clear he was including the vice president in his criticism of the
administration.
   ``We're going to have a president and a vice president who
understand that affirmative action is an essential part of making
the American dream come true for each and every citizen of our
country,'' Dukakis told the National Urban League.
   Reagan, meanwhile, in remarks prepared for delivery at a
fund-raiser for Sen. Bill Roth, R-Del., took issue with Dukakis _
also without naming him _ for declaring in his nomination
acceptance speech that ``the Reagan era'' is ending.
   ``Does he want to end the era of lower tax rates and higher real
income for families, record numbers of jobs, low inflation and
interest rates, steady growth and respect, not just lip-service for
families?'' Reagan asked.
   ``America this year has come to a divide in the road,'' Reagan
said. ``Take one fork and we continue in the direction that Bill
Roth has helped chart. Take the other, and in four years all of us
may be picking up the pieces.''
   Bush was out of the public eye at the White House Monday, still
weighing his choice of a running mate. And Dukakis, whose reception
was cordial but unenthusiastic received his only standing ovation
when commenting on the vice president's absence from the meeting of
the non-partisan group.
   Aides said Bush couldn't appear because of a prior commitment.
   Bush is to travel to Chicago on Tuesday for a foreign policy
speech, then make a trip to Texas later in the week before flying
to his home in Kennebunkport, Maine, for the weekend. He is to
address the Republican platform committee next Monday in New
Orleans, one week before the party opens its national convention in
that city.
   While Democratic senators worked in Washington to draft a
compromise package of new aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, Dukakis
reiterated his opposition to U.S. assistance to the Contras.
   ``It's a failed and illegal policy and it ought to stop,''
Dukakis said prior to leaving Boston.
   ``Right now the administration once again seems to be doing
everything again to ... destroy the peace process,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic nominee said that, in principle, he does not
favor humanitarian aid but would accept it if the aid was part of a
negotiated settlement and the money was used to resettle the
Contras and end the war.
   Democrats, in working on a new aid package, are trying to defuse
an issue that has divided Dukakis, who opposes Contra aid, from his
running mate, Lloyd Bentsen, who has consistently supported it.
   Dukakis insisted he wasn't bothered by Bentsen's support of
Contra aid.
   Bentsen spent most of Monday in private meetings in Washington
in preparation for expected action this week on trade and
plant-closing notification legislation.
   Dukakis, stepping up his efforts among the nation's black voters
who earlier backed Jesse Jackson's presidential bid, said in his
speech, ``We have to transform the cycle of poverty into a ladder
of opportunity, and that ladder must be sturdy and strong for all
our citizens.''
   ``Some people say it can't be done,'' he said. ``I say we
haven't tried.''
   Then, using a rhetorical tool often employed by Jackson, Dukakis
accused the Reagan administration of spending vast sums of money on
bad policies, following each contention with the refrain that at
the same time ``we haven't tried'' to help minorities and others.
   ``Fifteen billion dollars already wasted on Star Wars. We
haven't tried,'' Dukakis said. ``Thirty-six billion dollars for two
super-carrier task forces we don't need and can't afford. My
friends, we haven't tried.
   ``Hundreds of thousands of wasted lives, and millions of dollars
to overthrow the government of Nicaragua. My friends, we haven't
tried.
   ``An annual assault on the opportunity to go to college that has
left us with fewer black college students today than we had seven
years ago. We haven't tried.''
   In Chicago, meanwhile, Jackson, who lost the Democratic
nomination to Dukakis, said Monday he is willing to meet with New
York Mayor Edward Koch to try and iron out differences dating back
to Koch's strong crticism of Jackson before New York's April
primary.
   Koch, in New York, said, ``If you really believe as I do that
it's important to have a Democrat in the White House, you set aside
those differences.''
   Another former candidate, Republican Pat Robertson, returned
Monday as co-host of his cable network's flagship program, ``The
700 Club''.
   Dukakis received good news on the homefront before traveling to
Detroit.
   According to law enforcement sources who spoke only on condition
they not be named, the FBI has informed the state that a
preliminary inquiry turned up no evidence of law-breaking to
support charges that the Dukakis administration leaked confidential
information on prison-siting plans to developers who then bought
land and offered to sell it to the state.
   The allegations, lodged by opponents of plans to build a 500-bed
state prison in rural New Braintree, Mass., had been cited by
Dukakis critics to attack the good-government pledges at the center
of his presidential campaign.
   FBI Boston spokesman John Cloherty refused to characterize the
outcome of the inquiry but said no charges had been filed.
   In Washington, the Federal Election Commission told a federal
appeals court that the Democratic ticket should get $46 million in
matching funds despite a Republican contention that Bentsen was
benefiting unfairly. Bentsen is also running for re-election to his
Senate seat and has raised money for that race.
</TEXT>
