<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yemen-Government     08-01 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yemen-Government,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Yemen President Swears In New Cabinet After Elections</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SAN`A, North Yemen (AP) _ President Ali Abdullah Saleh swore in
a new Cabinet Monday and called on officials to ensure a prominent
role for the Red Sea state in international forums.
   He also urged closer cooperation with Marxist South Yemen, three
months after the two Arab neighbors eased travel restrictions and
settled a border dispute.
   Saleh, chairman for the first session of the 24-member Cabinet,
said a heightened international profile would ``crystallize the
country's role in serving just causes of humanity and issues of
world peace and stability, based on the principles of positive
neutrality and non-alignment.''
   Saleh made minor changes in the Cabinet following July 5
parliamentary elections.
   According to the constitution, Saleh also had to resign after
the elections but was quickly nominated by the 159-member
parliament, the Majlis Al-Shura, to a third five-year term.
   Abdel-Aziz Abdel-Ghani remained as prime minister along with his
four deputies. The minister of development, Mohammed Saeed
Al-Attar, retained his position and also was named as a fifth
deputy premier.
   Seven ministers retained their portfolios, seven others changed
Cabinet positions and five new ministers were named.
   Among the changes, a San`a military hospital doctor, Mohammad
Ali, became minister of health, and the ambassador to Morocco,
Mohammed Abdel-Hamid, was named minister of economy, supply and
trade.
   In May, North and smaller South Yemen agreed to ease travel
restrictions between their countries and settled a bitter dispute
over an oil field that straddles their border.
   Diplomatic sources quoted at the time said South Yemeni
representatives indicated they were willing to consider merging
with North Yemen in five years.
</TEXT>
