<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill 14 Shining Path</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers killed 14 Shining Path guerrillas
in a clash near this highland city, and a military sentry in Lima
was fatally wounded Monday during a foiled rebel attack, officials
said.
   The military command in Ayacucho, 225 miles southeast of Lima,
said a fierce firefight between troops and a Maoist guerrilla
column last Thursday on the city's isolated northeastern outskirts
left 14 rebels dead.
   The military reported the fighting here Sunday, but news reports
could not reach the capital, Lima, until Monday because of a
Shining Path attack last week on power pylons, which cut power
supplies and most telephone and microwave transmissions.
   Lima police said a military sentry at the Factory of Munitions
of the Army was fatally wounded at dawn Monday by suspected Shining
Path guerrillas, who attempted to plant a bomb at a gate.
   The assailants fled after shots were fired. Police said the
soldier died hours later in a hospital near the factory, located in
a northwestern suburb.
   Six women and four men were arrested in sweeps of the area
following the attack, police said.
   The government says the eight-year insurgency by the Shining
Path has claimed 15,000 lives and caused damage of $10 billion.
   The guerrillas seek to topple Peru's elected government and
impose Marxist rule, based on the worker-peasant state created by
China's Mao-Tse Tung.
