<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Rebels     08-01 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Rebels,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill 18 Rebels; Vandals Damage Aquino Tomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops killed 18 communist and Moslem
secessionist rebels in clashes, military reports said Monday. The
military also said vandals damaged the tomb of President Corazon
Aquino's husband.
   Maj. Hernando Patawaran, spokesman of the Presidential Security
Group, said vandals pried a concrete slab loose on the tomb of
assassinated former Sen. Benigno Aquino Jr., but the body was not
disturbed. Workers installed steel sheets to protect the body.
   In Bangkok, Thailand, Adm. Ronald J. Hays, commander-in-chief of
the U.S. Pacific Command, said Monday that if American bases in the
Philippines are lost, there will be ``only one big winner _ the
Soviet Union.''
   But Hays told reporters he was ``bullish about the future of the
bases.''
   The Philippines broke off talks on the bases with the United
States July 26. Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus said differences
over U.S. compensation for use of the bases were so wide he doubted
the talks could be revived. The agreement on Clark Air Base and
Subic Bay Naval Base expires in 1991.
   The official Philippine News Agency said troops killed nine
communist New People's Army guerrillas and wounded three in a
three-hour battle Sunday in Nueva Vizcaya province, 130 miles north
of Manila.
   It said government forces suffered no casualties.
   The clash occurred one day after marines and militiamen repulsed
two separate attacks by Moslem secessionists on Basilan and Jolo
islands, killing nine insurgents.
   A military report said about 80 members of the Moro National
Liberation Front tried to storm a marine camp on Basilan, 550 miles
south of Manila, but were driven away.
   Seven rebels were killed, the report said. It did not mention
government casualties. Two other Moslem seccessionists were killed
and four militiamen were wounded in a clash on on Jolo Island,
southwest of Basilan, another report said.
   The Moro front has been fighting for Moslem rule on Mindanao and
other southern islands since 1972.
   Patawaran said the vandalism of the Aquino tomb apparently
occurred Friday and was discovered Saturday after workers at the
Manila Memorial Park cemetery reported receiving a telephone call
that a bomb had been planted in the tomb.
   Patawaran said officials had no idea who desecrated the tomb or
why.
   Aquino was shot on Aug. 21, 1983, upon returning from three
years of self-imposed exile in the United States. His death fueled
opposition to President Ferdinand Marcos, culminating in a
civilian-military revolt that unseated Marcos in February 1986 and
drove him into exile after 20 years in office. The revolt swept
Mrs. Aquino into the presidency.
   Patawaran said workers cemented the slab back after bomb experts
found no explosives inside.
   Soldiers guarded the tomb Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
