<DOCNO> AP880801-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     08-01 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Studios Offer To Pay Union Fines For Returning Writers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two film studios said Monday they will pay
any union fines incurred by striking scriptwriters who return to
work while the union's 22-week strike continues.
   But a dissident group of writers, which has threatened
strike-breaking in the past, announced at the same time that it
would continue to honor the Writers Guild of America walkout.
   On Sunday, the contract talks were declared ``hopelessly
deadlocked'' by Nicholas Counter III, president of the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers. He added that it was
expected some union members would ignore guild warnings and return
to work.
   Jeffrey Katzenberg and Barry Diller, the respective heads of
Walt Disney Studios and 20th Century Fox, said that their studios
will compensate union members who return to work in violation of
union orders.
   Michael Binkow, a spokesman for Fox, confirmed Diller's offer.
Katzenberg's proposal was reported in Tuesday's editions of The New
York Times.
   Union fines against strike-breaking writers are set at 110
percent of all payment received for unauthorized strike work, said
union spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden. Furthermore, violators are subject
to lifetime expulsion from the guild, Rhoden said.
   Rhoden said that she knew of no movement within union ranks to
accept the indemnification proposal.
   ``It remains to be seen if any writers will be interested in
such protection or pseudo-protection,'' Rhoden said.
   Among those who have been expected to resign from the guild are
members of the Writers Coalition, 21 writers who have pushed for a
strike settlement under contract terms that union members have
strongly opposed.
   The coalition, after a four-hour strategy conference Monday,
announced that it would remain with the guild. The group was
apparently encouraged by a discussion with Brian Walton, executive
director of the WGA West and the guild's chief negotiator.
   The coalition had threatened to leave the guild on July 28 but
changed its plans last week when negotiations appeared to be making
progress.
   The strike by more than 9,000 union members began March 7.
   Meanwhile, Walton said on a recorded union hot line message
Monday that he hoped all members ``will decline (the) invitation''
to write during the strike.
   Walton said, too, that the WGA has asked the U.S. Labor
Department not to grant work visas to foreign writers coming to the
United States to write for Hollywood production companies during
the strike.
   ``Indemnification is a matter for discussion between each studio
and a specific writers,'' Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the
producers alliance, said Monday. ``(Indemnification) is not an
alliance function.''
   Rhoden said that any indemnification payments would be seen by
the union as compensation and therefore subject to further fines.
   ``The production companies are not concerned about the
writers,'' Rhoden said. ``They are looking for their own short-term
gain. One writing assignment is not worth a whole career. And
people do not forget when people cross a picket line in the middle
of a strike.''
   The union has so far handed out more than $2 million in hardship
loans to its finacially strapped members, Rhoden said.
   Meanwhile, the union was optimistic that contract talks with the
producers might resume, and placed the blame for last weekend's
negoatiating collapse on the alliance.
   ``We are doing all that we can to continue the negotiating
process,'' Walton said on the union's hot line message. ``It's
regrettable that the alliance has no such commitment to the
industry.''
   The producers have insisted that the union is making
unreasonable demands and repeatedly refuses to make any contract
compromises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0190 </DOCNO>
