<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0754 08-01 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0754,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Continue In Yellowstone; New Blazes In Surrounding Forests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 10 through 14, `Fire bosses...', with four grafs
to UPDATE with Willis Gulch fire contained and cause, delete
outdated quote, update containment of Riordan Lake. Picks up 15th
graf pvs, `In southwestern...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gusty wind fanned fires in Yellowstone National Park to greater
size Monday, and hundreds of firefighters were sent to the fire
lines in Idaho in a drive to contain a week-old fire in rugged
terrain.
   Fires also burned in Utah, Washington, Oregon and Montana.
   More than 125,500 acres had been burned in Yellowstone, the
oldest national park.
   High wind Sunday, and again on Monday, combined with backburning
intended to stop the blazes, spread the North Fork fire about four
miles west of the Old Faithful geyser complex from 11,300 acres to
12,700 in 24 hours, said fire information officer Earl LaOrange.
   About 360 firefighters were sent out Monday to re-establish fire
lines along the southern and eastern edges of the fire where the
wind pushed flames over fire breaks, said Larry Blade, another fire
information officer.
   Also jumping substantially in size was the Fan fire in the
park's northwestern corner, from 7,500 acres to roughly 11,600,
said LaOrange. The Lewis Lake or Red fire near Grant Village
covered 12,700 acres Monday and the nearby Shoshone fire had
blackened 13,100 acres, he said.
   The Wyoming Travel Commission opened a hot line Monday to answer
tourists' questions about the fire at Yellowstone.
   ``The forest fires have certainly gained us national attention,
but we are concerned that tourists planning to visit Yellowstone
and the Cowboy State may change their plans,'' said commission
director Gene Bryan.
   East of Yellowstone in the Bighorn National Forest, about 500
firefighters returned to work Monday in a drive to control two
fires covering an estimated 2,550 acres.
   Fire bosses in Idaho used more than 1,150 firefighters to
contain the 5,000-acre Willis Gulch fire in central Idaho, which
officials have determined was started by a cigarette.
   Most of the work in the rocky terrain had to be done by hand,
said Boise National Forest Service spokeswoman Jean Hawthorne said.
``The country is so steep and rugged, bulldozers can only do so
much,'' she said.
   The seven-day-old blaze about 35 miles northeast of Boise had
destroyed $7.5 million worth of timber and other resources and cost
over $1 million to fight.
   Elsewhere in Idaho, some 200 firefighters reached 90 percent
containment of the 110-acre Riordan Lake fire, burning in heavy
timber in a remote roadless area near Cascade. Fire bosses expected
full containment by Tuesday evening.
   In southwestern Montana, firefighters closed roads into the Lake
Como area Monday and shut down its recreational facilities as they
drove to complete lines around the Rock Creek fire, which had
burned 3,200 acres of the Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness and the
Bitterroot National Forest since July 22.
   Forest information officer Jo Barnier said 682 firefighters had
completed lines around 90 percent of the fire.
   A Texas man accused of starting that fire appeared in court
Monday on a misdemeanor charge of allowing a camp fire to escape,
Barnier said.
   Low temperatures and high humidity helped efforts to contain
three fires burning in Washington state, said Department of Natural
Resources and U.S. Forest Service officials.
   The largest, the 3,600-acre Falls Creek fire, was 90 percent
contained, said Forest Service spokeswoman Kathy Albert. A 55-acre
fire on the Olympic Peninsula near Hoquiam was under control and
firefighters had almost suppressed a 75-acre blaze near Skykomish,
officials said.
   High wind Monday morning in Oregon hampered efforts to contain
an 145-acre fire in the Mount Hood National Forest, but spokeswoman
Jane Cottrell said a line had been built around 95 percent of the
fire. She said firefighters expect to have it contained by Tuesday.
   A three-mile section of a Forest Service road was closed as
officials expressed concern for the safety of mountain bikers who
had been seen in the vicinity, Cottrell said.
   In southern Oregon, firefighters contained nearly 90 small
blazes Sunday on private and public lands.
   In northern Utah, a crew battled a 400-acre fire, said
Interagency Fire Center dispatcher Bill Brooks.
</TEXT>
