<NOTE>For Release Thursday, Aug. 11</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Aug. 11, the 224th day of 1988. There are 142
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 11, 1965, rioting and looting broke out in the
predominantly black Watts section of Los Angeles after police
arrested a black man suspected of drunken driving. In the following
week, 34 people were killed and more than 1,000 injured.
   On this date:
   In 1860, the nation's first successful silver mill began
operating near Virginia City, Nev.
   In 1909, the SOS distress signal was first used by an American
ship, the Arapahoe, off Cape Hatteras, N.C.
   In 1934, the first federal prisoners arrived at the island
prison of Alcatraz in San Francisco Bay.
   In 1945, the Allies responded to Japan's offer to surrender
provided Emperor Hirohito retain his sovereignty. The Allies said
they would determine the emperor's status.
   In 1954, a formal peace took hold, ending more than seven years
of fighting in Indochina between the French and Communist Vietminh.
   In 1956, abstract artist Jackson Pollock died in an automobile
accident in East Hampton, N.Y.
   In 1962, the Soviet Union launched cosmonaut Andrian Nikolayev
into orbit for a flight that would last more than 94 hours.
   In 1975, the United States vetoed the proposed admission of
North and South Vietnam to the United Nations after the Security
Council's refusal to consider South Korea's application.
   In 1980, hours before the Democratic National Convention opened
in New York, Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy withdrew from the
presidential race.
   In 1984, during a voice test for a paid political radio address,
President Reagan made a joke overheard by reporters in which he
said he had ``signed legislation that would outlaw Russia forever.
We begin bombing in five minutes.''
   Ten years ago: Chiefs of state and foreign dignitaries arrived
in Vatican City for the funeral of Pope Paul VI, who had died
August 6 at age 80. Leading the U.S. delegation was first lady
Rosalynn Carter.
   Five years ago: President Reagan met at the White House with his
new, 12-member commission on Central America, urging the panel to
develop long-range economic and social reforms for the region.
   One year ago: Britain and France ordered mine sweepers to the
Persian Gulf, but said they would not be used in combined
operations with the United States as it escorted reflagged Kuwaiti
ships.
   Today's birthdays: Author Alex Haley is 67. TV talk show host
Mike Douglas is 63. Newspaper columnist Carl Rowan is 63. The Rev.
Jerry Falwell is 55. Actress Anna Massey is 51. Singer Eric Carmen
is 39.
   Thought for today: ``A pessimist is a man who looks both ways
when he's crossing a one-way street.'' _ Laurence J. Peter,
Canadian educator and author of ``The Peter Principle.''
</TEXT>
