<NOTE>For Release Friday, Aug. 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Aug. 12, the 225th day of 1988. There are 141
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 12, 1898, Hawaii was formally annexed to the United
States after Congress passed a joint resolution. Hawaii was granted
territorial status in 1900, and became the 50th state of the union
in 1959.
   On this date:
   In 1851, Isaac Singer was granted a patent on his sewing machine.
   In 1867, President Andrew Johnson sparked a move to impeach him
as he defied Congress by suspending Secretary of War Edwin M.
Stanton.
   In 1898, the peace protocol ending the Spanish-American War was
signed.
   In 1915, the novel ``Of Human Bondage,'' by William Somerset
Maugham, was published.
   In 1941, French Marshal Henri Petain called on his countrymen to
give their full support to Nazi Germany.
   In 1948, Soviet schoolteacher Oksana Kasenkina survived a leap
from a window of the Soviet consulate in New York to avoid being
returned to her homeland.
   In 1953, the Soviet Union conducted a secret test of its first
hydrogen bomb.
   In 1955, President Dwight D. Eisenhower signed a bill raising
the minimum wage from 75 cents to $1 an hour, effective the
following March.
   In 1960, the first balloon satellite, Echo I, was launched by
the United States from Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   In 1962, one day after launching cosmonaut Andrian Nikolayev
into orbit, the Soviet Union also sent up cosmonaut Pavel Popovich.
Both men landed safely August 15.
   In 1972, the last American combat ground troops left Vietnam.
   In 1977, the space shuttle Enterprise passed its first solo
flight test by taking off atop a Boeing 747, separating, and then
touching down on its own in California's Mojave Desert.
   In 1982, actor Henry Fonda died in Los Angeles at age 77.
   In 1985, the world's worst single-aircraft disaster took place
as a Japan Airlines Boeing 747 crashed during a domestic flight,
killing 520 people.
   Ten years ago: Pope Paul VI, who had died August 6 at age 80,
was buried in St. Peter's Basilica after an outdoor funeral Mass
attended by thousands of mourners who heard the late pontiff
eulogized as a ``true prince of peace.''
   Five years ago: President Reagan opened a drive for Hispanic
political support as he denounced Cuba's communist government in a
speech to the Hispanic Chamber of Commerce in Tampa, Fla.
   One year ago: President Reagan addressed the nation on the
Iran-Contra affair, saying his former national security adviser,
John Poindexter, was wrong not to have told him about the diversion
of Iran arms-sale money. ``I had the right, the obligation, to make
my own decisions,'' Reagan said.
   Today's birthdays: Comedian-actor Cantinflas is 77. Actress Jane
Wyatt is 76. Choreographer Michael Kidd is 69. Sen. Dale Bumpers,
D-Ark., is 63. Actor-director John Derek is 62. Actor George
Hamilton is 49.
   Thought for today: ``Everybody talks too much, too many words,
and gets them out of order.'' _ Lillian Hellman, American author
and playwright (1905-1984).
</TEXT>
