<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv02   08-01 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 02,0648</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday Aug 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Do Cassandras Mismeasure the Economy?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy is now in its 69th month of
expansion, and according to a very popular view, three score and
ten is time sufficient _meaning the expansion should now roll over
and die.
   It is not a foolish concept, since aging expansions in years
past have always developed deteriorations similar to the organic,
muscular and osteo problems of human old age. But the concept is
perhaps overly simple.
   The average post-war economic expansion has averaged 45 months,
and ever since that average was surpassed two years ago the number
of Cassandras has grown. They view further growth as bad, a
recession as welcome.
   The reasoning is this: Factories are operating at near capacity
and cannot produce more; unemployment is down to the
scraping-the-bottom level, and that means job openings can be
filled only with less productive workers.
   Such measurements in the past have preceded inflation. Thus, a
recession is inevitable, and the sooner the better, the pessimists
argue.
   But some elements don't seem to fit.
   ``Growth needn't be inflationary if it is based on solid
productivity gains,'' says Prudential-Bache's Edward Yardeni, who
believes some notions about economic expansions, rather than
expansion itself, might be dated.
   Whereas the Cassandras fear that further growth will put too
much stress on the system, Yardeni and some others observe that
growth is what's needed to narrow the federal deficit.
   But what about the tight job market, ask the pessimists?
   To which those of more positive mind respond by calling
attention to the billions of dollars industry is spending on more
efficient plants and equipment, thus reducing the stress.
   In fact, economists of a positive bent point out, not all price
increases are inflationary. Why, they remind us, a price increase
accompanied by a bigger rise in product quality can actually be
anti-inflationary.
   Surprised by the persistence of economic expansion in spite of
their dire forecasts, some economists are now reviewing their basic
notions. They concede there is no better proof or disproof than the
economy itself.
   Incredibly, one factor that could explain the negativism is the
neglect of the newer, service sector of the economy, while
stressing the older industrial segment.
   Three-quarters of employment, 67 percent of gross national
product and 90 percent of new jobs are in the service sector.
Nevertheless, they figure less strongly in most analyses than do
older industrial measurements.
   Geoffrey H. Moore and Allan P. Layton of Columbia University
suggest that studies of the service sector do not always fit into
neatly constructed concepts of what the economy should be doing. In
short, there might be a built-in bias toward using industrial
rather than service indicators.
   They contend that ``one reason for this is that many of the
service industries have continued to grow during business cycle
contractions as well as expansions.''
   Therefore, ``indicators that skip recessions do not get a good
rating, and hence tend to be rejected.''
   Moore and Layton have developed service indicators for the
Center for International Business Research at Columbia, financed by
the Coalition of Service Industries. The first quarterly report has
just been issued.
   In that report, economist Allen Sinai analyzed the data and
concluded there will be continued expansion in the service sector
but at a somewhat slackened pace than had been so earlier in the
expansion.
   His conclusion: ``Service-sector economic activity is continuing
to expand nicely, but goods-sector activity is now driving the
economy.
   ``The pace of services economics has softened compared with
1987, but does not pose any difficulty for the overall economy or
job growth at this time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday Aug 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ADifferentLife Adv08   08-01 1110</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-A Different Life, Adv 08,1142</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Aug. 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Woman's `Counterclockwise' Journey from Ad Exec to Counselor of
Poor</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Harlem is a long way from Madison Avenue
but Annie Troy has made what she calls the ``counterclockwise''
passage, choosing sacrifice among the poor over affluence in the ad
game.
   Ten years after she left Ohio for the big city, Troy had risen
to a $42,000-a-year job as creative supervisor of a large New York
advertising agency.
   She gave it up, and now, at 35, is executive director of Emmaus
House Inc., a work and counseling program for about 50 formerly
homeless people in East Harlem. She lives and works with them,
subsisting on the same $25-a-week allowance that they receive.
   In a neighborhood where gunfire keeps her indoors at night, Troy
spends much of her day running up and down stairs. Among walls hung
with pictures of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., the pale, slight
redhead deals with everything from buying bathroom mirrors and
supervising food deliveries to finding a new drug counselor.
   In the 18 months she's lived at Emmaus, Troy has come to miss
her old neighborhood, her privacy and sometimes her old career. She
misses shopping and seeing her friends.
   ``The little things can become a real big treat now, like
getting together with a friend at a restaurant,'' she said. ``I
enjoyed the freedom of being able to buy what I wanted. ...
   ``But it's also a freedom in saying `OK, I think I have
enough.'''
   Three years ago, Troy lost a friend to AIDS. Searching for a way
to cope, she returned to church after a long break from her
Lutheran upbringing.
   In a sermon one day at St. George's Episcopal Church on East
16th Street, the priest discussed a man who established missions
for the poor and an integrated New York church in the 19th century.
The man, Stephen Tyng, was Troy's great-great-great-grandfather.
   Her astonishment at the coincidence of hearing about her
forebear in that church and her amazement at the breadth of his
accomplishments sparked a change in her. As she sat there, she
says, ``my eyes were opened to faith.''
   ``Most people don't need a religious experience,'' she said,
``but I guess I needed it to get my attention.''
   Troy began to spend her free time helping with mostly
administrative chores at a low-income housing construction project
on Manhattan's Lower East Side. After a month, they offered her a
job as assistant director, at a pay cut of more than 50 percent
from her advertising job. She accepted.
   Turning to the church had ``started my thinking going
counterclockwise to where it had been,'' she said. ``It didn't seem
like being competitive and making more money was really the thing
to put my time on anymore. ... I just started to think `if I'm
going to work this hard, maybe I could work this hard on something
that would really help people.'''
   Father David Kirk founded Emmaus in 1966; two years ago it moved
from a brownstone to what had been a hotel notorious for
prostitution and drug-dealing. Arsonists gutted the building twice
before Emmaus could move in. Now, Troy says, the dealers and
prostitutes join the 250 people fed in Emmaus' soup kitchen each
weekday.
   Kirk talks of how much simpler and quieter life at Emmaus used
to be, before homelessness and poverty intensified, before the
advent of crack cocaine.
   For a woman reared in a small town near Dayton, Emmaus was full
of revelations, despite what Troy already knew of New York.
   A drug addict would come to her room for a friendly chat _ and
leave with her watch. She felt betrayed until she sought guidance
from a drug counselor, who taught her to look beyond the lies and
manipulative behavior into the pain of a person bent only on
getting their next fix.
   When people go to serve the poor, says Troy, they're full of
romantic visions _ of rescuing lives, of finding a reward in
grateful faces. They soon learn that the changes take longer, that
successes are relative and that helpers, like those being helped,
are only human.
   ``If you try to live according to that dream,'' Troy said, ``you
get disappointed in yourself and in the others real fast.''
   This spring, after six weeks of daily struggles to get out of
bed, she recognized signs of the burnout that had hit her
predecessor. She left for two weeks at a farm and Catholic retreat
in Canada, where people are trained to work with the poor and
counseling is given to those who already do. On arrival they took
one look at her tired face and put her in the infirmary.
   A month or so later, Troy looks weary again. She says she rarely
thinks about returning to advertising, just occasionally when in a
``snit.'' But she won't try to predict where she might be 10 years
from now. ``Ten years ago,'' she says, ``I never would have dreamed
I'd be here.''
   Though she stays in touch with her family and though her
devoutly religious mother, in particular, supports what she does,
one of the hardest adjustments to life at Emmaus was losing touch
with her friends.
   Emergencies _ from a resident who's upset to a potential
knife-fight in the soup kitchen _ often interfere with Troy's
outside plans, and her friends are reluctant to visit in East
Harlem. When they do get together, there are awkward first moments
until they find themselves, once more, on equal ground.
   ``I guess there's something kind of odd,'' Troy said, ``about
this friend who leaves it all to go to work with the poor'' and who
becomes devout.
   But as she sees it, there can be as much stress in her old world
as she has now.
   At Emmaus, Troy said, her religious conviction has been
strengthened: ``There's so much that's beyond my ken or control, or
anybody's ability to help.''
   She turned to Roman Catholicism in October 1986, drawn by the
church's devotion to the Virgin Mary and the accessibility of its
weekday services.
   But her faith in human nature has suffered.
   ``I see the devastation that's happening with these people,''
she said, ``and I see on the other side people who are begrudging
even giving out that dime to somebody begging. ... I really see
that the problem is far more severe than I had ever thought.''
   ``Then,'' she said, ``I have to turn to the individual for my
hope.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Aug. 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
