<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-TabascoSauce Adv10   08-01 1177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tabasco Sauce, Adv 10,1214</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Aug. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>In Home of Tabasco, `Hot Sauces are Almost a Religion'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AVERY ISLAND, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roll down the car window anywhere near
the plant where Louisiana's most famous hot sauce still is made
from a century-old recipe, and your head just fills up with the
scent _ a little tomatoey, a little spicy, a lot hot.
   The odor is so much a part of the place that Paul C.P.
McIlhenny, whose family has been making Tabasco sauce from the
start, doesn't even notice it unless he's up close to the pulp
barrels.
   Hot sauce in southern Louisiana is like that smell. It's
everywhere. On every table in every restaurant. Two dozen or so
varieties. Louisiana hot sauce is a tourist attraction: It's on
posters and coffee mugs and key chains, and people take tours of
hot sauce factories.
   ``In the river parishes, where the Acadians first landed, its
hard not to find a bottle of Louisiana hot sauce on the table,''
said John Folse, a chef and restaurateur in Donaldsonville who
introduced Cajun food to Moscow during the summit meeting earlier
this year. ``It's almost like salt, pepper and Louisiana hot.''
   There is, of course, the theory that people who live in such
steamy heat eat hot foods to perspire and cool off.
   ``My mother's people and my father's people grew hot peppers
because they thought they were good for you,'' said television's
down-home Cajun chef, Justin Wilson.
   But there's much more than science at work in a land where what
to eat for dinner is often the focus of luncheon conversation and
what to eat tomorrow is the dinner-table talk. Good food really
matters here.
   ``When someone asks, `What are you doing this afternoon?, You
say, `Oh I don't know, maybe a crawfish boil.' They always think in
terms of cooking,'' said Folse.
   And most everything _ even to a bloody Mary sorbet, says Folse _
gets a dash or two of hot sauce.
   ``I don't think anything's worth a darn unless it's seasoned
well,'' said Wilson, who is partial to cayenne peppers.
   McIlhenny, 44, vice president of the McIlhenny Co., figures he
goes through a 2-ounce bottle a month of Tabasco, which, by the
way, is not a generic name, though McIlhenny's pleased if you think
so.
   Hot sauce is addictive, he said. ``I've had friends use it out
of loyalty, and then say, `Hey, this is good,' as if it was a
surprise. They say they get addicted.''
   So it's no surprise there are so many kinds _ Tabasco,
Trappey's, Tony Cachere's Creole Hot Sauce, Crystal Hot Sauce,
Cajun Chef, Louisiana Gold, Durkee Sauce, Panola Red, Cajun Power
Hot Sauce. You get the idea.
   A premium sauce, it's agreed, uses only the pepper pulp. No
seeds or skin. Most contain just salt, vinegar and peppers,
although some labels say it fancier. Crystal, for example, lists
``fresh ripe aged peppers,'' and Cajun Chef contains ``select
Louisiana cayenne peppers.''
   So, can connoisseurs distinguish among them?
   Sure, said Folse, noting that most chefs stock four of five
varieties.
   ``I've got items in my kitchen I use Tabasco on. However, I also
really like Louisiana Gold,'' he said. ``I don't find that it's
quite as hot as Tabasco ... and when you have five or six chefs on
the line, you want to have a little control. If they put one shot
or two shots, you don't want to change the flavor competely.''
   ``They all have a little different flavor, and they all use a
little different amounts of vinegar, salt,'' said Wilson. ``There
are certain ones I prefer. ... It's just a question of experience,
and God knows I have a lot of that.''
   The McIlhenny Co., too, has plenty of experience. Tabasco is
sold in 100 countries; it's been on space missions.
   ``We end up in strange places,'' said McIlhenny. ``I understand
two or three Sherpas in Nepal will use a bottle at a single meal.''
   Nepal is a long way from tiny Avery Island, 18 square miles that
are home to 700 people, the Tabasco plant and fields, a salt mine
and oil wells. There also are 100,000 snowy egrets, 30,000 azaleas
and 17,000 irises.
   Avery Island is not really an island, but a salt dome that rises
from the marshes and bayous on Louisiana's Gulf Coast. At 152 feet
above sea level, the island is the highest point along the gulf
from Mexico to Florida. It sits 150 miles from New Orleans,
separated by sugar cane, rice and oil fields.
   In 1818, John Craig Marsh obtained rights to part of the island,
and later a Louisiana judge, Daniel Dudley Avery, bought part. In
1837 Avery married Marsh's daughter and eventually obtained the
entire island.
   In 1859, Edmund McIlhenny married an Avery daughter. The story
is told, though not verified, that the family fled Avery Island in
the Civil War and returned to find everything destroyed _ except
one defiant pepper plant grown from a seed or seedling given to
Edmund by a friend returning from Mexico.
   What is known is that Edmund McIlhenny came up with a sauce to
perk up the bland food available during Reconstruction. n 1868, he
packed his invention in ladies' perfume bottles, and sent samples
off to 350 wholesalers. Two years later he had a patent, and in two
years more a London office to handle all the European orders.
   His sauce used a variety of Capsicum frutescens, a small
fire-engine-red pepper, of which the McIlhenny Co. today is the
world's largest producer. Tabasco is an Indian word for damp earth,
which McIlhenny apparently chose because he liked the sound of it.
   One hundred twenty years later, little has changed. McIlhenny is
still a family company, with Paul McIlhenny and two cousins in
charge. And Avery Island is their kingdom.
   ``This is an ideal site,'' said McIlhenny. ``Part of the
mystique is that only the soil, only the climate, only the nimble
fingers of Avery Island could pick Tabasco.''
   The peppers are harvested in summer, by hand, and must be
processed the same day.
   But today, only 10 percent of the peppers needed are grown on
the island. To protect against disease, pests, hurricanes and labor
troubles, seeds for the rest of the peppers are sent to Central and
South America. The mash is returned to Avery Island.
   Paul McIlhenny inspects every white oak barrel of mash for
aroma, color, particle size. He rejects one barrel in 100.
   The pulp is mashed with salt _ eight pounds to 100 pounds of
peppers _ and aged three years. The mash is then mixed with a
strong white vinegar and stirred mechanically for 28 days. Finally,
it is strained and bottled.
   And even then it's not just a bottle of sauce.
   ``Hot sauces in Louisiana are almost a religion,'' said Folse.
``You go to church on Sunday, hot sauce on Monday through Friday.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Aug. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
