<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--Shultz Adv14-2Takes   08-01 1116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Shultz, Adv 14-2 Takes,1147</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ As the Reagan administration's lease on the
White House runs out, so does George Shultz's tenure as secretary
of state. He leaves behind him no foreign policy ``doctrine,'' no
ringing rhetoric. But world affairs have changed significantly
during his stewardship, and now peace seems to be erupting in
unexpected places. Here's a portrait of a low-key diplomat who
seems to have been more concerned with the process than with
himself.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He sometimes talked about his job as
``pick-and-shovel work'' and himself as a ``gardener,'' images no
one would have pinned to the office that Henry Kissinger endowed
with jet-set glitter, John Foster Dulles with a prophetic edge, and
Dean Acheson with aristocratic elegance.
   Those three earlier secretaries of state over the past
half-century performed naturally on a floodlit stage that George
Shultz just as naturally avoids.
   Unlike them, he's never been the source of memorable quotations.
Despite his years as a Washington insider, he much resembles what
in fact he is: a Stanford University professor on leave.
   ``They've established a chair in my honor,'' he has said. ``I
told them that when I'm through with this job, I'll need a couch.''
   He'll be through in January, along with the administration he
serves, but its twilight is seeing a remarkable splurge of
peacemaking in U.S. diplomacy.
   Peace may be coming to Angola and southwestern Africa, where
preliminary agreements may point to the ultimate withdrawal of up
to 50,000 Cuban troops. Iran, in a startling turnabout, has
accepted a cease-fire in its war with Iraq. Soviet troops are
leaving Afghanistan. Pro-Soviet Vietnam is accelerating a military
withdrawal from Cambodia.
   Peace in Central America is more elusive and in the Middle East,
where Shultz has expended much effort, negotiations between
Israelis and Arabs seem as distant as ever.
   Shultz's interest in the Mideast antedates his appointment as
secretary of state. He is former president of the Bechtel group, an
international construction and engineering firm that made a fortune
in the Arab world.
   When President Reagan appointed Shultz in July 1982, his views
on the Middle East came under intense congressional scrutiny.
Against the apprehensions of some, he has emerged as one of
Israel's staunchest friends.
   On a recent visit to Amman, Shultz told a group of Jordanian
journalists that a total Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank was
``not in the cards,'' and neither was a Palestinian state.
   Traditionally, diplomats make cooing sounds in such
circumstances. Jordanian authorities never permitted the interview
to appear in print or on the air.
   Shultz, 67, will leave office without leaving a foreign policy
``doctrine'' or historic milestone associated with his name. Some
see his main accomplishment as secretary of state is keeping a
highly conservative administration on a moderate course in dealing
with the Soviet Union.
   His approach dovetailed with the rise to power in Moscow three
years ago of a pragmatic Soviet leader, Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
U.S.-Soviet summit meetings are now annual occurrences.
   How much credit belongs to Shultz? How much to Gorbachev? And
how much to Reagan, who not so long ago called the Soviet Union an
``evil empire''?
   It's anybody's guess. But the fact is that the two sides signed
a historic treaty last year to abolish all U.S. and Soviet
intermediate-range nuclear missiles and to exchange inspectors to
ensure the deal is kept. The way was cleared in monthly meetings
between Shultz and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Moreover, there is a framework in place for the next president _
Democrat or Republican _ to make more weapons cutbacks and to
reconcile superpower differences around the world.
   ``So far as his recognition that there's been a fundamental
change in the Soviet Union, he's been a good influence in toning
down the president,'' said former Undersecretary of State George W.
Ball, otherwise a critic of Shultz, especially on the Middle East.
   Shultz also eased frictions with Congress and strengthened U.S.
ties with the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and with Japan and
other Asian allies.
   ``He's been upfront,'' said Rep. Dante Fascell, chairman of the
House Foreign Affairs Committee. ``He's well liked by Congress. We
don't always agree with him. But the judgment on both sides of the
aisle is he's a good secretary of state.''
   Did Shultz try hard to talk Reagan out of sending American TOW
missiles to the Iranians in a futile attempt to free American
hostages in Lebanon?
   ``I wonder if there is more that I could have done,'' Shultz
said after the Iran-Contra scandal broke. ``I believe there was. I
don't give myself any plus on this.''
   Some on Capitol Hill are more critical. Rep. Robert G.
Toricelli, D-N.J., who heard him in closed testimony before the
House of Foreign Affairs Committee, says Shultz ``did more than
separate himself from White House policies on Iran. He built a wall
between himself and the White House.''
   Critics of the president's ambitious and, they say, fanciful
Star Wars project wonder if Shultz tried to slow the project down
and have found him ambiguous.
   Asked on national television whether he supported or opposed a
so-called ``broad interpretation'' of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty to allow debatable tests and early deployment,
Shultz played it close to the vest.
   The result was a headline in The New York Times the next morning
that ``Shultz Rules Out `Star Wars' Move Within Two Years'' and a
headline in The Washington Post, ``Shultz Accepts Broad View Of ABM
Pact.''
   Quizzed by Congress, Shultz was not much clearer. He said the
program should be deployed only after it was found to be effective
and worth the enormous investment in it.
   Was he subtly trying to slow down the program, which Caspar
Weinberger, then the defense secretary and a former Bechtel
colleague, was eager to deploy? Or was he for Star Wars full blast?
   ``I don't have a clear picture where he stands on Star Wars,''
former U.S. arms control director Paul Warnke says. ``I think he
felt this was the president's magnificent obsession and he wasn't
going to do anything about it.''
   But Warnke, an ardent proponent of arms control, gives Shultz
high grades for vigorously promoting the missile-ban treaty. ``He
definitely had his heart in arms control,'' Warnke says.
   Similarly, former Sen. J. William Fulbright, who practices law
in Washington and still keeps an eye on foreign policy trends, says
that what pleases him most is ``this move toward conciliation with
the Russians.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--Shultz Adv14-1stAdd   08-01 1066</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Shultz, Adv 14-1st Add,1088</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: the Russians.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On the other hand, Fulbright, a former chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, calls the hard-line U.S. policy in
Central America ``a great mistake.'' And in the Middle East, he
says, ``We've always been so completely supportive of Israel
there's not much chance of a compromise.''
   George Ball, who held an important State Department post in the
Kennedy administration, concurs. He faults Shultz for ``inepitude''
in trying to work out a deal between Israel and Lebanon in 1982
without consulting Syria, and then ignoring President Hafez Assad
for years because he didn't go along.
   Fascell credits Shultz with toughness and willingess to lay his
prestige on the line in Central America and the Middle East,
``although you can't say Lebanon was a success.'' There, 241 U.S.
servicemen were killed in October 1983 when a Marine command center
was blown up. U.S. peacekeeping forces, which critics said had been
foolishly exposed, were then withdrawn.
   Joseph Laitin, a longtime government press officer who worked
for Shultz at the Office and Management and Budget, tried to
explain Shultz this way:
   ``You have to remember the animal trainer describing how an
elephant moves. He puts one leg forward, shifts his body over to
that foot to see if it will hold him, then moves the next foot
forward. He never leaves his moorings in one place without having
another mooring. He's no great risk-taker.''
   The ringing declaration, the apocalyptic pronouncement were not
Shultz's style. He didn't convey the impression that the world's
fate hinged on his success in persuading foreign leaders to support
his policies.
   For six years, plodding through U.S.-Soviet, Middle East arms
control diplomacy, he methodically recited to reporters, ``You
don't have an agreement until you have an agreement,'' which seems
to echo baseball's Yogi Berra's, ``It ain't over till it's over.''
   But if reporters found the secretary less than electrifying,
neither did he play games with them, such as hiding behind
``background'' and not-for-attribution rituals in the ancient
Washington tradition. He said what he had to say on the record,
even when it meant admitting the failure of a high-stakes mission.
   And he persevered. He worked in behalf of Jews and other
minorities who were prevented from emigrating from the Soviet
Union. He made a point of giving human rights a ``pride of place''
on his agenda in all his sessions with Soviet leaders. He arranged
meetings with dissidents in Moscow and emigres in Jerusalem to lend
symbolic support to their cause.
   Low-key team player that he was much of the time, Shultz could
dissent sharply and publicly. He bristled at a White House order in
1985 to subject all government officials in sensitive positions to
lie detector tests. Shultz would have none of it personally and
threatened to resign unless the order was modified. It was.
   When Reagan two years ago decided to sell subsidized wheat to
the Soviet Union, Shultz called the sales ``ridiculous.'' Having
led the opposition within the administration, he kept up his
criticism after he lost. The Soviets, he said, must be chortling
over paying less for American-produced food than American
housewives.
   There was risk in such self-assertion. Shultz told the House and
Senate Iran-Contras investigating committees, ``You must be willing
to say goodbye, and I am.''
   He had offered to quit on two other occasions.
   One was in 1983 when he discovered that Robert C. McFarlane,
then the deputy national security adviser, had made a secret trip
to several Mideast states without Shultz's knowledge. He said he
told Reagan, ``Mr. President, you don't need a guy like me for
secretary of state if this is the way things are going to be done.''
   The other came in August 1986 when Shultz thought some
conservatives in the White House subjected him to ``a kind of
guerrilla warfare,'' to the point of hamstringing his authority to
use government aircraft for his State Department business.
   Shultz served in the Marines in World War II and met his wife,
Helena O'Brien, in Hawaii, where she was an Army nurse. They have
five children and five grandchildren.
   When Reagan asked Shultz to succeed Alexander Haig Jr. in June
1982, he was summoned from London, where he had been on a business
trip. Shultz was to meet with the president at Camp David, and he
found two limousines waiting for him at the airport. One was for
him, he was told, the other to take his wife wherever she wanted to
go while he had his interview with the president.
   Shultz waved off the second car. ``No, she will come with me,''
he said. ``We are a package deal.''
   He is the first man in history to have served in four Cabinet
posts _ State, Labor, Treasury and the Office of Management and
Budget _ 11 years in all of Cabinet service. A measure of his
aptitude for conciliation and avoiding controversy is that he held
three of these posts under Richard M. Nixon and emerged unscathed
by any of that administration's notoriety and scandal.
   Joseph Laitin's theory, shared by others, is that while Shultz
is a team player, he also has a well-developed ``protective
mechanism.''
   ``It was not that he was fighting them all the time,'' says
Laitin. ``There was an old-shoe relationship between Shultz and
Nixon. Shultz will go along, but at some point instinctively he'll
hunker down. He will not budge, because he's a man of character.''
   As secretary of the treasury, he disregarded a Nixon White House
request to have the Internal Revenue Service harass ``enemies'' of
the administration, provoking Nixon to unflattering comments. And
when Nixon complained about an IRS audit of his tax return, Shultz
told him that every recent president had been similarly audited.
   He showed no signs of winding down as his tenure neared its end.
So far this year, Shultz has made four trips to the Middle East,
three to the Soviet Union, and a 17-day swing through Asia.
   Why did he keep returning to the Mideast despite the refusal of
Israelis and Arabs to heed his plea to negotiate? Shultz explained
he didn't mind fighting long odds, and if he didn't succeed
himself, he wanted to lay some groundwork for his successor.
   Besides, he said, ``What am I saving myself for?''
   End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--SeniorGolfers Adv14-2Takes   08-01 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Senior Golfers, Adv 14-2 Takes,0837</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Was there ever a golden era of sports in the dim
past, as touted by septuagenarian chroniclers? Maybe not, but
there's one right now. It's the PGA Senior Tour, where golf's
ancient rake in the lucre in post-career careers that lack the
pressure and cutthroat solemnity of youthful competition but make
up for it in sheer pleasure on the back nine of life.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At times the senior scene seems lifted live from the frame of an
old Dutch golfing print, the whimsical kind you still find hanging
in country club corridors and locker rooms.
   Genial gentlemen of mellowing vintage in broad-brimmed hats and
knickerbockers bent over long crooked sticks in studious pursuit of
nudging a small white ball across a pleasant expanse of lawn. Or
perhaps these are Scottish shepherds who have lost their sheep in
the Highland heather.
   Weep no idle Tennysonian tears for a vanished yesteryear. These
are here and now maturing millionaires, some for the second time
around, playing the PGA Senior Tour, sports' biggest success story
in the past decade.
   ``It's a Mulligan on life, a chance for a second career at an
age when all other athletes are over the hill,'' exulted the
Australian Bruce Crampton, who made a million on the regular tour,
retired to hunt oil in Texas for eight years, then returned at age
50 to strike it rich again as a senior.
   In golf, a Mulligan is a second drive off the first tee, allowed
in friendly circles to compensate for a dismal start, but purely
illegal, even on the Senior tour where the over-50 set now competes
in a friendly way for official prize money in excess of $10 million.
   The lucre is so lucrative that last year no fewer than a dozen
seniors made more than in their regular career. At least a
half-dozen more are poised to join Crampton and seven other seniors
who already have won a million on the back nine of life.
   Here indeed is a new golden age of sport beyond the most
avaricious dreams of the actuarial tables.
   The ``Old Sarge'' Orville Moody, recently matriculated to the
millionaire class, is a splendid example of delayed golf growth.
Moody's only win in 17 years on the regular tour was the U.S. Open
in 1969. Prior to that, this part-Choctaw Indian spent l4 years in
the Army, rising to the envious rank of non-com in charge of golf
installations. Joining the seniors, he tucked a 50-inch long
putter, now affectionately known as ``the staff sergeant,'' tight
unto his sternum and began pendulum stroking putts that now
guarantee a more generous pension than the Pentagon had in mind.
   In physical contour, Moody more resembles Sgt. Snorkel in the
Beetle Bailey comic strip than your supple super jock. Senior
millionaires come in all sizes, from the well-rounded Billy Casper
and Miller Barber to lean and hungry exercise fanatics like
Crampton, a daily visitor to the physical fitness van in the
parking lot, and Gary Player, who still does 300 sit-ups a night on
the motel floor.
   But even with the choice of riding in carts, isn't it hot work
for chaps their age to be flailing away with woods and irons across
seven miles of uncooperating landscape for the better part of a
week?
   ``Playing golf is NOT hot work,'' demurs Chi Chi Rodriguez.
``Cutting sugar cane for a dollar a day, that's hot work, hotter
than my first wristwatch.''
   Chi Chi, who took up golf at 25 cents a bag as a caddy in his
native Puerto Rico, managed to match in less than 30 months at
senior play the million it took him 25 years to win on the regular
tour. ``Anything is possible in America,'' says this jovial
ambassador of the friendly, laid-back brand of golf that has made
the senior tour such a hit with the galleries and TV audiences.
   Instantly recognizable in his straw fedora, Chi Chi finds time
to chat with the fans behind the marshals' ropes, to autograph caps
and sun visors and visit with kids and old people in wheelchairs.
After sinking a 20-footer, he goes into his duelist act, wiping
imaginary blood from his putter and seemingly sheathing it like a
swordsman returning a sabre to its scabbard.
   Suddenly golf is fun again, in an age when so many younger
players come across as unsmiling, monosyllabic, computer-programmed
golfing machines, abandoning the color and drama to foreign players
like the fiery Spaniard, Seve Ballesteros, Australia's ``Great
White Shark'' Greg Norman, and Masters champion Sandy Lyle, the
slender Scot who deepened golf's mystique by revealing that his
girlfriend cured his tensions by tickling his feet.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
