<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Senior Golfers, Adv 14-1st Add,0830</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: his feet.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gary Player, the South African gold miner's son who at 50 found
a new mother lode on the fairways, is convinced that in two years
the senior tour will outshine the regular PGA circuit when enduring
idols Jack Nicklaus and Lee Trevino reach their semi-centennial.
   This Mulligan on life enabled Gene Littler to put another
million toward his hobby of collecting Rolls Royces after a bout
with cancer almost ended a great career that at age 58 is still
rolling in putts and prize money. Larry Mowry, whose ``best friend
_ V.O. and coke'' betrayed him into dissipating early promise,
joined Alcoholics Anonymous and came back with white hair and a
steadier putting hand. He's become a consistent money winner among
the seniors.
   Riding a golf cart has enabled Charles Owens, the gutsy former
paratrooper, to earn a half million in the senior game after four
operations on his right knee, mangled in a jump at Fort Bragg.
   ``They're coming back from the dead; this is the greatest thing
that ever happened in any sport,'' says Robert Trent Jones, the
82-year old golf course architect who still tees it up to test out
his creations around the globe.
   All sorts of Walter Mitty dreams are played out on the back nine
of life.
   Walt Zembriski, a New Jersey steel worker who used to tiptoe out
on skyscraper girders, is now walking on air in the top-20 senior
money list.
   Among the born-again at 50 are Ben Smith, who spent l5 years in
the auto repair business, and Earl Boles, a former mortician.
   Ralph Terry, the Yankee righthander voted most valuable player
in the 1962 World Series, smiles out from bubblegum cards and takes
the mound at old-timers games at Cooperstown. But he's just a
novice on the senior tour, not yet in the prize money class with
John Brodie, quarterback with the San Francisco 49ers for l6 years,
who turned to golf as a third career after a decade in the NBC-TV
sports booth.
   Having your intellect scrambled by the likes of Big Daddy
Lipscomb and Rosey Grier can be wonderful conditioning for golf's
hard knocks. ``I've been up by three touchdowns and forgotten to
win,'' Brodie philosophized after blowing a two-stroke lead to Chi
Chi Rodriguez at Houston in April. ``In golf you just wait until
the end and add it up.''
   Resilience of this sort enabled Bill Ezinicki, former
left-winger with the Toronto Maple Leafs, to trade in his hockey
stick for a persimmon wood and win the New England Seniors title.
   Pros getting a mite long in the tooth but shorter on drives
competed long before the PGA formalized a seniors tour in 1980. In
1937, three years after he inaugurated the Masters, Bobby Jones of
Grand Slam fame gathered some friends, including 23 Scots, eight
Englishmen, two Irishmen and only four Americans, at Augusta
National for the first PGA Seniors Championship.
   The purse totaled $2,000, which was generous in an era when Sam
Snead got $45 a month to represent the Greenbrier resort on tour
and Walter Hagen tipped his caddy his entire check for winning the
British Open, $240.
   Dwight Eisenhower promulgated golf as a sport for all ages by
installing a putting green on the White House lawn and assigning
the Secret Service to shag balls at Augusta. But senior tournament
golf took off when NBC-TV in 1978 aired the finish of the first
Legends of Golf from Onion Creek in Austin, Texas. The brainchild
of producer Fred Raphael and Jimmy Demaret, that unforgettable
blithe spirit in purple saddle oxfords and polka-dot slacks, the
Legends had going for it a $400,000 purse, a team format pairing
the best of yesteryear and a thrilling three-birdie finale by Sam
Snead.
   The popularity of the Legends, which Bob Hope dubbed ``The Prune
Juice Open,'' prompted the PGA to add other senior events that soon
attracted corporate sponsors.
   Now there are 37 stops on the Senior PGA Tour, including the
Chrysler Cup, an international competition that recently
spotlighted Argentina's 65-year-ld Roberto de Vicenzo and Ireland's
63-year-old Christy O'Connor, and the Madza Champions, which pairs
the cream of the oldsters with the best of the women pros in quest
of a $500,000 team check.
   Many other events outside the tour include a TV senior skins
game, which featured 76-year-old Snead, and a growing foreign
circuit that already stretches from Rich River, Australia, to
Narita, Japan.
   Now that a golf course is being built at Nachabino outside
Moscow, this capitalistic opiate of the aging masses is sure to
spread to Tbilisi, capital of the Soviet Republic of Georgia, where
the comrades reputedly live to 140 and beyond. In no time at all,
Pravda will be covering the first Senior Centenary Classic.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
