<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--SovietSchools-Scene Adv14   08-01 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Soviet Schools-Scene, Adv 14,0596</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Soviet Schools</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the lapel of his dark-blue school blazer, one
Moscow teen-ager wears a badge of Lenin, founder of the Soviet
Union.
   His classmate sports a button of Lennon, founder of the Beatles.
   Both are students at a school in the flatlands of southwestern
Moscow, where Yevgeny A. Yamburg is trying to encourage
wide-ranging inquiry and tolerance to help children cope with the
demands of modern Soviet society.
   In the three-story H-shaped building were Yamburg works as
principal, 1,500 pupils and 76 teachers meet six days a week in
split morning and afternoon sessions for the purpose of education.
   It is a business that Yamburg, 37, finds tremendously exciting.
   ``What we are trying to do is launch each child on an individual
trajectory for his development,'' says the Communist Party member,
himself a son of teachers. ``Children are like barrels. Some you
can fill up with just a little bit; others are bottomless. Each is
different.''
   Middle School No. 109, which sits in the middle of apartment
high-rises, is a synthesis of the traditional in Soviet education
and of the new possibilities now opening under Kremlin reforms.
   Yamburg says his is ``just an ordinary school,'' but Soviet
officials brought him to a Moscow news conference this year to talk
about changes needed in education nationwide.
   ``You can go to him with any question and get a sensible,
well-thought-out answer,'' says Tanya Litvinov, 15, a student at
Yamburg's school. ``He is open to us and to our problems.''
   One middle-aged Soviet visitor found School 109 strikingly
different from the schools he attended as a child. ``Most schools
in this country are like military barracks. This one is different,
and you see it right away.''
   As Yamburg lopes through his school's strawberry-colored halls,
children wish him good day, and he returns their greeting with a
smile.
   In one classroom, 9-year-old girls in brown uniforms and white
lace collars and boys in single-breasted blue blazers slowly repeat
as teacher Yevgenia N. Potapov introduces them to the complexities
of Russian spelling.
   Above the blackboard a red sign bearing the image of Vladimir I.
Lenin proclaims: ``Lenin is even now more alive than the living.''
   Up the stairs, a classroom of 15-year-olds openly disagree about
the role of Josef V. Stalin in the Soviet past.
   ``He had a lot to do with the industrialization and
collectivization of our country,'' says one blond-haired boy.
   ``Some consider him a criminal because he ruined our country's
economic system,'' says another.
   Yamburg relishes the debate.
   ``As someone who started life as a student of history, I feel my
chief task is to form non-conformist minds, so that children are
immune to mass manipulation,'' he tells a visiting reporter as he
puffs on a Vietnamese-made cigarette.
   The principal, with graying temples, also teaches history nine
hours a week, using recent newspaper and magazine articles because
textbooks have been outpaced by the official criticism now leveled
at Stalin.
   Yamburg also assigns his students to compare historical accounts
in Pravda, Izvestia and other Soviet newspapers and has discussed
the strengths and weaknesses of socialism and capitalism with them.
   ``We try to raise children to see all sides of the problem, then
to see the alternatives,'' Yamburg says. ``That's our ideal here.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
