<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv14   08-01 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 14,0891</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first time David Selby kissed a girl on
the stage his schoolmates teased him so relentlessly he almost quit
acting.
   That was in the ninth grade.
   ``It took me a while to get over it,'' says Selby, who stars in
the four-hour miniseries ``King of the Olympics: The Lives and
Loves of Avery Brundage.''
   While Selby temporarily gave up the theater, his faculty adviser
at the University of West Virginia suggested that he enroll in an
acting course.
   ``I took it and I've never looked back,'' he says. ``It was a
lifesaver. It gave me such an outlook.''
   Selby, who has spent a large part of his career on Broadway, is
probably best known as Richard Channing, the charming cad on the
CBS prime-time soap opera ``Falcon Crest,''
   In the new miniseries, which will be televised on the Harmony
Premiere Network in two parts between Aug. 15 and Sept. 15 on 85
stations, Selby has the title role as Avery Brundage.
   Brundage devoted more than 50 years to his dream of an Olympics
that was free of political and economic influences. He was a
controversial figure who made some enemies with his combative style
and autocratic rule as president of the International Olympic
Committee.
   He participated in the 1912 Summer Games at Stockholm, but lost
in every event to Jim Thorpe. He hoped to participate again in
1916, but the games were canceled by World War I. In 1952, Brundage
became president of the Olympics.
   The miniseries also reveals that although Brundage was married,
he kept a mistress in Europe and had two children by her.
   ``They sent me the Brundage script and we talked back and
forth,'' says Selby. ``The more I learned about Brundage the more I
admired him and his energy and the way he raised himself up from
his poor beginning. I loved his passion for the Olympics. It was
wonderful to play a man with such a strong belief.
   ``We only had four hours, so we had to strike a balance between
the Olympics and his personal life. His mistress, who's still
alive, was interviewed for the series.
   ``Brundage became an engineer and builder who put up much of the
Chicago skyline. He was a handball champion when he was 60. Doctors
kept telling him he was overworking, and he kept saying that other
doctors who had told him that were all dead.''
   The series also stars Sybil Maas as his wife, Elizabeth, Renee
Soutendijk as his mistress, Linnea Dresden, Kristoffer Tabori as
his alcoholic younger brother, Chester, Pat Starr as his mother,
Minnie, and Shelagh McLeod as his secretary, Frances Blakely. Lee
Philips directed from a screenplay by William Wood.
   Selby was born and raised in West Virginia, where his family has
a farm that has been in the family since 1660.
   ``The place was totally self-sufficient,'' he says. ``We raised
all of our own food, had a cherry and apple orchard and a little
coal mine where we got enough coal to heat the farm. An uncle on
the next farm had a dairy. My parents still live in a house in
Morgantown built with timber grown on the farm and made into lumber
in our own sawmill.''
   At the university, Selby became so consumed by acting that at
one point he quit school to go to New York. ``I had $25 in my
pocket and the first thing I did was pay $19 for a ticket to `The
Sound of Music,''' he says. ``I went back to college with my tail
between my legs.''
   After graduation, he spent eight months with the famous Barter
Theater in Abbingdon, Va., then nine months at the Cleveland
Playhouse.
   ``The Barter Theater was originally founded on the barter
system,'' he says. ``One day a girl came and traded two cats for a
ticket. I kept that calico cat for 19 years. I named her Safronia
Clandon Selby.''
   When he finally moved to New York to stay he not only began to
get parts on the stage but landed a role as a werewolf in the campy
soap opera ``Dark Shadows.''
   Selby was in such movies as ``Rich and Famous,'' ``Up the
Sandbox,'' ``Supercops,'' ``Rich Kids'' and ``Raise the Titanic.''
   ``I had been commuting to Los Angeles for years for film roles
and made the move about five years ago,'' he says. ``I needed to
change directions. I wasn't getting the right film roles. One day I
got a call from Lorimar. They needed a new character for `Flamingo
Road.' I only did a few shows and it was canceled.
   ``By then Earl Hamner was doing `Falcon Crest.' I had known him
from working on `The Waltons.' He said I was the only character to
ever kiss Mrs. Walton. Earl and I got along good. We told the same
stories. So Earl created the part of Richard Channing for me and I
joined the show in its second season.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv14   08-01 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 14,0794</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha Clarke has some tips for the audiences
watching her latest dream-like _ some would say nightmarish _
experimental theater production, ``Miracolo d'Amore.''
   ``It should be looked at the way one listens to music or the way
one would look at a symbolist or surreal painting, or interpreted
the way one might a stream-of-consciousness poem, where it is
highly imagistic and maybe metaphysical,'' says the show's creator.
   ``Miracolo d'Amore,'' which has 15 performers, played in May at
the Spoleto Festival in Charleston, S.C., then opened June 14 at
the off-Broadway Public Theater here. Most New York performances
have been sold out.
   Men wear the white costumes and tall caps of Tiepolo's
Punchinello drawings. At the beginning, women are nude and playing
a circle game denoting innocence. Their costumes make them look
like flowers, based on sketches by J.J. Grandville. There is
singing and talking, in pidgin Italian, embraces with a skeleton,
loneliness, gang rape, fighting.
   ``I meant the title (``The Miracle of Love'') ironically,'' Miss
Clarke says.
   Miss Clarke is known for experimental theater pieces, a
succession of scenes, usually around an hour in length, inspired by
art and culture, where theatergoers' ideas of what she ``meant''
vary widely.
   ``Miracolo d'Amore,'' is her least-literal, she says, and it may
be her last.
   ``I think it's a difficult piece for people,'' she says. ``They
can't come out being able to say exactly what it is. It has to be a
subjective experience for the viewer, because it is an emotional
work and it is a sad work. It's kind of a meditation on love gone
wrong.
   ``The people who don't get it at all are angered by it and
dismiss it. I think it makes them frustrated. I'm afraid I always
feel in trouble with people looking for literal or intellectual
ideas in my work.
   ``Of the people who like it, somewhere it touches a deep
emotional response in their own minds or dreams. People can be open
to it and not feel they have to understand in a literal sense.
Dreams have magic.''
   ``The Garden of Earthly Delights'' in 1984 was Miss Clarke's
interpretation of a Hieronymous Bosch painting of heaven and hell.
It had dancers flying over the audience on wires.
   ``Vienna: Lusthaus'' in 1986 showed the elegance and decadence,
in which one might see seeds of fascism, of Vienna at the turn of
the century.
   ``The Hunger Artist'' in 1987 was taken from starvation in Franz
Kafka's writings and emotional starvation of his life.
   Miss Clarke started ``Miracolo d'Amore'' a year and a half ago.
``It went in an unpredictable direction,'' she says. ``You never
know where they're going till you've gotten there. I read a lot of
Italo Calvino fairy tales, to be inhabited by Punchinellos and
these flower fairies. The stories were very dark, horrifying, funny
_ and impossible to translate to stage. I gave up on them real
quickly. And New York seemed glutted with fairy tales at the time.
   ``Then I just started working with my company in improvising
themes on primal emotions. There are elements of fairytale in it
but fractured and shattered.''
   She isn't working on another one. ``I don't want to do this any
more,'' she says. ``It's not a matter of success or failure. It's a
matter of my own growth not to stay still and repeat. I want to
explore and direct opera next. I want to get into film directing _
specific, literal stories. I'm now ready to go linear.''
   In July, she went to London to talk to Peter Hall about possibly
doing movement for a co-production planned by the Glyndebourne
Opera Festival and the Houston Grand Opera. ``It is a discussion,
not a job, at this point,'' she says.
   Miss Clarke studied modern dance at the Juilliard School, was a
member of Anna Sokolow's dance company for three years, then the
Philobolus Dance Theater from 1972 to '78. She founded her own
dance company, Crowsnest, before moving into experimental theater.
   She lives in Connecticut, divorced from sculptor Philip
Grausman. Her son, David, is 19 and studies jazz composition.
   ``Garden,'' probably her best-known work, was revived
off-Broadway in 1987. It has been on tour and will tour again next
year. ``Vienna'' will tour this fall to Spain, Portugal and France.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
