<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video Views: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hold onto your machetes, folks, and don't let
your goalie masks down. Jason's back.
   That human slice-and-dice machine who put Camp Crystal Lake on
the map will be in your video stores in seven movies that have
grossed over $172 million: The ``Friday the 13th'' series.
   Paramount Home Video will have a package this fall featuring the
first six movies in the series at a special $19.95 price. ``Friday
the 13th Part VII _ The New Blood'' will sell for $89.95 in VHS and
$29.95 in beta.
   Jason began his rampageous career quite modestly in 1980, in a
low-budget thriller created by producer-director Sean Cunningham.
Ironically, Cunningham devised the title when he was planning a
children's TV show. He thought it might work for the title of a
feature film, and ``Friday the 13th'' grossed an amazing $40
million.
   The action takes place at Camp Crystal Lake. Jason returns from
the dead, wearing a goalie mask and wielding an ax or machete to
pay back a grudge. Many years ago when he was a camper he drowned
in the lake because his inattentive counselors were making love in
the bushes. Jason's vengeance is wreaked upon the human race in
general, but he takes special delight in whacking oversexed
counselors.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Raw'' and ``For Keeps.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Raw'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS _ $89.95, Beta _ $29.95;
Rated R)
   
   ``Raw'' is the technical result of an Eddie Murphy performance
at New York's Felt Forum, and it is aptly titled. It seems that
Murphy went to the Richard Pryor school of comedy and emerged with
a doctorate in dirtyspeak.
   The video opens at a family Thanksgiving gathering in the 1960s.
After dinner, a few of the youngsters give a talent show for their
adoring parents. Eddie the child tells a scatological joke, raising
eyebrows from the grownups and providing a fast seque to 1987 and
his stage show.
   Murphy's routines are pat and almost formula by now, with
predictable swipes at women, marriage, sex, homosexuals and various
ethnic groups. Occasionally, he's funny.
   He gives a great imitation of Bill Cosby, who allegedly called
him on the phone one day to tell him that dirty words do not a
comic make. He also does good impersonations of Mr. T and Richard
Pryor.
   ``Raw,'' however, is strictly for connoisseurs of Eddie Murphy's
brash narcissism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``For Keeps'' (RCA@Columbia Pictures Home Video; VHS@Beta,
$89.95; Rated PG-13)
   
   Darcy Elliot and Stan Bobrucz are on top of the world: They're
madly in love with a sun-filled future. She's an aspiring writer
who's about to get on the college newspaper, and he's waiting for a
scholarship so he can go to Cal Tech.
   Everything is as rosy as life can be for bubbly, optimistic
teen-agers. Then Darcy becomes pregnant.
   Rather than go through with an abortion and continue chasing her
goals, Darcy (Molly Ringwald) decides to have the baby and marry
Stan (Randall Batinkoff).
   Their idea of marriage, though, is as idyllic as a TV sitcom:
neither realizes the realities, and they face financial tortures,
social snubs and a crumbling relationship.
   Darcy is not allowed to complete her senior year in high school
and must take an adult education class at night; Stan gets his
scholarship but decides to turn it down so he can work in a shoe
store and be a father. By the time the baby comes, Darcy doesn't
even want to hold it.
   In the end, all works out through some personal sacrifice and a
lot of growing up.
   Directed by John G. Alvidsen, ``For Keeps'' is surprisingly
good, escaping the silliness that usually invades movies about teen
social problems. Alvidsen is lean and focuses on the harsh
realities and the human, comic gifts that get most people through a
crisis.
   ``For Keeps'' is especially good viewing for those teen-agers
who think that having a baby _ with or without a marriage _ is a
nifty idea. They'll quickly learn what dicey really means.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
