<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--ChemicalIllness Adv04   08-01 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Chemical Illness, Adv 04,0666</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 4, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Victims Of Pollution Seek Toxic-Free Homesites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Pressinger's troubles began when
he was teaching in a portable classroom built with particle board.
   His chest hurt, he couldn't concentrate and he was depressed. He
had frequent colds and an abnormally low white-blood cell count,
indicating liver malfunction. Doctors couldn't determine a cause
for his symptoms.
   Pressinger's suffering became so intense he finally left his
girlfriend and gave up his job. He joined the Peace Corps and went
to teach in Jamaica, but had to leave after a year because the
Ministry of Education began using a strong pesticide in the
classrooms in which he taught.
   Suspecting sensitivity to chemicals, he began sleeping on a
beach to escape the smells of pesticides, disinfectants, paint, and
even perfume.
   Pressinger, 33, is one of a growing number of people who believe
they are severely allergic to chemicals, victims of environmental
illness.
   Doctors, however, can't agree on what is causing symptoms that
have led some sufferers to seek a ``toxic free environment'' by
giving up their jobs and moving to the desert or even going so far
as to seal their rooms with aluminum foil linings.
   ``Much of what is attributed to environmental factors can only
be theorized,'' says Dr. Phillip Lieberman, a Memphis, Tenn.,
clinical allergist and president of the American Academy of Allergy
and Immunology. ``So there is great controversy as to whether the
precepts of the physicians practicing environmental medicine are
valid, at this time.''
   The burden of proof ``belongs on the physicians practicing the
specialty,'' Lieberman says.
   Dr. William Rae, a cardiovascular surgeon who also specializes
in clinical ecology, says, ``Nothing is 100 percent proven. But
most of the debate occurs out of ignorance... It's a scapegoat for
not looking into it critically.''
   Rae contends that 10 percent to 20 percent of the population
suffers from such sensitivity. His clinic in Dallas says it has
treated 17,000 people for environmental illness in the past dozen
years.
   Some of them are sensitive to formaldehyde in particle board,
paneling and rugs, others to food or gasoline. Even the smell of
deodorant, vehicle exhaust, newsprint, clothes, bedding and other
everyday substances can cause reactions.
   Pressinger lives at his mother's home here, doing everything he
can to avoid contact with chemicals. He believes his only real
escape is a secluded, uninhabited island. He has checked out
properties in Florida, North Carolina and Tennessee, and now is
trying to get enough sufferers together to buy an island in the
Bahamas which is untainted by pollution.
   The island he's found is 2{ miles long and a half-mile wide
about 5 miles from Abaco Island. Its asking price is $4 million and
Pressinger says it could be subdivided for sale just to sufferers
of chemically caused illnesses.
   ``This type of arrangement would allow complete control of the
surroundings without the risk of unexpected chemical exposures.
We've got to find someplace. It's not a matter of if, but when.''
   Fred Nelson, who heads the National Foundation for the
Chemically Hypersensitive, in Wrightsville Beach, N.C., says the
group is interested in a chemical-free environment. ``We feel the
need is for an inexpensive, long-term rehabilitation oasis for the
environmentally ill and their families.''
   Pressinger also has taken his idea to the Chicago-based Human
Ecology Action League, which publishes a magazine, runs educational
campaigns about the problem and helps sufferers find treatment. Rae
is one of its directors.
   ``In the beginning, I thought I was the only one that had such
problems,'' says Pressinger. ``The initial reaction of doctors is
that it's a psychological problem. It's a complex illness that is
little understood, even by physicians.
   ``There are many people out there who have it and don't even
know it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--PrairieDogs Adv04   08-01 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Prairie Dogs, Adv 04,0638</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 4, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Researcher Says Prairie Dogs A Problem But Misunderstood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TENA HARALDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranchers say prairie dogs don't live up
to that cute-sounding name. Prairie rodents is more like it, they
grumble of the furry animals that chomp grass and booby-trap
pastures with their burrows.
   Zoologist John Hoogland admits the critters cause problems but
says they're basically misunderstood. Much of what he says flies in
the face of lore.
   ``Prairie dogs will expand unless they are controlled, said
Verne Brakke, director of regulatory services for the state
Agriculture Department.
   Not so, said Hoogland. In fact, in a behavior pattern observed
in fewer than a dozen other species, prairie dog mothers leave
their own pups unguarded to enter the burrows of female relatives
where they kill and eat the babies.
   ``The implications of this are enormous,'' he said. ``There
seems to be a system in which the prairie dogs are controlling
themselves.''
   Hoogland, of the University of Maryland, has been watching
prairie dogs in one colony in Wind Cave National Park since 1975,
and the population has stayed around 150. ``That colony has not
expanded 1 inch,'' he said.
   The killings at first went unnoticed because they occurred in
burrows, then Hoogland noticed that females visiting other burrows
would emerge with blood on their fur. The evidence was uncovered
when a burrow was excavated.
   ``Fifty-one percent of all litters are killed by infanticide,''
he said, adding that the common perpetrator is a female relative,
though in a few cases the mother turns on her own litter. Litters
average two to three pups.
   ``The leading candidate is that they are doing it for food,'' he
said. ``I have never seen them eat any other meat.
   ``Maybe in other colonies there are certain things we could do
to make the prairie dogs control themselves.''
   Ranchers won't shed tears over the deaths of prairie dog pups.
Since the 1800s, when pioneers and their cattle moved west, it's
been war.
   ``Back in the early 1900s at one point the U.S. government hired
125,000 people whose only job was to eradicate prairie dogs,''
Hoogland said.
   Those efforts continue today in states like South Dakota,
Wyoming, Montana, Nebraska and Colorado, said Brakke. Most states
have animal damage offices, but anti-prairie dog efforts are not
coordinated from state to state.
   South Dakota had 800,000 acres of prairie dog towns in 1980.
Today that is down to 250,000 to 300,000, Brakke said. No figures
are available on the amount of land infested nationwide, but
millions of acres are involved, he said.
   ``They are a rodent. We give them kind of a cute and furry
little attribute, so we call them prairie dogs. If we called them
prairie rats or prairie rodents there wouldn't be that
connotation,'' he said.
   ``I grew up with a dislike, a distaste and an aboslute hate for
prairie dogs,'' said state Agriculture Secretary Marvis Hogen.
``The bread of life in South Dakota is grass, and those little
buggers eat grass, and the second thing is they make holes that
your horse can step in and break his leg.''
   Hoogland said it's hard to find examples of that, and added,
``Everybody hates prairie dogs but almost nothing was known about
them. Ranchers say, `Look what they've done to my land,' but
there's a lot of evidence that prairie dogs move into areas that
have already been overgrazed.
   ``I'm not saying there's no competition (with livestock) but I'm
saying all the evidence isn't in yet. Two hundred years ago there
were jillions of prairie dogs and jillions of buffalo, so they
could coexist.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End of Adv for Aug. 4</HEAD>
