<HEAD>Superconductivity Race Continues At Frantic Pace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first word came in January: Hiroshi Maeda
in Tokyo had found a superconductor that broke all previous
temperature records.
   While legions of physicists struggled to duplicate Maeda's feat,
newcomers Allen Hermann and Zhengzhi Sheng at the University of
Arkansas topped it.
   A few days later, IBM scientists fiddling with the Arkansas
superconductor in San Jose, Calif., hit a high-temperature mark
that still stands.
   All the pandemonium began with the January 1986 discovery by two
IBM scientists in Switzerland that a mix of lanthanum, barium,
copper and oxygen could carry electricity with no resistance at
minus 296 degrees Fahrenheit. The discovery won K. Alex Mueller and
J. Georg Bednorz the 1987 Nobel Prize.
   Before the ``Zurich oxide,'' superconductors _ which carry
electricity with no resistance and thus no loss through heat _
worked only when colder than minus 418 degrees, about 42 degrees
above absolute zero.
   President Reagan told a conference last year, ``There are
predictions of high-speed trains levitated above their tracks,
supercomputers on a single silicon chip, cheaper and more effective
medical imaging devices.''
   The truth is,      
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
          
</TEXT>
