<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices surged higher in moderate trading
today, while the dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 288.31-point
winner during Saturday's half-day session, added 126.37 points, or
0.45 percent, for 28,326.31 points, its second-highest finish ever.
   ``Up till now, gains were retricted to one area, specifically
steel issues, but activity has now expanded to include high-tech
and real estate issues,'' said a dealer at a major securities firm.
   The gains are likely to continue, he added, speaking
anonymously. It was the sixth consecutive gain for the index, which
broke the 28,000-point level Saturday for the first time since
mid-July.
   Shortly after the start of the week's trading, the Nikkei
briefly touched 28,409.17 points, higher than its previous record
reached June 17 when it finished at 28,342.46.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at 133.23 yen
and inched up before closing at 133.25 yen.
   The currency traded in a tight but stable range of 133.09-133.42
yen during the day because of ``a lack of any market-affecting
news,'' said another dealer at a major Japanese securities firm,
who also demanded anonymity.
</TEXT>
