<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0900EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CrashComing?     08-01 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Coming?,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Tech Computer Models Say Wall Street Headed For Another
Big Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market will be ready for a major fall,
similar to the one in October, if interest rates go any higher,
according to a Georgia Institute of Technology professor.
   ``It looks in a sense like '88 may be a replay of '87 as it
relates to the stock market,'' said Fred C. Allvine, a management
professor who based his forecast on computer analyses of the
economy.
   With factories operating near capacity and unemployment at a
14-year low, ``you see the possibility of inflation breaking out
all over, the genie getting out of the bottle,'' said Allvine, who
has headed Georgia Tech's stock marketing forecasting project for
nine years.
   Four of Georgia Tech's five market computer analyses ``have
reached a negative threshold which has been associated with
ultimate downturns on the market,'' Allvine said.
   ``Last year the economy was running very strong, there were
inflationary concerns and the Fed (Federal Reserve) was compelled
to hold a steady course on liquidity, which ultimately led to the
very speculative stock market,'' he said.
   ``Our numbers on our Fed models are showing that both the
short-term and long-term (interest) rates are becoming very close
to where they were a year ago at this time,'' Allvine said.
   ``The Fed is snugging up in terms of its action to see that the
economy does not run away,'' he said. ``If this does not work and
interest rates continue to rise, there could be another crumble in
the stock market.''
   Inflation has been a major concern of the Fed, which tries to
keep the economy stable by manipulating the supply of money in
circulation.
   The gloomy analysis is based on the fact short term rates are
higher, with the federal funds rate, the interest for overnight
borrowing by banks, as high as it was on Oct. 19, the day of the
crash, Allvine said.
   The fed funds rate, which stood at 7.625 percent when the market
collapsed, was quoted at just over 7.75 percent on Friday.
   ``Other interest rates are up sharply from the beginning of the
year, and some are higher than at the time of the crash,'' Allvine
said.
   In 1987, the prime rate rose from 7.75 percent in March to 9.25
percent two weeks before the market crashed. It stands now at 9.5
percent. The Fed's discount rate, the interest rate it charges
member banks for loans, was increased from 5.5 percent to 6 percent
a month before the crash and remains at that level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
