<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BizWeekProbe     08-01 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biz Week Probe,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Printer Fires One in Biz Week Leak Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago printing company said today it had
fired one employee and suspended another after investigating
allegations its workers were leaking advance copies of Business
Week in an insider-trading scandal.
   R.R. Donnelley & Sons Co., which prints Business Week at two of
its plants, said a production worker at its Old Saybrook, Conn.,
plant had admitted furnishing advance copies of the magazine's
``Inside Wall Street'' column to a former broker with Merrill Lynch
& Co.'s New London, Conn., office.
   Merrill Lynch dismissed broker William Dillon on Thursday after
conducting an investigation into suspicious trading that appeared
linked to the Business Week articles.
   Donnelley said its investigation, in conjunction with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., also had led to the suspension of
an employee in its Torrance, Calif., plant.
   The printing firm did not identify either employee.
   Last week, the Securities and Exchange Commission subpoenaed the
names and addresses of all Donnelley's employees.
   Also last week, Prudential-Bache fired a broker, Advest Inc.
suspended one and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said as many as three
former brokers may have traded improperly on advance knowledge of
information contained in the influential Business Week column.
   Using such information to trade before it becomes publicly
available is considered a form of securities fraud under federal
law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
