<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-01 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Open Limit-Up On Hot, Dry Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures soared their permitted
daily limits at the opening today on the Chicago Board of Trade as
hot, dry weather returned to the drought-stricken Midwest.
   Wheat and oats also were sharply higher.
   After a two-week reprieve, the hostile weather has returned with
the soybean crop in the midst of its most critical growth stage,
analysts said.
   ``The next two to three weeks are going to make or bake the
soybean crop, and it looks like we're going to bake it,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with the investment firm Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Dry heat is expected to persist in the Midwest for most of this
week and that could mean another round of sharp price increases in
the crop futures markets, analysts said.
   Most contracts for future delivery of corn and soybeans opened
up their respective daily limits of 15 cents and 45 cents a bushel.
The August soybean contract, on which the limit has been removed
pending the contract's expiration later this month, was up more
than 70 cents in early trading.
   Also in early trading, wheat was 12 cents to 17 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.83 a bushel; corn
was 15 cents higher across the board with July at $3.05\ a bushel;
oats were 10 cents higher across the board with September at $2.81{
a bushel; soybeans were 45 cents to 71 cents higher with August at
$8.47 a bushel.
   Most cattle futures were sharply lower while pork futures were
sharply higher to limit-up in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .70 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August
at 66.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .42 cent to 1.27 cents
lower with August at 78.40 cents a pound; hogs were .73 cent to the
limit 1.50 cents higher with August at 45.05 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.85 cents to the limit 2 cents higher with
August at 32.52 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Friday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
