<DOCNO> AP880801-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Horne     08-01 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Horne,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Department Store Surprised By Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Horne Co. Inc. said Monday its
operations would not be affected by the collapse of an agreement
between Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. and Dillard Department Stores
Inc. to buy the department store chain.
   ``The current ownership and management of Horne's is and will
remain committed to the company's future,'' Robert A. O'Connell,
president and chief executive officer, said at a news conference.
   ``We intend to continue to operate Horne's as we have been
doing,'' he said.
   Horne officials said they were ``surprised at the abrupt
termination'' of the proposed sale of the 16-store chain to a
partnership formed by DeBartolo, of Youngstown, Ohio, and Dillard,
based in Little Rock, Ark.
   O'Connell said Horne officials learned the deal was in trouble
late Wednesday and learned it would not go through on Friday.
   On Saturday, Horne announced that DeBartolo, the largest
shopping mall developer in the country, and Dillard had withdrawn
from the deal.
   The two companies had been expected to close their purchase of
Horne's on Friday.
   O'Connell said Monday a number of Horne's employees who had been
told they would lose their jobs as a result of the sale will now be
kept on.
   Horne, whose stores are located in western Pennsylvania and
northern Ohio, employs about 3,500 people.
   Spokesmen for DeBartolo and Dillard Department Stores could not
be reached for comment.
   DeBartolo and Dillard agreed in April to buy Horne's from the
MMC Group Inc. of Pittsburgh for a price believed in excess of $200
million.
   MMC, which manages a $25 million investment fund called the
Maverick Fund I, is in the business of buying companies with money
from the fund and later selling them at a profit.
   MMC and a group of Horne's managers acquired the chain for $200
million in a December 1986 leveraged buyout after its former parent
company, Associated Dry Goods, was taken over by May Department
Stores. May is the parent company of Kaufmann's, Pittsburgh's
largest department store chain.
   After the deal with DeBartolo and Dillard was announced,
employees began receiving layoff notices in June.
   MMC officials have said Horne's is profitable, with sales of
about $270 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
