<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-KruseCars Adv06-07   08-01 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kruse Cars, Adv 06-07,0656</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 6-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kruses Cruising Along On Top of Classic Car Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When fashion designer Ralph Lauren set his
heart on a pair of racy Ferraris, he made one quick telephone call
to Indiana.
   Many of America's richest car buffs do the same.
   Displayed on the office walls of Mitchell D. Kruse, the man who
answered Lauren's phone call, are photographs of actors Ken
Kercheval and Joe Piscopo, pro football lineman Brian Bosworth,
hotelier Bill Marriott, and former senator and White House chief of
staff Howard Baker.
   In his late 20s, Kruse is president and owner of Kruse
International, one of the nation's most exotic auction houses.
Founded by his father, Dean V. Kruse, the company has come to
dominate the classic car market at a time when values have
skyrocketed.
   With the dizzying prices in the classic car arena, would-be
buyers of modest means are likely destined to remain would-be
buyers.
   ``We deal with such wealth that a guy can get excited and caught
up, and it doesn't matter that he just spent $100 for what most
other people think's worth $10,'' said Kruse.
   His figure of $100, of course, is figurative. Top models such as
Duesenbergs routinely fetch $1 million and more. The record belongs
to a 1931 Bugatti Royale Merline, which brought $6.8 million in
1986. Last year, the Kruses coaxed bids of $152 million on about
10,000 automobiles.
   The business started in 1971 at Auburn's annual weekend car
festival. Dean Kruse, a successful local auctioneer of real estate
and household goods, noticed many of the old cars carried for-sale
signs. So he stepped in and set up an auction.
   ``We had a rope as a gate, and 3,500 people paid $1 to get in,
and another 3,500 jumped the rope,'' said the younger Kruse. ``A
man turned down $35,000 for his Duesenberg, which was just unheard
of because they were selling for about $5,000 to $10,000 at the
time.''
   The auction became an annual Labor Day weekend event and sales
jumped. Their calendar takes the Kruses across the United States
and Europe, with auctions in Switzerland and Luxembourg, as well as
major sales in Reno, Nev., Atlantic City and Florida.
   ``We've really developed Florida as a market in the last couple
of years because of the incredible wealth down there,'' said Kruse.
   The Kruses claim to hold 75 percent of the market.
   Wherever they go, their sales technique doesn't vary much from
the manner that sells low-price household goods at a farm auction.
Sell the sizzle, the Kruses say, not the steak.
   ``You can have a frying pan, and go `One dollar, two dollar,
three dollar,''' said Kruse. ``Or you can say, `Oh, I can smell my
grandmother's fried chicken in there right now. Who'll gimme $20?'''
   Kruse's picks for today's best bets to become the classics of
the future include the limited edition Buick GNX, Mustang
convertibles, Corvettes, the IROC-Z Camaro, maybe the Cadillac
Allante, and the Avanti, created by Studebaker designer Raymond
Loewy and now in limited production under owner Michael Kelly.
   The keys to collectibility are condition, design, horsepower and
historical significance, Kruse said. People seem to value notoriety
more than wholesome fame.
   ``Usually if a bad guy owned it, it's worth more than if a good
guy owned it,'' he said.
   Does it seem like there are limitless numbers of Hitler staff
cars?
   Kruse says there are more than 20 of the Mercedes 770-K models,
many protected by armor plate and bulletproof glass, that might be
touted as Hitler's personal car.
   ``If (reich marshal Hermann) Goering even looked at it, it's a
Hitler car,'' Kruse said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 6-7</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC     08-01 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cartel Officials Confirm Aug. 3 Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto, one name is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries confirmed Monday that a meeting of
the cartel's price monitoring committee would be held Aug. 3 in
Lausanne, Switzerland.
   The confirmation of the date, which had been tentatively set,
came in the wake of a visit to the United Arab Emirates by OPEC
Secretary-General Subroto.
   The five-nation price monitoring committee, made up of the oil
ministers of Saudi Arabia, Nigeria, Indonesia, Algeria and
Venzuela, is empowered to study the situation on world oil markets
and can also call an extraordinary meeting of all 13 OPEC member
countries' oil ministers.
   OPEC officials hope to stabilize the cartel's price fluctuations
and runaway overproduction now that Iran and Iraq are negotiating
to end the eight-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   The last ministerial meeting, held in Vienna in June, failed to
unify the cartel on the pricing and production issues.
   The next OPEC ministerial meeting is scheduled for December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
