<HEAD>Computer Company Gets $225 Million Line Of Credit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. has established a
secured $225 million line of credit with a group of nine banks led
by Bank of America, the computer company said Monday.
   The arrangement, Control Data's first line of credit in the
United States since its financial restructuring in 1986, provides
for up to $125 million in standby letters of credit and up to $100
million of revolving credit, the company said in a prepared
statement.
   The line of credit will provide Control Data with a less
expensive and more flexible source of money for financing
day-to-day business, the company said.
   In addition to Bank of America, participating banks include the
Bank of Nova Scotia, Barclays Bank PLC, Chemical Bank, Continental
Illinois National Bank and Trust Company of Chicago, First Bank
National Association, Irving Trust Company, Morgan Guaranty Trust
Company of New York and Norwest Bank Minnesota.
   Control Data, with $3.4 billion in revenues in 1987, provides
computer products and services for science, engineering and
business applications worldwide.
</TEXT>
