<DOCNO> AP880801-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Boeing     08-01 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Boeing,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Profits Up 36.8 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher sales and lower expenses and taxes helped
boost Boeing Co.'s second-quarter profits 36.8 percent over the
same period of 1987, the Seattle-based aerospace company said today.
   Boeing reported net earnings of $160 million or $1.05 a share on
sales of $4.71 billion, compared with profits of $117 million or 75
cents a share on sales of $3.48 billion a year ago.
   For the first half of 1988, Boeing had profits of $296 million
or $1.94 a share on sales of $8.32 billion, up 26 percent from
first-half 1987 profits of $235 million or $1.51 a share on sales
of $7.24 billion.
   In a news release, Boeing chairman and chief executive officer
Frank Shrontz attributed the brighter performance to increased
sales volume; lower levels of research and development and other
new business costs for computing, electronics and military and
space programs; and lower federal tax rates.
   But Shrontz said the gains were offset somewhat by ``significant
performance problems'' on several military airplane programs;
increased research and development and production costs at Boeing's
deHavilland commuter plane division; and having to bear a larger
share of expenses on government contracts.
   Boeing enjoyed record orders of $13.3 billion for commercial
planes in the second quarter, with 23 customers ordering 268 jets
and 29 turboprop commuter planes. That compares with orders
totaling $7.6 billion for second-quarter 1987.
   For the six months ending June 30, Boeing had orders for 397
jets and 35 turboprop planes valued at $18 billion. In the same
period of 1987, there were 208 jets and 34 prop planes ordered,
worth a total $11.1 billion.
   Boeing is expected to have its fourth straight year of record
orders for commercial jets. The company, however, does not receive
payment for planes until they are delivered, which can be years
after the orders were entered.
   Military sales in the first half totaled $2.4 billion, $200
million less than in the same period of 1987. Shrontz said military
sales for 1988 are expected to be slightly less than last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Economy Bjt   08-01 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, Bjt,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Inches up 0.1 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for digest item slugged AM-Construction Spending.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending inched up 0.1 percent in
June as a big increase in investment for new factories helped
offset declines in housing and government projects, the Commerce
Department said Monday.
   Building activity rose to a seasonally adjusted, but not
inflation-adjusted, annual rate of $402.8 billion in June,
following a 0.8 percent increase in May.
   Construction spending for the first half of 1988 was only 1.3
percent above the January-June period of 1987, lagging behind the
2.0 percent rate of inflation in construction costs between the two
periods.
   Analysts had been expecting even greater weakness, predicting
office and hotel construction would decline in response to high
vacancy rates. But projects are getting built anyway.
   ``What is happening is ... there is a lot of money available,
from here and overseas,'' said economist Michael Sumichrast, who
heads a consulting firm in Washington.
   Different aspects of the same phenomenon are fueling both the
increase in factory investment, which rose 5.7 percent in June and
stands 21 percent higher than it was a year ago, and the growing
availability of money for other construction projects.
   U.S. manufacturers are spending more on new equipment and
building projects to meet higher demand for U.S. goods overseas.
They're finally benefiting from the fall in the value of the dollar
between early 1985 and the end of 1987, which made American goods
cheaper on foreign markets.
   However, although the trade deficit is not as bad as it was,
foreigners still collect more dollars than they need to buy
American goods and thus look for ways to invest that money.
   The Japanese, particularly, prefer to invest surplus dollars in
government securities and real estate, rather than in other
investments such as corporate stock.
   ``There's one good (real estate) deal for every 50 that you
bring to the table, but the money has to be put someplace. ... I'm
afraid we're going to continue to build in some areas where we
shouldn't really build,'' Sumichrast said.
   For the rest of the year, analysts are expecting a continued
softening of construction activity, led by weakness in housing,
which is being hurt by an upward creep in mortgage interest rates.
   Residential construction fell 0.9 percent in June to an annual
rate of $188.1 billion, the third decline in a row. A 0.7 percent
drop in construction of single-family homes more than offset a 2.3
percent increase in apartment construction.
   John Savacool, an economist with the Wefa Group in Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., said factory construction will likely strengthen and
residential building wane through the rest of this year.
   However, he said, if the recent appreciation in the dollar,
which has rebounded somewhat from its lows at the end of last year,
continues, it could choke off the U.S. manufacturing boom and
dampen the main area of construction strength.
   The Commerce Department offered these details of construction
spending in June:
   _Non-residential private construction climbed 2.5 percent, the
fourth consecutive monthly increase, to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of $99.2 billion.
   _Hotel and motel construction increased 19.4 percent after
falling for two months. Analysts said the category swings widely
from month to month because one or two large projects can skew the
total.
   _Construction of office buildings was off by 0.4 percent from
the May level. However, the small decline followed increases in
May, April and March, and the June rate was still 12 percent higher
than a year earlier.
   _Shopping center and other commercial construction was unchanged
from May.
   _Government construction projects fell 1.4 percent in June to an
annual rate of $78.6 billion with highway construction, the biggest
segment of the government sector, suffering a 1.6 percent decline.
</TEXT>
