<HEAD>Company Names Successor to CEO Lawrence Kitchen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. said Monday it has
selected 30-year company veteran Daniel M. Tellep to succeed
Lawrence O. Kitchen as chairman and chief executive offer when
Kitchen retires at the end of this year.
   Tellep, 56, group president of Lockheed Missiles and Space
Systems, the company's largest unit, was elected president of the
corporation to ease the transition to the top office, Lockheed
announced.
   The company's current president, Robert Fuhrman, 63, was named
vice chairman and chief operating officer.
   Tellep joined Lockheed in 1955 as principal scientist for the
X-17 missile re-entry flight experiments and has held a series of
engineering and administrative posts.
   Kitchen, who reached the mandatory retirement age of 65 earlier
this year, will remain on Lockheed's board of directors. Kitchen
became chairman and chief executive officer in 1986 after 10 years
as president and chief operating officer.
   Succeeding Tellep as president of the Sunnyvale-based Missiles
and Space Systems Group is John N. McMahon, 59, who had been
executive vice president of the group.
</TEXT>
