<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SouthAfrica-Stocks     08-01 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Stocks,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Bill Would Cost Americans $1.2 Billion, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. investors could lose $1.2 billion on their
shares in South African gold mining stocks if legislation requiring
Americans to sell all their investments in South Africa becomes
law, a report said Monday.
   The legislation introduced by Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., is
intended to bring pressure on South Africa to end its system of
apartheid, in which the black majority has no voice in national
affairs.
   Americans would lose money because the legislation would force
them to sell at depressed, ``fire sale'' prices, the study said.
The report was based on economists' models of the interaction of
supply and demand.
   The study was conducted by the Wefa Group, a consulting firm
based in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., on behalf of International Investors
Inc., a New York-based mutual fund that invests in precious metals
mining stocks and has about 40 percent of its assets in South
Africa.
   Americans owned $4.5 billion in South African mining shares as
of the end of 1987, and of that, $3.2 billion was in gold mining
shares, making it the single most popular South African investment
for Americans, the study said. International Investors estimated
that about 500,000 Americans own shares in gold mining stocks.
   The study did not attempt to calculate overall losses to
American investors if the bill became law.
   A Dellums spokesman, R.H. Miller, said the congressman believes
negative effects of the bill would be temporary because the end of
apartheid would free the South African economy from its ``state of
siege.''
   The legislation is sponsored in the Senate by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
