<2ND_LINE>AM-Sears-Brand Names,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears To Sell Brand-Name Appliances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. stores will begin offering
appliances and home electronic equipment carrying outside brand
names _ a first for the nation's largest retailer, officials said
Monday.
   Some 60 national brands, including Sears' Kenmore appliances,
will be available Thursday at 13 Indiana stores, Sears officials
said in a statement.
   Michael Bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of Sears
Merchandise Group, said the move at the Indiana stores marks a
``first step'' in Sears' plan to sell outside-brand appliances at
its stores across the nation.
   ``We will begin our national rollout early in 1989, on an
average of more than one store a day,'' Bozic said.
   The new variety of brand names will be offered at ``Brand
Central'' departments, which Sears bills as ``a superstore within a
store.''
   Free-standing Brand Central stores also are planned, promoted as
``the brands you want at the store you trust,'' Bozic said.
   Outside-brand telephones, stereo equipment, televisions,
electronic office equipment and kitchen appliances are among the
products to be offered, said Marvin Stern, a company vice president.
   ``We see this as a great opportunity to strengthen Sears'
position as America's leading appliance retailer,'' Bozic said.
   Sears now operates 819 multi-line retail stores and more than
3,000 other retail, catalog and specialty stores in all 50 states
and Puerto Rico, company officials said.
</TEXT>
