<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Gillette-Coniston 1stLd-Writethru   08-01 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gillette-Coniston, 1st Ld-Writethru,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette and Coniston Settle Suit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 11th graf to UPDATE with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Gillette Co. and Coniston Partners ended a
six-month power struggle Monday with settlement of lawsuits over
their proxy fight earlier this year.
   As part of the settlement, Gillette will buy back an estimated
16 million shares at $45 each, or a total of $720 million.
   The deal also contains a ``stand-still'' agreement, under which
Coniston said it would not buy significant numbers of Gillette
shares, participate in any proxy contest or otherwise seek control
of the company for three years.
   The settlement ends Coniston's suit stemming from the April 21
proxy vote it lost to Gillette. As a result, the personal care
products giant does not face a rerun of the election.
   A federal judge said last month he was inclined to order a new
vote because Gillette misled stockholders in an advertisement about
Coniston before the election.
   Industry analysts have said a rematch would have strengthened
Coniston's hand.
   Under terms of the settlement, all Gillette stockholders may
sell one share back to the company at $45 for each seven they own.
   Gillette officials estimated the total number of shares likely
to be purchased under the settlement agreement are about 16 million
of the approximately 112 million outstanding shares.
   Edward Froelich, an analyst with Pershing & Co., said that the
settlement means that Gillette management ``wants to keep the
status quo. But they're shrinking the capital and diluting earnings
a bit.''
   After Revlon chairman Ronald O. Perelman's failed bid for
Gillette in 1986, Gillette paid $558 million to buy back 9.2
million shares of stock. But Froelich said the company will be able
to continue to fight off such takeover attempts ``as long as they
keep the earnings rising and they have. I don't think the
stockholders will be too badly off.''
   Gillette stock plunged $2.62{ a share to $37.50 in composite
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Coniston, which owns nearly 6 percent of Gillette stock, forced
the proxy vote earlier this year in hopes of winning four
directors' seats to pressure the 12-member Gillette board to sell
the company. Coniston believes a sale would boost the value of
Gillette stock.
   Gillette filed suit April 14 seeking to block Coniston's proxy
bid on the grounds that Coniston falsified Securities and Exchange
Commission filings and di not fully disclose all investors.
   A countersuit filed by Coniston five days later alleged Gillette
misrepresented Coniston in advertisements and mailings to the
company's 27,000 shareholders and failed to publicly disclose all
companies that had expressed interest in buying Gillette.
   U.S. District Court Judge Mark L. Wolf ruled in early April that
Gillette inaccurately portrayed Coniston in newspaper
advertisements leading up to the proxy vote in which shareholders
rejected a Coniston slate of four dierctor candidates.
   Paul Tierney Jr., a Coniston general partner, issued a statement
saying: ``We believe this settlement at this time is in the best
interests of all concerned.''
   Joan Fitzgerald, spokeswoman for Gillette, maintained that ``all
shareholders will benefit'' from the repurchase agreement and said
it was not dissimilar to a buy-back plan announced by the company
for shareholders in 1986, prior to the Coniston action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
