<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished mixed Monday but
largely resisted traders' sporadic efforts to cash in on last
week's sharp gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which surged 68 points
last week, inched up 1.78 to close at 2,130.51.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 11-to-9 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
830 issues up, 672 down and 481 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 138.17 million shares,
down from 192.34 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
157.84 million shares.
   Stock prices opened mixed and seesawed in a narrow range. While
traders wondered whether last week's gains could be sustained,
analysts were divided over just how healthy the day's trading
shaped up to be.
   Some were encouraged that the market held its ground. ``The
market is holding rather tenaciously to (last week's) gain,'' noted
Michael Metz, vice president and technical analyst at Oppenheimer &
Co. ``It is absorbing profit-taking with relative ease.''
   A stronger bond market and a rise in the Dow's key
transportation sector helped support equities.
   But other observers, pointing to anemic volume and a lack of a
conviction, were not so satisfied.
   ``All last week's rally did was recover losses from the prior
week,'' said Eugene Peroni, a technical analyst at Janney
Montgomery Scott in Philadelphia. He noted that stocks moved to
``the upper end of their trading range and then ran out of
momentum.''
   Those who appeared pleased with the day's events said they would
have been far more concerned had the market's upward move resumed
at a brisk pace.
   ``What you don't want to see is instant euphoria,'' said Larry
Wachtel, first vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   A measured approach to the market could mean better things down
the road. ``That's the kind of action you get prior to a trend
resuming,'' Wachtel said.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Gillette was down 2| at
37{; the razor-blade maker reached a stand-still agreement in its
legal dispute with Coniston Partners and said it will buy back 16
million shares for $45 each.
   Boeing, which reported higher quarterly earnings, was up 1~ at
62]. Armtek jumped 4\ to 42|. Mark IV Industries, which holds 14.9
percent of Armtek, intends to offer $40-a-share for the company.
   Central & South West, the most active issue with 19.7 million
shares changing hands, was up [ at 31{. Traders were interested in
capturing the company's dividend.
   Elsewhere, IBM was up { at 126\, American Express was up 1 at
29[, and Exxon was off | at 44}.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $3.25 billion, or 0.12
percent, in value.
   The NYSE index rose 0.17 to 153.52.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 0.03 to 313.95,
while S&P's 500-stock composite index rose 0.19 to 271.21.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.53
to 306.71. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 388.00, up 0.67.
