<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NorthAmericanPhilips     08-01 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North American Philips,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NV Philips Restructures U.S. Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NV Philips, the Dutch electronics giant, Monday
named a new chief executive at North American Philips Corp. and
split off $1 billion worth of peripheral operations into an
independent subsidiary.
   Philips said the changes, which will take effect Sept. 1, were
intended to ``further integrate the Philips organization in the
U.S.A. into the global activities of the company.''
   Philips, Europe's largest electronics company and the world's
No. 1 television manufacturer, last week reported a 44 percent
decline in its second-quarter profit. It blamed foreign-currency
losses and competition from Southeast Asia.
   Named to be chairman and chief executive of New York-based North
American Philips was Gerrit Jeelof, who will continue as executive
vice president and vice chairman at the parent company, based in
Eindhoven, the Netherlands.
   Cees Bruynes, who has held the top post at North American
Philips, will become the chairman and chief executive of a new
subsidiary, Consolidated Electronics Industries Corp., Philips said.
   The new subsidiary will include the Magnavox defense contracting
business, which had to be kept independent of the Dutch-based
company because of Pentagon rules. It will also include a variety
of peripheral businesses ranging from Anchor Brush toothbrushes and
Genie garage door openers to Selmer musical instruments and
Magnavox cable television equipment.
   The creation of Consolidated Electronics Industries should not
be considered a prelude to the disposal of some of the businesses
in it, said Albert A. Ruttner, a vice president at North American
Philips.
   The operations to be included in the new subsidiary accounted
for about $1 billion of North American Philips' 1987 revenue of
$5.5 billion and about 15,500 of its 59,000 employees.
   Philips' brand names include Philips, Norelco, Magnavox, Philco
and Sylvania.
</TEXT>
