<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DefenseProbe-Consultants     08-01 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Consultants,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pryor Bill Would Require Registration of Consultants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private consultants to defense contractors
would have to register with the federal government under provisions
of a bill introduced in the Senate on Monday by Sen. David Pryor,
D-Ark.
   Pryor chairs the Senate Government Affairs federal service
subcommittee, which has held a series of hearings on the use of
consultants by Pentagon contractors.
   ``The bill is intended to shed some sunshine on the
all-too-shadowy world of consultants. Bringing everything into the
light should cut down on the shady dealings,'' said Pryor.
   He was referring to the current investigation that focuses on
allegations that contractors' consultants, many of them former
Pentagon employees, paid bribes to current Defense Department
workers for inside information about contracts. No charges have yet
been filed.
   Federal officials testified to Pryor's subcommittee that they
didn't know specifically how much was being spent on consultants.
In part, that lack of knowledge comes from the fact that contracts
don't have to detail services provided by consultants.
   Pryor's bill would create a registry of consultants and no
consultants could be hired unless they were registered. That
registration would require detailed information about the identity
of a consultant's clients along with the services provided by the
consultant.
   The bill would also detail a new category in federal budgets,
requiring government departments to list the amount they spend on
consultants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
