<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NCNB-FirstRepublicBank Bjt   08-01 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NCNB-First RepublicBank, Bjt,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Invasion, But Bringing Team From North Carolina Took Some
Planning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They prefer not to call it an invasion, but it was
a meticulously planned operation that brought about 250 NCNB Corp.
officials to Texas to take over the state's largest bank holding
company.
   With military-like precision and secrecy to match, the North
Carolina bankers set up camp at a Dallas hotel and waited for the
announcement that finally brought the failing First RepublicBank
Corp. into their fold last Friday.
   ``We were all real pleased,'' said Brad Iversen, NCBC's senior
vice president for marketing on Monday. ``There haven't been any
hitches at all.''
   The NCNB employees were flown into Dallas late Thursday and
early Friday morning, expecting a Dallas press conference that
would mark the end of First RepublicBank's Texas banking presence
and the birth of NCNB Texas National Bank.
   Rumors had circulated earlier in the week that NCNB had a lock
on a takeover and that the press conference would be a mere
formality, one local bank analyst said.
   But Iversen said Monday that he and his NCNB advance team had
heard no such rumors. When the press conference site shifted to
Washington, D.C., near-panic set in.
   ``It wasn't a done deal as far as we were concerned,'' Iversen
said. ``We were on pins and needles.''
   Iversen and others breathed a collective sigh of relief when
news came that the North Carolina bank holding company had indeed
won the bidding, conducted by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   ``We had done ads for newspapers and radio, tons of posters and
customer letters,'' he said. ``If the deal hadn't been done, we
wouldn't have been able to use that for anything but scrap paper.''
   All of the posters, letters and advertising was secretly
produced in North Carolina and then quietly shipped to Dallas on
Thursday via Federal Express.
   There was so much material that NCNB had to rent a separate
hotel room just to store it, Iversen said.
   The North Carolina delegation will stay on for short time
longer, officials said. Advance team members will be stationed at
each of the First RepublicBank offices throughout Texas.
   ``They'll be there to reassure customers,'' Iversen explained.
``Then after one week, we'll go away.''
   First RepublicBank's 40 Texas banks were turned over to NCNB on
Friday.
   The following day, First RepublicBank and IFRB Corp., its wholly
owned subsidiary and intermediate holding company formed in last
year's merger with InterFirst Corp., filed for protection from
creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   In light of the bankruptcy filings, the New York Stock Exchange
on Monday suspended trading in First RepublicBank's stock.
   First RepublicBank retains a single bank in Delaware and certain
subsidiaries engaged in non-banking activities, the bank said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NCNBProfile Bjt   08-01 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NCNB Profile, Bjt,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RepublicBank Rescue Part of NCNB's Aggressive Nature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When NCNB Corp. came to the rescue of
ailing First RepublicBank of Dallas, it was doing what came
naturally _ aggressively expanding into new markets.
   ``The single biggest strength of this company is we have a `do
business' attitude,'' NCNB vice president William P. Middlemas said
Monday. ``We try to do something with every deal that comes in.
Maybe we don't do it as it's presented, but we try to do it.
   ``It's part of our culture _ our strength,'' he added. ``We're
quite prepared to go there (Texas) and do business.''
   As he spoke, some 250 NCNB managers were in Texas taking control
of the 41 banks that made up the insolvent First RepublicBank
Corp., now operating as NCNB Texas National Bank.
   On Friday, NCNB _ currently the nation's 18th largest bank with
$28.6 billion in assets _ was selected to acquire the financially
ailing Texas bank in what has been described as the largest bank
rescue in U.S. history.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said it would spend up to $4
billion to bail out First Republic but expects to recoup a large
portion of those losses.
   North Carolina National Bank was created in 1960 when American
Commercial Bank of Charlotte and Security National Bank of
Greensboro merged.
   The new bank had $480 million in assets, 1,300 employees and 40
offices in 20 North Carolina cities and towns.
   In the next two decades, NCNB grew rapidly through mergers with
existing banks and by opening new offices. It also gained a
national reputation for aggressively pursuing new markets.
   In 1981, NCNB purchased First National Bank of Lake City, Fla.
   Federal law had barred a bank from operating in more than one
state, but the merger was approved by the Federal Reserve Board
because NCNB had owned a trust company in Florida since 1972,
before the state enacted laws prohibiting the takeover by
out-of-state companies.
   Observers say NCNB's venture into Florida sparked a five-year
buying spree that tripled it's assets to nearly $29 billion.
   Once allowed to capitalize on opportunities in other states,
NCNB bought up banks in Florida, Tennessee, Georgia and South
Carolina.
   Former NCNB Corp. President William Dougherty said the latest
move reflected the same strategy that opened the door to interstate
banking seven years earlier. ``If we hadn't been aggressively
interested in Florida, we wouldn't have ever gotten in,'' he said.
   Middlemas, who is in charge of the company's North Carolina
banking group, said the Texas deal ``is a big step in ensuring
NCNB's survival in banking circles for a long time. Size is
important.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880801-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CarterHawleyHale 1stLd-Writethru   08-01 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Carter Hawley Hale, 1st Ld-Writethru,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Department Store Company Sells Stake in Shopping Center in Santa
Clara</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd graf pvs, Carter Hawley ... to make it July 30
sted June. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The company ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc. said Monday it
has sold its interest in a California shopping center for $32
million.
   Carter Hawley, the nation's 14th-largest retailer, also said it
had established $25 million in reserves for consolidation and other
costs in its fourth quarter, which ended July 30.
   The company said the sale of its share in the Valley Faire
Shopping Center in Santa Clara, near San Jose, would result in a
$30 million fourth-quarter gain. The share was sold to Carter
Hawley's partners in the center, Ernest W. Hahn Inc. and R.H.
Macy's & Co. Inc.
   Carter Hawley operates 112 department stores under the names
Broadway-Southern California, Broadway-Southwest, Emporium Capwell,
Thalheimers and Weinstock's.
</TEXT>
