<1ST_LINE>u f AM-C&NWStrike 1sdtLd-Writethru f0190 08-01 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-C&NW Strike, 1sdt Ld - Writethru, f0190,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>C&NW Offers Compromise To Avoid Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 new grafs, ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with Simon
proposal to extend cooling off period.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago & North Western Transportation Co. issued
a compromise offer Monday in an effort to avert a strike by the
United Transportation Union that could affect 41,000 commuters and
disrupt freight deliveries in several Farm Belt states.
   Separately, Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said he planned to
introduce legislation to speedily extend a cooling-off period in
the labor dispute for 36 days, which would postpone any strike
action.
   The railroad offered to accept a recommendation by a
presidential emergency panel to eliminate 700 brakemen's jobs,
instead of the 1,150 cuts C&NW had previously said were needed.
   But United Transportation Union general counsel Robert Hart said
the union was not impressed by the offer. ``That won't settle it,''
Hart said.
   C&NW spokesman James Foote said the railroad ``made a
concessionary offer to the union to try and settle this dispute.''
   But he acknowledged the railroad is ``not very hopeful'' the
union will accept the offer to avert the strike, scheduled to begin
Thursday.
   The recommendation initially came from the Presidential
Emergency Board in July, which President Reagan appointed in April
in an effort to solve the longstanding dispute, Foote said.
   Until Monday's compromise offer, C&NW had said it wanted to save
$51 million a year by cutting most of its train crews from four to
two people, eliminating what it considers unnecessary brakemen's
jobs and leaving an engineer and conductor on board.
   The union has considered that move unacceptable.
   The presidential panel recommended that all the railroad's
freight trains be operated with three brakemen instead of four,
that only two brakemen be used on certain nonstop freight trains,
Foote said.
   The strike would affect commuters in a six-county area around
Chicago for whom C&NW provides service through an agreement with
Metra, a suburban commuter rail service. It would also affect
freight service in several Midwestern states.
   However, neither side can act until a cooling-off period ordered
by Reagan ends at 12:01 a.m. on Aug. 4.
   Hart said Monday's move by the C&NW was intended to persuade
Congress not to extend the cooling-off period.
   ``C&NW doesn't want'' the strike to be postponed, he said.
``They want it to come to a head.
   ``All the purpose of this statement is to persuade Congress not
to take any action,'' Hart said.
   But in Washington, Simon spokesman David Carle said an extension
of the cooling-off period would give both sides ``breathing room''
to come up with a solution on their own.
   He said Simon would introduce the bill under a ``fast-track''
procedure that would allow a Senate vote Tuesday, and would work
with several House members who could get it through that chamber
the next day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
