<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SteelForecast     08-01 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Steel Forecast,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Trade Association Forecasts 3 Percent Rise in Shipments for
1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipments from the steel service center
industry, which includes carbon industrial steel products and
stainless steel, should increase by 3 percent this year, a trade
association forecast said Monday.
   Such an increase would bring total U.S. shipments for the $24
billion steel service center industry to a record 23.7 million
tons, the Steel Service Center Institute said.
   `We had a record first quarter and a solid second quarter,
pushing first-half shipments 5 percent ahead of last year's record
pace,'' said Andrew G. Sharkey, president of the institute, which
represents the interests of 85 percent of the steel service center
industry.
   According to Sharkey, ``We anticipate that the third and fourth
quarters will be strong, although unable to match 1987's
exceptionally strong second half. As such, the overall gain for the
year will be about 3 percent, versus the 5 percent gain through the
first six months.''
</TEXT>
