<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 2139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Butcher-Singer     08-01 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Butcher-Singer,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Butcher & Singer Being Sold to Wheat, First Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Butcher & Singer, Philadelphia's largest
independent brokerage firm, is being acquired by Wheat, First
Securities of Richmond, Va., the two companies announced Monday.
   The terms were not disclosed.
   The merger is the culmination of talks that began two months ago
and were prompted partly by Butcher & Singer's interest in Wheat's
computer operations, said John L. McElroy Jr., chairman and chief
executive of Wheat, First Securities.
   McBee Butcher, chairman and chief executive of Butcher & Singer,
which has roots going back to the American Revolution, said both
parties would like to have the merger completed by the end of
September.
   ``I think that everyone is enthusiastic about it because it
makes you much more of a contender when you're this size,'' Butcher
said.
   Butcher also said the privately-held firm was being sold to cut
costs and to boost efficiencies. The merger will eliminate about
100 of the firm's 500 jobs in Philadelphia, he said.
   Butcher and other executives from the firm will become officers
of WFS Financial, the Richmond-based parent of Wheat, First
Securities. However, top levels of management will be filled by
Wheat executives.
   Although the headquarters will remain in Richmond, both Butcher
and Wheat will maintain separate brokerage offices and none will
close.
   Butcher said Wheat interests would own a majority of the
combined companies. He also said Johannes Fuerst von Thurn und
Taxis, a West German prince who bought one-third interest in
Butcher last December, will be a minority owner in WFS.
   Under the terms of the arrangement, the companies will form WBF
Securities Inc., a financial services and investment banking
holding company with two separate divisions. The company will have
capital of $56 million, about $15 million contributed by Butcher &
Singer. WBF will be owned by the existing WSF Financial.
   The company will have about 2,000 employees, including 750
investment brokers in 92 locations from Massachusetts to South
Carolina.
</TEXT>
